{"Author": "Chad Mc", "Date": "on November 29, 2017", "Stars": "2.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "More Cons than Pros", "Text": "Ive had it for a week now and there are things I like about it, and much more that I don't.\n\nPros:\n\n1) Works great with the Hue app as long as I'm home and connected to my WiFi network.\n\n2) Very easy to set up. Install the bulbs, set the light switches to on, plug in the hub, download the app, sync and done.\n\n3) Works with Amazon Echo Dot (some times).\n\n4) Ability to dim my lights without having to install a dimmer switch. Can set any brightness I like depending on mood or any occasion.\n\n5) Can set schedules of when to turn on and off lights based on geographical location and time zone. Cool little part of the app.\n\n6) Geofencing: Can detect when you're home or away and turn on/off lights as needed or requested.\n\nOk, now that I've gone through the good, now time for the cons. There are only a few, but to me they severely outweigh the good. The reason for home automation is so that I can control my devices effortlessly, whether I'm home or away. That isn't really so much the case with this right now.\n\nCons:\n\n1) As soon as I get out of my home network, it's a painful experience trying to connect through the app, whether on 4G or connected to another WiFi somewhere else. Even being connected through my Google account, has issues staying connected. Can't turn my lights off after I left my house, it's aggravating.\n\n2) Amazon Echo Dot skill works about 25-30% of the time. Almost always I get the response \"Philips Hue isn't responding.\" Some times it'll work after a 30 second delay, but most times when hearing that message it does nothing. Doesn't communicate directly to hub with Amazon Echo devices. Yes, that's right. It goes through Philips instead of being integrated wirelessly through your own home network.\n\nAll in all, I probably wouldn't have bought this yet if I had known all this. Would I buy it later down the road knowing these issues would be resolved, definitely yes.\n\nBut for now, I'll continue to use it at home only and continue to mutter profane words to myself under my breath every time Alexa says she can't connect to Philips Hue..."}
{"Author": "loneranger", "Date": "on November 29, 2017", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "It's great fun to turn the lights on and off in ...", "Text": "I was surprised at how little light they give off. It's great fun to turn the lights on and off in different colors with Alexa commands, and their very well suited for creating a romantic ambiance. I just can't read anything."}
{"Author": "Shirley L.", "Date": "on November 29, 2017", "Stars": "4.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Great kit to use!", "Text": "Very nice lightbulb kit to use. They brighten and dim just like you can with a built in wall dimmer. If you own an Apple device, it connects with Home-Kit flawlessly and you can simply swipe up onto the control center and turn your lightbulbs on/off or brighten and dim them. This kit was on sale for $60 at the time that I bought them and it was a great deal."}
{"Author": "Derek", "Date": "on November 29, 2017", "Stars": "2.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Very YELLOW colored light. Look at the attached picture ...", "Text": "Very YELLOW colored light. Look at the attached picture, these bulbs are as \"warm\" as they come. I wish I would have known they were this yellow beforehand. My fault. Unfortunately, I have to return these bulbs because I can't handle how drastically yellow they are. Wish I didn't have to pay more than double the price for their white ambiance bulbs, just to get a bulb that has natural \"cool\" light..."}
{"Author": "Chris Baboolal", "Date": "on November 29, 2017", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Works well with amazon echo", "Text": "You are able to change brightness and turn them on/off by using either your phone or amazon echo"}
{"Author": "William", "Date": "on November 29, 2017", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Five Stars", "Text": "great deal works perfect with alex echo n plus. Haven't figure out how to add more bulbs"}
{"Author": "Blue_Fender", "Date": "on November 29, 2017", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Simply marvelous", "Text": "This is awesome. I love being able to control my lights with just my voice. The setup was easy. Just download the app and follow directions."}
{"Author": "Matthew Smith", "Date": "on November 29, 2017", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Great Product", "Text": "So easy to use with Amazon Echo and the app IFTTT, would recommend everyone to download that app and use it with these bulbs and the bridge."}
{"Author": "Kelle Allen", "Date": "on November 29, 2017", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Awesome product, set up is cumbersome", "Text": "Once set up, app downloaded, and bulbs synced with the bridge, Alexa, and the Nest, I was satisfied. The included instructions are minimal and I had to google how to get the bridge to sync with the app. After 30 minutes of searching online, I figured out that I had to change my wifi signal to the 5g signal for the app to recognize the bridge. Smooth sailing from there but it took too much effort for such a pricey purchase to get it to work. If they would just include a tips and tricks our troubleshooting guide that would be great. Or even include in the help section in the app or link to the Philips website, that would be great. I'd still recommend this product as it truly adds convenience to your lifestyle. If you are building a smart home, this purchase is definitely worth it as it is pretty easy to set up (barring you know which wifi signal to connect your phone to) and connecting to other smart home devices and equipment is seamless."}
{"Author": "jenny", "Date": "on November 28, 2017", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Extremely impressed! 10/10", "Text": "I'm so grateful that I received these as a gift! Setup was simple, only a slight glitch but it was fixed and set up in less than 5 minutes. App is good, I like that it's pretty much just plug and play! Well worth the money for the convenience. So glad I got this instead of wasting money on the wemo switch! Homekit integration is LIFE"}
{"Author": "mike", "Date": "on November 28, 2017", "Stars": "3.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "I feel like I am back at grandmas house before they had ...", "Text": "These \"White\" lights are VERY Yellow. Be aware. SUUUUPER Yellow. I feel like I am back at grandmas house before they had better light bulb technology. When glass was blue and a man delivered your milk..."}
{"Author": "Bobby Sprinkles", "Date": "on November 28, 2017", "Stars": "4.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Can't Operate the Lights Outside of Your WiFi network", "Text": "First the Negatives:\nYou cannot control these lights from the Hue app if you're not at home. The app only works if you're within your home's wifi range. Part of the reason why I wanted these is so that I could manually turn on my lights when I'm out of town (to make it look like someone's home). But the Hue app doesn't work that way.\n\nHOWEVER, there is a work around. If you have a Google Home or Google Home Mini, you can link the lights to your Google Home app and turn them on and off from there instead. You would have to say \"Hey Google, turn on my lights\" into your phone, which might look odd to a passing stranger but it does the job.\n\nAnother annoying thing is that the hub does not connect to your internet wirelessly. You have no choice but to tether the hub within the distance of the included Ethernet cable, which is about 5 feet.\n\nOne more thing that\u2019s kind of odd and, I can\u2019t prove this, but I have a hunch that the bulbs only work with specific lamp assigned numbers on the Hue app. In other words, if you have a pack of four light bulbs, each bulb must be specifically synced to a specific lamp number on the app. For example, when I screwed in the first light bulb and assigned it to White Lamp 1 on the app, it didn\u2019t work. But then I screwed in a different bulb and it worked just fine. And the first one that didn\u2019t work initially worked perfectly once I assigned it to a different lamp number on the app. I couldn't find any markings on the bulbs and there isn't anything in the instructions that bring this up, but like I said, it\u2019s just a hunch.\n\nNow for the Positives:\n\nDespite all of the aforementioned annoyances, at the end of the day, the bulbs are fantastic!\nThey work perfectly with my Google Home Mini, and they have pretty easy dimming controls.\nI linked up two lamps in my living room through Google and now all I have to say is \u201cHey Google, turn on the Green Lamp\u201d or \u201cHey Google, turn off the floor lamp\u201d or if I want all the lights in the living room on or off I just say \u201cHey Google, turn on the living room lights\u201d\nThese are a fun way to \u201csmarten\u201d up your home and they work great with the Google Home."}
{"Author": "JD", "Date": "on November 28, 2017", "Stars": "2.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "The 3 lights that work are fantastic -- super easy to set them up with the ...", "Text": "The 3 lights that work are fantastic -- super easy to set them up with the bridge.\n\nHowever, one light constantly turns itself back on as soon as it's turned off. I guess that's a defective bulb, and from Googling around this seems like a very common problem, hence the 2 stars."}
{"Author": "D. Thakkar", "Date": "on November 28, 2017", "Stars": "4.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Very Good except for the bug with the Hue bridge that was introduced by latest update.", "Text": "The bulbs are fine but there is a bug introduced on the latest Hue bridge update. As soon as I plugged the bridge into my router with Ethernet cable, It insisted on taking over my Router's IP Address 192.168.1.1 and because of that I lost Internet Connection to all of my devices. I could not configure the bridge at all due to lack of Internet connection and the third light on the bridge kept blinking. To resolve this I had to change my Router's IP address to something else to restore Internet connectivity. After that I configured bridge to higher static IP Address and then revert my Router back to original 192.168.1.1 IP Address. It finally started working. I spent more than an hour to resolve this issue. Hope it helps someone. On a brighter note the Hue bulbs work great and I have connected Alexa to it. Other than this bridge issues I am very happy with the package. Developers at the Phillips Hue need to fix this bridge issue otherwise they will have lots of unhappy customers."}
{"Author": "Paul S. Kim", "Date": "on November 28, 2017", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "great wifi lights.", "Text": "these lights are amazing. they do take a little bit to set up but once you get it up and running, they work pretty well. i'm still working out the kinks of how to label them so that they work with my google home. as of now, i have it set up where all the lights turn on and off and that's it (it says on the box that these cost ~$1/year so that ain't bad. i bought 2 of these sets and plan on selling one of the hubs on ebay.\n\ni was thinking of getting the tplink ones but felt a hub would have been easier to control a lot of lights. i have 8 in total.\n\ncon: they are not as bright as i would like them to be. and you can't change the \"warm\" color to a \"cool\" color unless you get the ambiance ones which cost a lot more. if it were able to do that, these would be A++"}
{"Author": "Wayne Chou", "Date": "on November 27, 2017", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "It does require motion sensors and voice assistants to maximize its smart capabilities. I really enjoy playing around with it ...", "Text": "Performs well as a starter kit. It does require motion sensors and voice assistants to maximize its smart capabilities. I really enjoy playing around with it and integrating it with my other smart devices."}
{"Author": "Dylan", "Date": "on November 27, 2017", "Stars": "4.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "3 work, 1 does not", "Text": "Bought this starter kit with high hopes, which I\u2019m so far pleased\n\nExcept one of the builds light will not turn on at all, the light it self is defective, only three working bulbs is highly disappointing"}
{"Author": "Amazon Customer", "Date": "on November 27, 2017", "Stars": "3.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Everything was great until we added more bulbs", "Text": "Needs better instructions. Had to play trail and error to get everything going, and watched a few videos on YouTube. But after figuring it out, works great.\nIf it had better instructions it would have made it to 5 stars."}
{"Author": "TJP", "Date": "on November 27, 2017", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Let There Be Light!", "Text": "I started with two white bulbs and the hub, connected to my google home mini. I added four more lights and another google home mini. I have 3 lights in the living room, an accent light by the kitchen, and two lights in the bedroom. It's so easy to control them and I love the dimming function.\n\nIt took a while to connect to the mini but once I figured it out adding more lights was a breeze.\n\nI did notice my one of my Rokus was buffering too much after I installed the lights, but changing the channels on my router fixed that. It's an older Roku, I have a brand new stick and it works fine."}
{"Author": "Joshua", "Date": "on November 27, 2017", "Stars": "4.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Spendy, but good", "Text": "I figured I'd try these out, but saw them as more of a gimmick than something that we'd actually use in our house.\n\nBoy, was I wrong. We started with just this small kit with 4 bulbs (one we put in our dining room, 3 on the fan in our master bedroom), and I can't tell if I use them more or my wife does. (One day we lost power in our neighborhood and she called me pissed off because she couldn't tell Alexa to turn on/off the lights.)\n\nit's a bit on the spendy side, hence the one star deduction, but other than that they're great (and we're now running 8 bulbs instead of just the 4 we started with).\n\nPros:\n- Works fantastically well with Alexa and mobile apps\n- Allows multiple users for mobile app\n- Dimmable by voice, even if the socket isn't dimmable by default\n\nCons:\n- A bit spendy"}
{"Author": "Amazon Customer", "Date": "on November 27, 2017", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Five Stars", "Text": "Love it. Works great with Alexa."}
{"Author": "Debnzona", "Date": "on November 27, 2017", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Easy to set up and easier to use!", "Text": "Favorite product yet! Love asking Alexa to \"turn on my lights!\" So nice to say \"dim or turn off\" at bedtime too! Can't wait to try the colors!"}
{"Author": "JKByrnes", "Date": "on November 26, 2017", "Stars": "3.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Nice bulbs, nice color rendering", "Text": "A not-so-stellar app. Seems there are work-arounds, but why would that EVER be needed. Nice bulbs, nice color rendering, awful app. Crashy and not intuitive."}
{"Author": "Andrew", "Date": "on November 25, 2017", "Stars": "2.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Misleading", "Text": "Doesn\u2019t change colors like the description claims. If you want the color changing bulbs then be prepared to pay a lot more."}
{"Author": "Consumerist", "Date": "on November 25, 2017", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Versatile and with ambience", "Text": "Works with iphone, ipad mini3, & Alexa (Echo AND dot) ... love dimming to 37%"}
{"Author": "Amazon Customer", "Date": "on November 24, 2017", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Five Stars", "Text": "So far so good. Works well and easy with alexa"}
{"Author": "Rajkumar A", "Date": "on November 23, 2017", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Greatl value", "Text": "Cheap for how well it functions"}
{"Author": "Que G.", "Date": "on November 22, 2017", "Stars": "2.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Very Yellow Unflattering Light- Look into other Phillips products instead maybe", "Text": "These lights are incredibly yellow and extremely unflattering masking everything in a dull depressing light. I believe it to be an effort to drive consumers to the higher cost Phillips Hue White Ambiance lights instead. That product is around $50 more for the starter kit compared to this $99 Philips Hue White Starter Kit. I would love to exchange rather than return but not sure I can trust the White Ambiance product to be a better option."}
{"Author": "New York", "Date": "on November 22, 2017", "Stars": "4.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "great lights once you get them working with an Amazon echo", "Text": "they work great but get ready to spend a few hours getting them setup with Amazon support - of course that is assuming you are going to use them with Alexa. I was on the phone for almost 45 minutes with Amazon. Phillips and Amazon really do need to get better integrated. I know some people have know problems getting these lights to work with Amazon echo's with relative ease, but when it doesn't work you REALLY need to have plenty of time in your calendar and lots of patience. Thus the reason this got only 4 stars and not five."}
{"Author": "Heidi7", "Date": "on November 21, 2017", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "They are really good", "Text": "Easy installation. I have not experienced any problem with remote switching - it works every time.\nThe set up was a breeze. You wound't regret getting these bulbs."}
{"Author": "StevenPatterson", "Date": "on November 20, 2017", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Five Stars", "Text": "Works great with Apple HomeKit!!:)"}
{"Author": "R. Poston", "Date": "on November 20, 2017", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "One Star", "Text": "Bridge does not work"}
{"Author": "Stringbean70", "Date": "on November 19, 2017", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "AWESOME \ud83d\udc4f\ud83d\udc4f\ud83d\udc4f", "Text": "If you\u2019ve got kids, you\u2019ll love this! No more getting up and down shut the lights off after them !!!\nI LOVE IT!!"}
{"Author": "Amazon Customer", "Date": "on November 19, 2017", "Stars": "2.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Two Stars", "Text": "I have difficult to connect to Alexa thru smart home."}
{"Author": "Katie D.", "Date": "on November 18, 2017", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "The future is now", "Text": "This is the coolest thing ever! It\u2019s helping me get one step closer into turning my home into Skynet. The hub connected immediately to the lightbulbs, although it was hard to tell which bulb was \u201c1, 2, 3, or 4.\u201d The setup was easy and the app works quite intuitively. I especially like the different preset lighting options and timers; no need for loud mechanical timers now. This product is seriously cool and I hope to eventually replace all my lightbulbs with these."}
{"Author": "Daniel Miles", "Date": "on November 17, 2017", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Hub needs to be physically connected to wifi router", "Text": "Before I bought this it wasn't clear to me that the hub needs to be physically connected to the wifi router. Given the setup of my home, this means it won't work for me and it feels like a giant step back in time."}
{"Author": "Patrick Behar", "Date": "on November 17, 2017", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Very easy to", "Text": "Works perfectly. Very easy to install"}
{"Author": "Pepper", "Date": "on November 16, 2017", "Stars": "4.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Look mom no hands!", "Text": "I really like the Philips Hue with the Smart Hub because it makes my home feel like a smart home. I like the hands free way of turning the lights on just by telling my Echo Dot to turn them on. What don't like about them is they are expensive. I like them because you can set the mode in the room according to how you feel at that time hands free."}
{"Author": "Sam M", "Date": "on November 15, 2017", "Stars": "3.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Three Stars", "Text": "over priced. works ffine"}
{"Author": "CJ in Seattle", "Date": "on November 15, 2017", "Stars": "4.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Adds security while you are away from home", "Text": "I bought this starter kit just before we went on vacation. I wanted to be able to turn the lights on and off remotely using my phone so it would look like someone was home. It was easy to set up and it worked great. I don't use the phone to turn lights on and off at home. I haven't figured out how to get it to work well with a dimmer switch so I only put the bulbs in lamps that I don't dim. I plan to add one or two more lights but I'm only interested in using it as a security feature rather than an overall lighting solution."}
{"Author": "Sherri Lee", "Date": "on November 15, 2017", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "The light bulbs are awesome! When you download the Hue app you can ...", "Text": "I got the lights for my bedroom lamps with the echo dot.\nThe light bulbs are awesome! When you download the Hue app you can set them to slowly turn on at a specific time to mimic a sunrise. I use that with my morning alarm as well and it is much more peaceful getting up.\nThese lights are dimable. Just tell alexa \"\"turn on (whatever you named that bulb) at 50%\" and it does. Great for late nights or anyone who has headaches such as myself.\n\nThey are a yellowish light and do not turn any other color."}
{"Author": "JCP11", "Date": "on November 15, 2017", "Stars": "4.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Almost doesn't reach to my basement bedroom lights, but ...", "Text": "Almost doesn't reach to my basement bedroom lights, but it does just a slow connection. Otherwise it would be 5 stars."}
{"Author": "Amazon Customer", "Date": "on November 14, 2017", "Stars": "4.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "... actually don't want to publicly admit just how much fun I'm having with this system", "Text": "I actually don't want to publicly admit just how much fun I'm having with this system. It's perfect!\nOne star off because the iPhone app is really sub-par. It works, but it's clearly designed by committee. Hey Philips? Call me if you're looking for an app developer who could make this thing sing, ok? Just saying! I might even consider being payed in more light bulbs! ;)"}
{"Author": "Ajay Singh", "Date": "on November 14, 2017", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "First time setup is easy and connect to Google Home.", "Text": "Great product and easy to setup. Just keep the bulb on while you setup Hub using the Philips Hue app. Just follow the on screen instruction on App and within 10 minutes I had bulbs configured and working. Once setup is done, don't forget to create your Philips hue login, this will allow you to control it over the Internet.\nAlso I was able to connect it to Google Home pretty easily, after that I can control bulbs by voice command. For connecting Google Home/ Home Mini, use Google Home App and go to Home Control segment. Here you can find and add Philips Hue.\nWill be adding more bulbs in future as single Hub can control 50 bulbs."}
{"Author": "Omar Narvaez", "Date": "on November 14, 2017", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Five Stars", "Text": "Excelent"}
{"Author": "daniel", "Date": "on November 13, 2017", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Great product", "Text": "Awsome lights the color is amazing and the dimming is just perfect."}
{"Author": "Karl Slingsby", "Date": "on November 13, 2017", "Stars": "3.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "After initial hurdles, seem to be operating more reliably. Poor Range, though.", "Text": "The light color is good. If you don't use them with the bridge, they work well as expensive LED lights. If you use them with the Bridge, be prepared to be frustrated.\n\nI initially had the bridge setup upstairs (closest to the router) and the lights downstairs. They couldn't always reach. Several times the lights were \"unreachable\". What was funny is that two of the lights were about 15 feet apart, and one light was reachable, but the other was not! Zigbee is supposed to create a mesh network, but it was obvious this wasn't happening.\n\nWhen I moved the hub downstairs, I had better luck getting both lights to respond together. There is a slight delay between the two when adjusting them. Also I had to delete them from my Harmony setup, and re-add them after I moved the hub.\n\nNow that they seem to be operating more reliably, it's a bit more reassuring, but I wasn't blown out of the water by them."}
{"Author": "Amazon Customer", "Date": "on November 11, 2017", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Five Stars", "Text": "Excellent"}
{"Author": "Xiaowei Dziadon", "Date": "on November 11, 2017", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "The beginning to a smarter home!", "Text": "Setting up is a breeze and with just my phone, I can remotely control how or when the lights come on. Getting the extra light bulbs soon! *super love* Hopefully, the bulbs will become more affordable over time and then, we can replace most of the bulbs at home!"}
{"Author": "Cory", "Date": "on November 10, 2017", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "I installed these bulbs in the Living Room which makes it nice to be able to dim lights and control them ...", "Text": "I bought this when it was on sale during Amazon Day. I installed these bulbs in the Living Room which makes it nice to be able to dim lights and control them when I'm not home. Philips Hue is a great lighting system, and I prefer it much more than the WiFi bulbs or other ZigBee standards. The system is built to work, and keeps maintenance out of the question. Make sure you install bulbs close to the Hub, as in my testing the Hub didn't work very well at a long range passing several walls. However the more bulbs you have, the better chance you have at increasing that range."}
{"Author": "Matthew J Groveman", "Date": "on November 10, 2017", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "They're great, but we all knew that already.", "Text": "Does anyone not love these? \"Alexa do this, Alexa do that\" I barely have to move my arms anymore which is great because I'm so lazy! I've got them in my living room, bedroom and dining room. At their dimmest they give off just enough light to see and at their brightest they're just as bright as any other lights. The app has some cool features too including \"mood lighting\" where you can make them flicker like candles which is pretty cool. I'm watching for a price drop on the extra bulbs because, let's face it, they're pretty pricey but we got this as a lightning deal last year so it wasn't as bad."}
{"Author": "Amazon Customer", "Date": "on November 10, 2017", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Five Stars", "Text": "Nice gadget to be used with Alexa"}
{"Author": "Ivan Rigovsky", "Date": "on November 9, 2017", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "One Star", "Text": "When I put it on, nothing happens. The device does not work."}
{"Author": "Maxime", "Date": "on November 9, 2017", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "It took me 10 minutes and Alexa is working like a charm", "Text": "I just finished setting up the bridge, 4 white lights and 1 color light. It took me 10 minutes and Alexa is working like a charm. How do i register all of the devices for warranty purposes?"}
{"Author": "John K. Karlson", "Date": "on November 9, 2017", "Stars": "4.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Four Stars", "Text": "None"}
{"Author": "Mr Home Mechanic", "Date": "on November 8, 2017", "Stars": "4.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Excellent smart lighting option with minimal fuss", "Text": "It's my first adventure into the smart home light arena and I choose to go with Philips Hue. Sure, I have the options of either the smart switches from Lustron, Sylvania but then I have to rewire some of the wall switches and replace some of the wall plates. Although it is not hard to do that, I think it is much easier to change the light bulbs instead so I don't have to running around finding the parts to replaces the wall switches. After plugging in the Hue bridge, I found that the Hue app it easy to use and set up the bridge and the lighting I wanted. Granted, the UI interface could be better as it was not obvious how I would start creating the light groups after I connected to the Hue bridge. I only wish that the Hue bridge is Wifi enable so it does not need an Ethernet port to connect. For this kit, the bridge already come connected to the two A19 bulbs so it already know them when I put them into the light sockets. For additional light, I have to manually add them as the bridge does not automatically discover them as I plug them in. I got a Hue Bloom light for mood lighting in the family room as well as a few BR30 flood lights for both the family room and kitchen areas. I also link them to Alexa app and use my Echo to control the room lights which is great after dark as I don't have to search for the light switches on the wall. The only drawback with the Philips system is the light bulb cost, the A19 cost $12.5 each in a 4 pack, the BR30 flood light cost $25 each in a 2 pack, the color version are higher at $50-60 each like the color BR30 or the Bloom. My approach is not to replace every light bulbs since I recently changing them from CFL to LED, not need to change them out. I only replace the bulbs I want to control via the Hue app or Amazon Alexa. The Hue app also allow me to set these lights to turn on/off for waking up, going to sleep or at certain time of the day so I don't really need to use the wall switch for them. This app is also working great as security lighting at home while I am away, I don't need to set the manual timers anymore."}
{"Author": "G. Fleming", "Date": "on November 8, 2017", "Stars": "2.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Still an unreliable toy", "Text": "Philips hue system g2 remains an unreliable toy unsuited for serious applications.\n\nBulbs intermittently become \u2018unreachable\u2019 for minutes or hours and can\u2019t be controlled by the app or by Alexa, then spontaneously become reachable again. Nevertheless, some bulbs can be controlled even when they are in \u2018unreachable\u2019 state. Or not. It depends on something. Neither I not Philips support have any idea what. They replaced one hub and the new one worked for a few months. Then problems started creeping in (slowly) again until the system is now almost totally unusable."}
{"Author": "Robert Pinc", "Date": "on November 7, 2017", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Five Stars", "Text": "Super simple setup and easy to use"}
{"Author": "Anthony Armstrong", "Date": "on November 7, 2017", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Philips Hue Bridge Unit Dead", "Text": "Unplugged the Hue Bridge unit when leaving for vacation. I only did this because the system had begun randomly turning on the 2 Philips lights located in our bedroom - in the middle of the night.\n\nAfter one week, I plugged the Bridge back in and... nothing. None of the 3 blue indicators light up and neither does the 'app connection' button. Even after pressing the interior reset button on the unit, no connection to the app, no controllable lights.\n\nMy Philips Hue Smart Lighting System is pretty much worthless at this time."}
