{"Author": "Andrew Honma", "Date": "on October 26, 2017", "Stars": "3.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "If you really just want the smart hub because you were an early Hue adopter and ...", "Text": "If you really just want the smart hub because you were an early Hue adopter and still using the first gen hub, this is the most economical way of getting it. I popped the two whites in a bathroom because I don't really need color lights in there, even if it is hilarious painting the bathroom red or turning on a super fast color loop when an unsuspecting houseguest is using it.\n\nAs for ease of setting up...wow. It should not be this difficult. The hub comes pre-loaded with the two supplied bulbs. I already own 20 Hue bulbs, plus my first gen hub. Anyway, it wants to transfer your old hub settings to your new hub, but I skipped that initially because I didn't have any more free ports in my router, and figured it's probably better to just do a clean install anyway. How naive. Second hub gets online, I go into the Hue app, search for my 20 other bulbs...and it detects none of them. Even after numerous scans. It passive aggressively floats that \"search by serial number\" option. I'm thinking to myself...are you ****ing kidding me? You want me to go remove 20 bulbs and write down all those serial numbers?\n\nSo, I unplug a cable from my router and plug both hubs in. I go with the first option of transferring my settings over. It finishes without any hitches it seems. I go into the Hue app. It's got my scenes, and 20 bulbs, but not the two new white bulbs. I search for them. It doesn't find them. Again with the \"search by serial number\" suggestion. After muttering a few choice curses. I go and unscrew those two bulbs to write their serial numbers down, enter them into the app, and it finds them just fine within seconds. Whatever terrible logic is going on in the underlying algorithm...well, it's clearly pretty terrible.\n\nNow, because I've got Amazon Echos everywhere, I run into a problem that is probably more Amazon's fault than Hue's fault, but who knows. Maybe it's both their faults. The Echos/Alexa app still have info from my previous hub. Some of that info has changed since I moved some bulbs around, and renamed a few things. I use the Alexa app to scan for new devices, and I now have both all the old and new bulbs and rooms listed in Alexa (btw, totally not Hue's fault, but it's beyond stupid how Alexa doesn't differentiate between bulbs and rooms). And, for some insane reason, you can't delete devices. You have to disable them. Now, I've got copies of many devices as a bulb named \"kitchen sink\" from the old hub, and the same bulb named \"kitchen sink\" from the new hub are both now in the Alexa app. I had to go in and experiment to determine which copies Alexa actually saw and which copies had to be disabled because they were tied to the old hub.\n\nSo, what really should have been a 3-5 minute process ended up taking half an hour of bug-eyed wonder at how bad this entire process was.\n\nWhy did I bother to upgrade to the 2nd gen hub? Was it worth it? I'm not sure. I can now tell my Echos to change bulb colors without using IFTTT triggers. I can call scenes directly, rather than tying multiple light changes to the same IFTTT trigger word. Some natural commands revolving around rooms don't have any visible effect, whereas when I had my lights set up as groups to mimic rooms in Alexa...I never had that issue. That's honestly about all that's changed. Functionality hasn't really changed (if anything, it's worse); just the verbiage. Is it worth having a zillion disabled devices tugging at my OCD whenever I look in my Alexa app's 'Smart Home' screen? I don't know."}
