{"Author": "Dave", "Date": "on May 18, 2017", "Stars": "2.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Very limited range from the Hue bridge...for starters...", "Text": "Summary:\n\nIf you are going to use this product in a small house, you will likely be okay...as long as you don't expect the Hue app from the Amazon Appstore to work with it on your Fire tablet. And your bulbs are less than 25' from the bridge.\n\nHowever, another app in the Appstore , 'all 4 Hue', written by someone who appears to be an independent developer, works quite well. (BUT, you cannot update the bridge firmware with it...it says to use the native Hue app for that...which does not work with a Fire tablet...even though it is in the Amazon Appstore...)\n\nThe nitty gritty: 1. when I kept the bulbs within 25 feet or so of the bridge, they were detected and worked fine. Alexa could also detect them. The aforementioned app could detect them. (Again, the native Hue app does not even get by the 'authorize the bridge' stage.)\n2. You cannot use a wi-fi range extender with the bridge...even if your range extender has an ethernet plug. I thought I might be able to work around the bridge range limitation with a TP-Link wi-fi range extender. Nope. The bridge *must* be hard wired (no wireless extender in the config) to the router to work.\n\nI verified both issues above with Philips tech support. She apologized for the native Hue app in the Appstore not working...she verbally stated it would not work as soon as I mentioned I was using a Fire. Same with using a wireless extender with the bridge plugged into it with an ethernet cable.\n\nAfter rooting around for a bit, I found there might be a way to have this work by using multiple Hue bulbs arranged in fairly close proximity to each other to create their own 'network' if you would. I decided against this frustration. I also checked out the reviews of the app in the Google Play store and the Apple store (wish I had done that first...my own fault of course...) and saw they were less than stellar...especially in the Google Play store...the 1 star ratings far exceeded the others. Although I am usually fairly diligent in my research, I was negligent in this detail....my bad.\n\nThese were my experiences. Fortunately, I think I may have a more limited use for this product than the one I first intended...so I shall hold on to them but certainly won't build upon this system."}
{"Author": "Travis Knight", "Date": "on May 18, 2017", "Stars": "3.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Three Stars", "Text": "Does its job. Slower than I expected when responding to voice/phone commands."}
{"Author": "Taylor", "Date": "on May 17, 2017", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "The range is a joke making an otherwise good product nearly useless", "Text": "The range is a joke - the bridge is in my roommate's bedroom maybe 5-10 meters (this is supposed to have a range of 30m) from my bedroom with only doors separating us and the bridge can't hold a connection to the light bulbs. I have to have the light bulbs in the hallway only a few meters from the bridge for there to be a connection - do not buy - either the product is faulty or they are peddling refurbished models past their useful life.\n\nThe price was too good to be true because it is!"}
{"Author": "danwittek", "Date": "on May 17, 2017", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "There are better products out there for a better price.", "Text": "Horrible product. It starts with the app as it is not easy to use at all. There are no instructions on how to work with the app nor does it mention anywhere that creating an account with Phillips will give you more access to the app and products you've already purchased.\n\nThe bulbs and bridge work fine as long as you are on the same wifi as your bulbs. But if I'm on the same wifi all the time I figure it's pointless to have because I'll just get up and turn the lights on/off myself.\n\nThe widgets you can use for iOS do not work correctly or consistently. Setting your schedules for home / away for the lights to go on/off is difficult and does not work. You must also adjust your bulb brightness every time to your liking as the app does not remember your preferences. This is pointless if you're trying to use remotely.\n\nI'm extremely disappointed in the Phillips product because I don't feel they put a lot of thought into it or have made any updates to address the issues that customers have voiced their concerns about. I'll will be returning the product and purchasing something else."}
{"Author": "Amazon Customer", "Date": "on May 16, 2017", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Great for baby", "Text": "Love it. Use it in our room and the babies room so we can dim the lights at night."}
{"Author": "Mark Hegarty", "Date": "on May 16, 2017", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Works with Alexa (Echo) with ease. GREAT PRODUCT!", "Text": "Works as advertised. Great product if you are automating your home. I got this and the Echo Dot for my aging mother. The combo of voice controlled lighting and music on demand has put some pep in her step. All seniors should have this. If you love your parents, buy this for them with at least the Echo Dot."}
