{"Author": "Jeff Dell", "Date": "on May 6, 2017", "Stars": "4.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Good, but not a standalone product!", "Text": "Overview: Excellent product, if you are going to use it with Alexa. Otherwise, its too frustrating to use a phone app to control the lights.\n\nThe Good:\n* Fast and easy to setup with the Phillips Hue Mobile app for Android. Also works with the Wink app for Android.\n* Lightbulbs are of good quality and provide sufficient light for their use.\n* Works with Alexa\n\nThe Bad:\n* Unless you are using Alexa you need to use an App on your phone to turn on lighting\n* No wall switches available with Phillips system limits ability to expand beyond a few lamps.\n\nThe Phillips Hue Starter kit is a really good and inexpensive way to dip your toe into the waters of Home Lighting Automation. Overall, I really like this product and what it does, though there are some other things that really drive me crazy:\n1. The Phillips Bulbs are only worth using if you the bulbs you are replacing aren't connected to a \"room\" switch. If its easier to use the switch in the room, than to ask Alexa to turn it on, its not worth doing. For this reason, I cannot use the Hue with any lights that are attached to a wall light switch. Just not worth it for me.\n2. Using a phone app to turn on your lights is annoying. There I said it. I find it annoying. The reason I love this product is because I never actually interface with its front end app, except when I added the bulbs. Instead I use Alexa. The Phillips Hue app is actually not bad to use but... I don't want to be tied to my phone to turn on my lights.\n3. This is not a starter kit. For me to make it worthwhile, I really needed to buy an Amazon Echo Dot. This product is really incomplete without it."}
{"Author": "GrphxD_Amy", "Date": "on May 6, 2017", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "I think I need more!", "Text": "I bought this to go along with my new Echo Dot, and I liked the idea of programming my lights to come on at a certain time/brightness. I know this deal only came with 2 bulbs, but now I think I need a few more to cover the rest of the lights in the house."}
{"Author": "Sam", "Date": "on May 5, 2017", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Stellar, great with HomeKit (and Homebridge)", "Text": "This really couldn't have been easier to setup. Originally I did the normal thing where I configured it directly with HomeKit and it worked perfectly.\n\nI wanted a more advanced home setup so I used a tool called Homebridge that basically mimics HomeKit support for non-HomeKit devices. It takes a Raspberry Pi and some free software, and is mostly for nerds. I figured I may as well connect it to the Homebridge gateway just to see if it would work. Indeed it did.\n\nI'm really impressed and can second pretty much every other positive review. The cost for Hue has dropped DRAMATICALLY; it's finally completely accessible for anyone with only a small amount of money to spend on home automation. It used to be an expensive product for those with lots of disposable income. I plan to get one for my Mom's birthday because (no offense to all Moms out there) it's really so easy even Mom can do it \u2026in her sleep :)"}
