{"Author": "Just Al", "Date": "on April 5, 2017", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Home automation? Not quite ready for prime time yet.", "Text": "Bought this so that I could use Apple's Homekit to control the porch lights, as Homekit (with 4th Gen Apple TV) has the ability to create events, such as: turn lights on at sunset, turn lights off at sunrise. Neat! Or so I thought. The problem is that my front porch has 3 lights on the same circuit. The only wall switch from Phillips is battery powered, 'can be placed on the wall anywhere', (i.e. not an in wall switch) and I'm *guessing* that will only pair with a single bulb -- NOT what I need.\n\nI need in-the-wall 110v A/C switches that replace the existing in the wall switches and control an entire circuit of lights. So Apple says that Lutron Caseta dimmers ($55) were compatible with Homekit with (and \"with\" being the operative word there) the Lutron Bridge. And I've already purchased the Hue bridge, so now I need two? I suppose that I could replace all of the LED bulbs in the front porch with Phillips bulbs, but I'd kind of like to be able to control them with the wall switch sometimes, as opposed to leaving the switch on all of the time and grabbing my phone to turn them on/off manually.\n\nWhat other switches are out there that work with Homekit? Elagto Eve. (About $50). Doesn't even need a bridge. And there is the iDevices wall switch, also doesn't need a bridge (about $100 each). Both work off of WiFi?! So why buy a Hub at all? And how safe is the WiFi interface? There are several switches announced and/or coming soon that are also compatible with Homekit, but those appear to be WiFi as well. Lutron has several switches coming soon, but they'll probably require the Lutron bridge again.\n\nHere's my two cents take on all of this. Home automation isn't quite ready for prime time yet. And Phillips needs in the wall switches that replace existing 110v A/C switches. And while you're at it, how about an A/C outlet? And a device the plugs into an outlet that can be controlled by Hue? You know, for something other than Phillips lights?\n\nPhillips light bulbs are cheaper than Lutron switches, so if you want to control a lot of Phillips lights, and nothing else, Phillips Hue is a good choice for you. HOWEVER, it doesn't work reliably with Apple's Homekit. (Misses on/off events).\n\nI do have a Lutron Caseta dimmer in the house already. I bought it so that I could turn on the back porch lights from the second floor with their Pico remote -- works great. I guess I could buy the Lutron bridge ($80) and another Caseta dimmer ($55) for the front porch lights. But I've read that Lutron has compatibility problems -- will my existing switch work? And is it worth spending another $135 to turn the porch lights on at sunset and off at sunrise? (I didn't mind buying the 4th generation Apple TV, it's a big improvement over my 1st generation Apple TV).\n\nI'm disappointed that I didn't read the details about Phillips' silly and useless battery-powered wall dimmer switch before I wasted $70. Since I ordered Hue, and it works as advertised, I won't return it. But I don't currently have any use for Hue in my home."}
