{"Author": "Robert R.", "Date": "on April 4, 2017", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Not Ready for Prime Time", "Text": "Not ready for prime time.\n\nI just want to control two light bulbs near my front entrance and have them turn on at 7 p.m. to 11:00 p.m. and again at 5:00 a.m. until 7:00 a.m.\n\nThat requires setting up four \"Routines\" (tasks).\n\nThe problem is, every one worked flawlessly except the one to turn the lights off in the morning at 7:00 a.m.\n\nThey lights stayed on.\n\nI worked today with Philips over the phone (a person I could barely understand on the phone) and did a \"clean up\" with the Hue app, then rebuilt my routines (tasks).\n\nThat SEEMED to work, but then the lamp came on again on its own later that morning.\n\nUgghhhhh.\n\nSo I had already asked Philips what to do if the \"clean up\" didn't work and they told me I'd then have to do a total wipe of the Hue Bridge, and if that didn't work the Bridge was defective and they'd have to send me a new one.\n\nSo I did the wipe of the Bridge, bringing it back to how I bought it (just a week ago) and rebuilt everything from scratch. All those \"Routines.\" Again. From scratch.\n\nUgghhhhh.\n\nWe'll see if it works.\n\nWhat I can say, having used Alexa and Wemo too, is that the Hue app seems very poorly designed and thought out. You can't even tell a light to turn on at sunset or sunset for instance, so over the course of the year you will have to change this yourself. They do have an even less ready for prime time \"Sunset Timer\" at their Hue Labs site to add this feature in, but it's basically in beta and you're taking your changes.\n\nThis is really a pretty basic feature to have in something like this, and indicative of how the Hue app is really way more basic than it should be at this stage in its development.\n\nThe app is also very poorly thought out and designed, and, for instance, much of the time the screen keyboard on my iPhone is obstructing the poorly arranged features I need to get to and it's not always easy to get the keyboard off so I can get to the features I need.\n\nFrom how they named everything to how they arranged the screens and features, it's just not intuitive or even logical (at all).\n\nThis product still needs a lot of work, and again, all this just to turn on two of their light bulbs twice a day, and off twice a day.\n\nUPDATE:\n\nAfter all this hassle, Hue insisted on sending me a replacement Bridge. And I waited and waited and it never arrived.\n\nSo I called AGAIN and it was like starting the entire explanation from scratch and there was no record of the replacement Bridge order.\n\nThey finally sent me one and when it showed up it not only wouldn't work, it wouldn't get as far as the previous one did. It couldn't even find the lights that the other one had no issue finding.\n\nNOTHING I did helped the situation and I just decided that nothing is worth this, and that the only product one should buy from Philips is a Philips Sonicare, and the only reason is because every one you order will break in less than two years and you'll a new one on warranty indefinitely. Their flossers are even worse. This is a despicable company that really isn't interested in making functional products or giving customers value for their money. It's a company run by morons and whoever they've got designing their app clearly doesn't ever have to use it, as even the most basic things are poorly thought out and totally unintuitive.\n\nAvoid this product at all costs."}
