{"Author": "Kara", "Date": "on March 12, 2017", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Waking up to a bright room before the sun has risen!", "Text": "I originally bought the Philips 455386 Hue Wireless Dimming Kit with one bulb and one wall switch, thinking the bridge was overkill for my needs. I thought I did not need to operate my lights with my smartphone, and I wanted a wall switch for guests to use. Bulb and (stick-on) switch installation was five seconds of work; they arrived synced to each other and worked perfectly.\n\nAfter a few days, though, I became obsessed with the idea of waking up to a lighted room (I consistently wake up before the sun rises). I wanted a way to have my bulbs fade on in time to my alarm. I knew this was possible with the SleepCycle app, but only if I bought the bridge. I spoke to Philips customer service about it and was very satisfied with the service I received, which convinced me to buy this product: the Philips Hue White A19 Starter Kit. (Two bulbs allowed me to connect an additional lamp and to have a spare bulb.) Best decision ever. I LOVE waking up to a bright room. Even more surprising was how much I actually DO use my smartphone to operate my bulbs. Yes, the dimming wall switch from the 455386 product is also a remote and can be removed from the wall, but I often find that I'm already sitting in bed (reading, working on my laptop, etc.) when I want to dim or turn off my bulbs, which is when the smartphone operation becomes enormously convenient. Now I can't imagine living without the bridge.\n\nThe only thing I've found lacking are the Hue app's routines, since there is no way to set a criterium for smartphone location: I only want my lights to turn on at 4:45pm every day IF my smartphone is located within 400 feet of the bulbs. This algorithm is not possible with If This Then That either, since IFTTT allows for a \"Date & Time\" setting OR a \"Location\" setting but not both. I think this is a very obvious consumer desire that Philips should consider in their next Hue app update.\n\nOverall I'm very happy with this purchase and think home automation in general has great potential. I did NOT receive a discount or any other kind of marketing persuasion to write this review."}
{"Author": "Kirk", "Date": "on March 12, 2017", "Stars": "3.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Not worth the money if you plan on whole home automation", "Text": "This is not a bad product but if you are looking to do whole home automation then you will get better value for your money by going with smart switchs and normal energy efficient bulbs. The cost of additional smart bulbs makes this approach not worth the money."}
