{"Author": "WillGEB", "Date": "on February 28, 2017", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Easy to transfer from the original bridge to the new ...", "Text": "Works well with all the rest of the Hue products that I have. Easy to transfer from the original bridge to the new bridge."}
{"Author": "Desmond", "Date": "on February 28, 2017", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "These bulbs work great. I wish I had ordered the daylight instead ...", "Text": "These bulbs work great. I wish I had ordered the daylight instead of soft white and would like more daylight bulbs as options but other than that personal issue it works impressively. A must buy."}
{"Author": "Angela Johnson", "Date": "on February 28, 2017", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Amazing - Just Buy It", "Text": "LOVE, LOVE, LOVE. I can't tell you how much I love these bulbs! Yes they take a bit of time to set up and get them established in the house (you need a hub or bridge that supports them which this comes with), but once they're set up you can control them with Alexa or your smartphone. I set mine up to turn on automatically right before I get home and dim as the night progresses until they turn off when I normally go to bed. The possibilities are endless with all of the compatible apps. My father just equipped his entire home with these bulbs and can't stop showing people his \"cool\" new lights!\n\nIf you're thinking about wanting a \"smart\" home, son't wait any longer, get these bulbs!"}
{"Author": "Jonathan Ruiz", "Date": "on February 27, 2017", "Stars": "4.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Complements my Google Home / Alexa", "Text": "Bought this kit in November and the Hue Bridge died in February. Only the power light was turning on so I had to send it to Philips and get a replacement. When actually works, the Hue system is very convenient for lazy people like myself. I got so used to telling Google Home to turn on/off the lights that I really missed it when I had to send it in for a replacement. The only thing i really hate is how annoyingly bright the Hue Bridge LED light is, and there's no option to turn it off."}
{"Author": "Jenny M", "Date": "on February 27, 2017", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Expensive but if you can afford it, totally awesome.", "Text": "Alexa and I have an agreement. I set this up, and in exchange, she turns my lights on when I ask. These bulbs are set-up in two lamps. The lamps do not have dimmer switches. Yet when I ask Alexa to turn on the lamps, they can be dimmed. She can operate the lights separately or independently. They are in two lamps in the same room. I gave each lamp a name and noted that they are both in the same room. I can tell her to turn the lights on, and she does. I can tell her to turn on just the floor lamp and she will. I can tell her to turn both lights on 100% then tell her to turn the floor lamp down to 50% and she will. I can decrease and increase strength by 10%.\n\nThe lights can also be programmed independently of Alexa. I actually have them set so that they slowly turn themselves on 30 minutes before my alarm goes off. I LOVE THAT FEATURE.It makes waking up far easier. I also have them set so that they automatically start dimming about 30 minutes before I should be going to bed. It's a nice gentle reminder to go to sleep (as opposed to setting a bedtime alarm which is jarring and also wakes me up instead of putting me to sleep."}
{"Author": "Amazon Customer", "Date": "on February 26, 2017", "Stars": "4.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Took a while to connect with alexa, but it ...", "Text": "Took a while to connect with alexa, but it works well. Sometimes she does not turn on lights though. However, if I use it without Alexa, it always works."}
{"Author": "S. McHaggis", "Date": "on February 26, 2017", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Works great with Echo / Alexa. Very easy to set up.", "Text": "Works perfectly with my Amazon Echo Dot. It was very easy to set up and add lights to it. It integrated very nicely with the Alexa app and was easy to configure in that too. The lights turn on every time and are exactly the same color between the multiple bulbs. The app itself is very easy to use and easy to configure the lights. The app makes it really easy to adjust the lights warmth level and the dimming percentage. I will be adding more lights in the near future!"}
{"Author": "Amazon Customer", "Date": "on February 26, 2017", "Stars": "3.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Three Stars", "Text": "Still figuring out how to use them with the Echo."}
{"Author": "Carl jacksn", "Date": "on February 26, 2017", "Stars": "4.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Overall very goog", "Text": "Pretty easy set up and the work great. I have a wemo 2 light starter kit and one Flux bulb and for me this is the best. I was not looking for color changing or anything like that so these are fine and the price was good. So far not buggy like the wemo kit. The app is just ok, the wemo app was much better, but it is better than the Flux app."}
{"Author": "Stephanie Butenhof", "Date": "on February 25, 2017", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Wish I could put them everywhere!", "Text": "I bought this to use in my bedroom (as a modern-day Clapper of sorts!) to turn the lights off and on after I'm in bed. I originally had an Amazon Echo Dot on my bedside table, which worked perfectly with it, but I then switched it out with my Amazon Echo. This one works with it just as well, plus it has an awesome speaker. I set up scenes in the Hue app, which is clunkly at best, but once they were set up, Alexa works great with it. I can set a scene, or simply tell her to lower the lights to 25%. It very rarely doesn't respond the first time I ask it to do something, but always responds once I ask again. I assume in these cases it's something to do with the wifi going down briefly, the hub updating, or some such anomaly. Therefore, it's very reliable, and I just wish they weren't so expensive, so I could use them in every room in my house! (These white ones are much cheaper than the colored ones, but they're still more expensive than the regular Philips LED lights. For example, I recently bought 16 of the regular Philips LED lights for $40 on Amazon, and a 3-pack of these white bulbs (without the hub) runs between $50-70 on Amazon, as well.)"}
{"Author": "dave", "Date": "on February 25, 2017", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "You gotta love it baby get this setup it is a very ...", "Text": "You gotta love it baby get this setup it is a very good price the lights can get pricey but what the hell life is short.I have over 12 lights 9 are the second generation colored and getting more \" yeah that gets a little pricey when you want to add more lights especially the colored ones, but it was easy for me I am divorced \"\" I recommend this kit and just slowly add your lights if your wife don't agree \"\" peace :)"}
{"Author": "Cherith", "Date": "on February 25, 2017", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Great product", "Text": "Excellent buy. Set up was a snap."}
{"Author": "Amazon Customer", "Date": "on February 25, 2017", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Five Stars", "Text": "I love this product and I love Amazon thank you...."}
{"Author": "Albert Carcamo", "Date": "on February 25, 2017", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Works as expected! The hub requires a ethernet connection ...", "Text": "Works as expected! The hub requires a ethernet connection, making it one more device to be hooked up to your router. Works well with Apple Home as well as Siri."}
{"Author": "Sam Lemieux", "Date": "on February 24, 2017", "Stars": "3.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Disappointed", "Text": "I am giving this two stars because they do function but it says they work with Alexa and my Alexa dot takes between 5-10 seconds to communicate with the hub. I didnt expect to have to wait that long for a response from the hub. If Phillips makes an update to the communication method maybe I will add more stars. Until then i will not buy anymore of these lights.\n\nEDIT: Updating from 2 stars to 3. Found out that if i setup through Alexa by just discovering devices and not pushing the bridge button it works much quicker. Something i read about it processing through Amazon when it doesnt try to recognize the Hue scenes. With the scenes it processes through the Hue servers. Now it processes in 2-3 seconds."}
{"Author": "Tommy Burd", "Date": "on February 24, 2017", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "A great companion when used with Alexa", "Text": "We are very happy with it especially when paired with Alexa."}
{"Author": "WI Doorbell", "Date": "on February 23, 2017", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Thumbs up!", "Text": "Product as promised. Shipped promptly and received on time. Having a blast setting up a smart home. Doing pretty good considering that the house is almost 100 years old! Now if I could just get Siri and Alexa to acknowledge one another's presence. There is a chill in the air when they are both awake.\ud83d\ude09\ud83d\ude09. Wish price of Phillips Hue bulbs was a little more affordable."}
{"Author": "Michael Pobat", "Date": "on February 23, 2017", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Five Stars", "Text": "These lights are easy to use and awesome!!!! Setting up the hub is also a piece of cake...."}
{"Author": "Brad D.", "Date": "on February 23, 2017", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Good Product", "Text": "If I could, I would probably give these bulbs 4.5 stars, instead I'll give the benefit of the doubt. This starter kit was my first move into a \"smart\" home after buying Alexa, and I would recommend this set for both novices like me as well as more experienced smart home users. I will write my review for those making their first move into it though.\n\nThe kit as a whole seems to work pretty well. The set up was easy, just download an app, plug the bridge connector into an ethernet port, and pop a light bulb into any light and it works. That is the best thing about these bulbs imo, that you can use them on any source of light to get it to work. The app makes it simple to turn on and dim the lights, as well as assign groups so multiple lights can be used at once. Connecting to Alexa was pretty simple as well, so I am able to tell her to turn on the lights which I think is pretty cool.\n\nThe only reason I say 4.5 instead of 5 is that my bulbs don't always connect to the bridge, meaning I can't always control them with my phone. Normally I would say this would be a major functional problem, but I have a couple of factors that come into play. I live in an older house, so I do not have ethernet ports all over. The only one I have is located on my modem, which is in the front of my house while the room with my bulbs is in the back, so right away there's a pretty big distance in between them. On top of this, there is various plaster walls with concrete and metal, along with metal appliances like the fridge and oven directly in between the two, all which can disrupt the signal. My Alexa and roku still connect in the room, but the bulbs have been very spotty so far. I wouldn't expect smart bulbs to have as strong of connection to a network as either of those products, but it has come into play for me. If you think you are in a similar situation, you may want to consider the adaptability of your home. In short, I'm having connectivity issues, but I believe it is because of a variety of factors and would not prohibit me from buying this product.\n\nIt is pretty clear in the description, but this is a starter kit because you need the bridge connector for the bulbs. Once you purchase one of these, you will not need to buy another starter kit and instead will just need to buy additional bulbs at a reduced rate. While $60 seems like a lot to pay for 2 light bulbs, you're pretty much paying for the novelty of a smart home. I've been told that bulbs like these last over 20 years, so it's not like they'll burn out quickly. I compared this brand to another, and it seems like Philips really knows what they're doing, so I'd be comfortable buying from them.\n\nAll in all, I would buy this product again even with the issue I'm having. I will likely buy additional bulbs (and put them in different rooms) if that says anything."}
{"Author": "Julie Garman", "Date": "on February 23, 2017", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Love it", "Text": "I absolutely love my new Phillips lighting system. I bought three more bulbs after this to expand my system. Aside from just being fun, it's a great thing to have for people like me who have very weak hands and trouble gripping the little knobs on the light fixtures. Plus, I can have lights come on downstairs BEFORE I walk down the stairs, making it safer. The starter kit had been suggested to me and it's one of my best purchases in the last year."}
{"Author": "MikeCap", "Date": "on February 22, 2017", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Love them!", "Text": "This was the first item I added to Alexa. It's really cool but be warned... it's addicting! I've started replacing all the other bulbs in my house. The hue system works really well. I also tried a wifi outlet from another manufacturer and it has some glitches. The hue system uses a radio hub and it seems to work quite well compared to any other system. It's great for scheduling lamps and you don't have to mess with setting up a timer when you go on vacation. Tons of possibilities with this system!"}
