{"Author": "vanessa cruz", "Date": "on February 20, 2017", "Stars": "3.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Echo yes, Siri no", "Text": "Not sure what exactly to rate this since it's integration and performance is reliant on apps and not the product itself. It does work, however I had to remove stars for this reason. The Philip's hue app that is meant to utilize these bulbs with is atrocious! After an extended period of time trying to get it to work manually, I kept getting error messages. It looked like it should've worked so I took a shot in the dark and commanded Siri to turn on living room lamp, and while she claimed she couldn't do that, she actually did. And my ligh went on. I was happy it was working but still confused. Commanded off, same thing. Commanded to turn on at 50% and sane. All worked Altho Siri claimed otherwise. Later on I tried commanding her again but for the life of me it just wasn't working. Tried again manually and still nothing. Very frustrating.\n\nThen I tried with my echo, and while the Alexa app was lagging and dragging and taking forever to find my hue, it eventually did and that was the end of that. It's worked perfectly since through commanding Alexa.\n\nI feel bad for anyone who purchased this without Alexa because they just paid a ton for regular lightbulbs and a paper weight. I would be furious. Especially since more people own iPhones rather than echo's, there's bound to be quite a few \"less than ecstatic\" customers.\n\nI also feel it's quite unnecessarily expensive, but once you get the starter kit out the way, adding extra bulbs isn't too hard on the wallet, but for the price, it should absolutely work seamlessly since it's not intended specifically for the echo. Otherwise I do like it and it's very convenient to have. I will be buying more bulbs but I strongly suggest immediate fixes to the hue app!"}
{"Author": "Tommy Boy", "Date": "on February 20, 2017", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Works great!", "Text": "Works great with Google Home and Android application"}
