{"Author": "Amazon Customer", "Date": "on January 28, 2017", "Stars": "2.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Great product, but only when it works right (which is rare)", "Text": "I bought these lights to work with my Amazon Echo Dot to control the lights in my room. I have 4 lights in my room and created one group for them called 'the lights'. When I attempt to turn on or off the lights, more times than not I find at least one of the bulbs doesn't respond and I often have to repeat the command or manually turn off the light, defeating the purpose of this product. The same goes for if I wish to dim the lights, a lot of the time only a certain amount of lights will dim.\n\nThe other downside is the response time can vary from being instant, to taking 10+ seconds, which can be annoying when you're entering a dark room. I find that calling on individual lights will generally get a faster response than calling on groups of lights, as the system will only turn on the lights after 'giving up' on searching for an unresponsive light.\n\nThere are many occasions where you give Alexa a command regarding the lights which she acknowledges with an 'OK', but still the command isn't carried through."}
{"Author": "LW Seligman", "Date": "on January 28, 2017", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Five Stars", "Text": "Great way to start home AI. Works great with Google Home"}
{"Author": "Lorraine McNair", "Date": "on January 28, 2017", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Five Stars", "Text": "love it"}
{"Author": "Paul Korm", "Date": "on January 28, 2017", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Waste of Money", "Text": "Waste of money. Go buy a regular bulb. The bulbs constantly lose connections to the network. When that happens, Alexa is totally confused. I've reset the Hue Router over and over, added bulbs to the network again and again. This product is an expensive fraud."}
{"Author": "Scott Miller", "Date": "on January 28, 2017", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Five Stars", "Text": "Works great with my Echo Dot."}
{"Author": "Potter O.", "Date": "on January 28, 2017", "Stars": "2.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Configuration not for the faint of heart", "Text": "I finally got this to work with Amazon Echo but it was a nightmare. No, strike that, it would have to improve some to get up to disaster status. The documentation is non-existent. I went to the Hue website and it has no inforamtion about setup, no support button, no contact information for tech support and even there no hint that a wired connection was needed.\n\nNowhere could I see any way to configure the bridge for wireless. It would only work when plugged in to the network by ethernet cable. Once connected and the Hue app downloaded to my cell phone I could turn the lights on and off using that app. Even so, the 2 bulbs were names \"Hue Lamp 1\" and \"Hue Lamp 2\". While the name does not matter in the Hue app since you are clicking a button, saying \"Alexa turn on Hue Lamp1\" is a bit much. No hint on the Hue app about renaming. Stubborness lead to pressing the italic i for information. Still no noticce on screen that this wasn't just information but allowed name editing. BTW if you change name after getting Alexa to discover, you have to re-discover.\n\nAlexa had no clue. Googling the question I found that the balance of the confugration included enabling a new skill in the Alexa app. Then off to the Alexa control panel but you have to know that the Hue lamps are in Smart Home Skills."}
{"Author": "VICTOR M. DIAZ", "Date": "on January 28, 2017", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Five Stars", "Text": "Excellent thanks!"}
