{"Author": "Nick Ferri", "Date": "on January 25, 2017", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Excellent Smart Home light system", "Text": "I purchased this along with a three light color starter kit. The kit arrived on time in a no-hassle box, which was of a solid construction cardboard supporting the bulbs with a compartment for the Bridge and instruction booklet.\nInstalling the light bulbs was a learning curve. After downloading the Hue app, I plugged the bulbs in and turned them on expecting the app to auto-populate with the lights. They did not initially connect. I had to unscrew the bulbs and input the bulb serial numbers into the app before they would connect to the Bridge. Once connected, the app was easy to navigate, change the light names, add rooms, etc.\nI have had the light kit for about two months and have since connected them to my Echo Dot. The voice commands work well for the white lights, but to an extent. Even though the lights are white in color, you can change them to have a blue or yellow tint to mimic the outside world. You can change the dim percentage, turn them on or off, and blink them with the IFTT app, but you can not set a scene with a voice command. That could be an Echo issue, or it could be a combination of the Echo and the Hue.\n\nI would definitely recommend it for a smart home purchase.\n\nPro: Solid, heavy lights fit the majority of household sockets.\nFun and easy to use once installed.\nEcho integration is very easy.\n\nCon: The Bridge comes with a short (roughly 2ft) Ethernet cord and must be plugged into a router or the wall for operation.\nI wish the Echo voice commands could work to set the scenes as well as basic operations.\nAll the lights dropped their connection to the Bridge once since installation. A Bridge reset was required to reconnect everything."}
