{"Author": "Robert Lassiter Jr", "Date": "on January 3, 2017", "Stars": "3.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Can Not Rename Devices", "Text": "Just got it and noticed that you can not name the devices yourself. What good is technology supposedly for YOUR HOME when the very first security threat is that all of its accessories are \"pre-named\" which means that EVERYONE HAS THE SAME NAME? Break into house A and use the same device names you did at home or when you break into house B. Not very savvy on the security front."}
{"Author": "so9966", "Date": "on January 3, 2017", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Five Stars", "Text": "Haven't hooked it up yet but its what i wanted"}
{"Author": "Jenn", "Date": "on January 3, 2017", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Best way to control lights", "Text": "I love these - I wanted to turn on/off my lights remotely and be able to control them from a smart assistant like Alexa or Google Home.\n\nWhat is best about these lights is the sheer amount of integrations they have - that's what makes these better than another brand. You can use them with Google Home, Amazon Alexa, Logitech Harmony, Smartthings, or even with Google Wifi/OnHub (in any browser, you can permit even guests to type in on.here and control certain smart devices). I own all of the above except Smartthings, and it works seamlessly.\n\nIt also has IFTTT integration, which makes it basically compatible with anything. If you have a IFTTT-connected router, you can make it so every time your phone comes back on wifi (aka you arrive home), certain lights come on. If your Fitbit senses you're awake, turn lights on.\n\nI like the smart bulbs better than smart outlet plugs for lighting, as these can dim and turn on a little slower. They also work better/with more things than TP Link or WeMo.\n\nSome people like the color changing ones - but really it seems like a gimmick. The lights aren't as bright when in color, and when are you really going to make your lights green?\n\nI will say, sometimes the app can very infrequently be unreliable, but this is my top pick for smart lighting."}
