{"Author": "Amazon Hulk", "Date": "on January 1, 2017", "Stars": "3.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Bulbs great but app management is bad", "Text": "Bulbs work great and easy to connect to my WiFi. However, the app is really not easy to use to schedule different rules based on location (away from home, schedules, etc.).\n\n99% of functionality has to be configured on your mobile device. You can connect to the bridge via a web browser but all you can really do on your computer is turn things on and off. You cannot create rules/routines/schedules, etc. This may be a deal breaker for future purchases for me."}
{"Author": "Amazon Customer", "Date": "on January 1, 2017", "Stars": "4.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Gift with a Echo Dot", "Text": "THis was a gift and they are working."}
{"Author": "RobotWare", "Date": "on January 1, 2017", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Works with Siri and Alexa easily", "Text": "Perfect.. Brand new and fast shipping, set up is easy and simple to use.\nIt took me about 10 minutes from the time I took it all out of box to complete setup. The entire family can use Alexa or Siri to control lights on/off/dim.\nTo help Alexa avoid confusion, using multiple lights give them separate names and create groups for Rooms to turn on/off all in those areas.\nHope this helps if needed"}
{"Author": "Robert", "Date": "on January 1, 2017", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Five Stars", "Text": "Everything I thought it would be"}
{"Author": "Kindle Customer", "Date": "on January 1, 2017", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "So far so good. I only received these yesterday and i am ...", "Text": "So far so good. I only received these yesterday and i am still playing around with all the settings. I do have to say that i love being able to ask siri to turn my lights on. Maybe one I will get an amazon echo and ask Alexia to do it for me too!"}
{"Author": "Jeff", "Date": "on January 1, 2017", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Five Stars", "Text": "Bought to convert all of my standard led bulbs. Works with an app and Alexa"}
{"Author": "sqpyle", "Date": "on December 31, 2016", "Stars": "4.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Four Stars", "Text": "Good product. A bit temperamental during set up... but it works well"}
{"Author": "Nate Wind", "Date": "on December 31, 2016", "Stars": "4.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Does what it should great, but a bit over-priced and range is a bit lacking...", "Text": "The bulbs are high quality, well-designed, and adequately bright. The wake-up and sleep timers work great and Amazon Echo integration is seamless. However, I've got the Hue bridge one floor below and occasionally the bulbs will not respond even on a clean channel. I'm sure this could be remedied with an additional bulb between the existing bulbs and the Hue bridge.\n\nPersonally not a fan of the usage of Zigbee Light Link over Home Automation, but what can you do? At $15 a bulb for plain white, these are one of the more pricey bulbs on the market, but lights are just one thing you don't want to troubleshoot when you get home after a long day's work. Honestly the LIFX or Osram bulbs will run you a bit cheaper, but if you don't mind the extra device (Hue bridge) in your setup, this is the way to go."}
{"Author": "LFB", "Date": "on December 31, 2016", "Stars": "4.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "be sure to get philips hue bulbs if adding to this", "Text": "pretty much necessary if you're going to use Alexa/Echo to control your household lights. be careful though, A19 is just the shape of the bulb. the two bulbs included are network ready. to add more bulbs, you need to get specific bulbs that are also network ready, not just A19. i had to call the manufacturer to get the part numbers, which i found at home depot. look for Philips Hue bulbs. I paid about $14 apiece for them."}
{"Author": "Amazon Customer", "Date": "on December 30, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Extremely easy set-up", "Text": "This is my favorite Christmas present. My fiance got this for me (per my request) this year and I don't think he had any idea what he was getting himself into because I am constantly playing with the lights. The set up was really easy. I bought two more bulbs because I have a lot of fixtures that require more than one bulb. The additional lights were easy to add to the hub. I love dimming the lifts and turning them on and off with my phone! I am constantly messing with the settings, trying to get the best lighting possible."}
{"Author": "Tinny Yu", "Date": "on December 30, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Five Stars", "Text": "Very convenient when pair with Amazon Echo (Alexa)"}
{"Author": "Tim B.", "Date": "on December 30, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Great Product.", "Text": "Just got it today and love it. It was easy to sync with my Echo. Still learning the options it has but it seems very simple to understand. Cant wait to add more bulbs and plugs."}
{"Author": "D. Graf", "Date": "on December 30, 2016", "Stars": "4.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Hue system rocks, but these bulbs are too yellow and dim", "Text": "The hue system is awesome, but these bulbs have a nasty yellow color (way too \"warm\"). If you're going to do it right, get the $30 bulbs that allow you to adjust the color temperature as well. The bulbs are also not that bright."}
{"Author": "Amazon Customer", "Date": "on December 30, 2016", "Stars": "3.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "No wifi to set this up.", "Text": "My only issue with this product is that the Bridge has to be connected to wireless router in order for this device to work correctly. it think these guys need to learn from others (e.g., Belkin) to do everything through wifi."}
{"Author": "Delmar T. Neeley", "Date": "on December 30, 2016", "Stars": "2.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "cannot get Alexa to control these either!", "Text": "these supposedly work with Alexa but I cannot get her to control them... she tells me that function doesn't work with bedroom! so we have to use our phones to do the lights... I bought these to replace the Belkin Wemo's I bought to go with Alexa, and they don't work with her either... Amazon says this after I bought them with Alexa preorder! now Phillips don't work either! So, 200$ into this bedroom lighting debacle, and still no Alexa/Dot control!"}
{"Author": "Paul D.", "Date": "on December 30, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Phenomenal Home Automation Product", "Text": "I bought these Phillips Hue Bulbs to work with my All-New Echo Dot (2nd Generation) - White, and they go together perfectly. I've always found the Philips 464503 Hue White and Color A19 LED Bulb, 3rd Generation with Richer Colors for IOS and Android to be a bit pricy (although I'll still buy some), but the white bulbs are similarly priced to other LED bulbs. Now that I have the bridge (which was very easy to setup by following the instructions on the Hue app), I'd like to expand the use of them in my house. Asking Alexa to turn off lights in a particular room is incredibly convenient and very easy to set up. Furthermore, you can dim these lights to specific percentages, allowing you to illuminate the room as much as you find necessary. Because of the ease of use with Alexa, I have not utilized the Hue Routines to their full potential, but their are lots of options available within the app. You can program the lights to dim as you fall asleep, brighten as you wake up, or turn on and off at certain times when you are away from home. Overall I'm very happy with this purchase and plan to use these bulbs in an increasing capacity in my home."}
{"Author": "jerry moon", "Date": "on December 30, 2016", "Stars": "4.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Works well", "Text": "Package arrived on time and intact. Works as expected."}
{"Author": "Valerie", "Date": "on December 30, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "This is amazing. ALexa turn off lights", "Text": "This is amazing. ALexa turn off lights. Alexa turn of lights. If you wanna spoke your friends and tell them the house is haunted you can dim and turn it on or off with your phone. you can even say alexa lights 30%. and it'll dim. I was alittle worried about my light bill would go up bc the light is always on but bulbs turned off but it hasn't."}
{"Author": "Magical-ringo", "Date": "on December 29, 2016", "Stars": "2.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "It is a great concept, but setting up Philips Hue was a ...", "Text": "It is a great concept, but setting up Philips Hue was a nightmare!\n\nThe app downloaded via Amazon Fire Tablet did not work at all (it could not detect the bridge). Then, I somehow found the setup screen within Alexa app and tried to set it up in the program -- yet I could only make one of the two light bulbs work. Frustrated, I read the manufacturer's instructions again, researched web for solutions, change the light bulb location (thinking that it might have been placed in the wifi dead zone), etc. After wasting so much time on it, I called Philips tech support. The tech admitted that the Amazon version of Hue app did not work (if they knew that the app was completely USELESS, why didn't they remove it from the app store??? ) and advised me to use iPhone app instead. After the iPhone download, I was able to set up everything in both Apple app and Alexa app in minutes...\n\nI love the product, but I sure did not appreciate the setup experience -- Philips needs to do a better job."}
{"Author": "J. Horne", "Date": "on December 29, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "More useful than I thought.", "Text": "Better than I expected. I thought that it was pretty silly to automate my lights through my phone and with my echo network. I gave it a try though and I like the Phillips hue a lot. I'll be getting more. I only have 4 hue lights now. The bulbs and network component seem rock solid."}
{"Author": "Oh That Gigi", "Date": "on December 29, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Great Alternative for Older Homes", "Text": "Who knew a couple of adults could have so much fun playing with the lights? My home is 70+ years old and the lighting situation is interesting -- one switch turns on a set of lights so it's either really bright or dark, no switches are paired with outlets so you can't use them to turn on a lamp, etc. Rewiring a house is expensive, so decided to pick up the Hue starter set and it was a game changer.\n\nSet up took an entire two minutes, and the Hue app is incredibly user friendly. The dimming capability alone was enough to make me jump for joy - no more dinners in a room lit like a fast food restaurant, and I don't have to replace my too-bright reading lamp for a dimming version. I also like the ability to control each lightbulb separately within the same room, especially for that pesky switch in our house that turns on multiple fixtures.\n\nMore bulbs are in my future! So happy I bought these."}
{"Author": "rick901", "Date": "on December 29, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "The best! Get these...NOW!", "Text": "Love these! Being able to control your lights through echo or siri or your phone is just \"cool\". The functionality is great as well if you are carrying grocers or items down the step, simply say \"Alexa turn on lights\" and you are zipped into the future and your lights turn on. $15/bulb after you buy this it can get expensive, but if you h ave a smart home these are a must have. Amazon has 3 bulbs for $40 which is a great deal but they are out of stock for 1 or 2 months which is a bummer. Overall would definitely recommend!"}
