{"Author": "Christopher Blachowicz", "Date": "on December 27, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Great lights", "Text": "These are great. They respond to commands quickly if not instantly. No lag time. I have 5 of them. Three ceiling lights, one table lamp, and one closet light. All controlled with my Amazon Echo. Color is a warm white similar to an incandescent bulb. I love the dimming function which also can be controlled by an Echo. Great product."}
{"Author": "bookworm", "Date": "on December 27, 2016", "Stars": "4.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Try, Try Again", "Text": "I saw some of the other reviews after I made my purchase and was immediately wishing I had made a different selection. But I decided to see this through. Still, I was more than a little skeptical as I opened my starter kit and went through the set-up process with my brand new Echo and a companion Dot. So if you just want the short version, I will say that while the set-up wasn't a walk in the park, it wasn't climbing Mount Everest either. If you want the \"gory details,\" perhaps hoping to discover a few helpful hints, here's the longer version of what took place after I installed one of the Philip's bulbs in my bedroom and the other one in the living room:\nAfter 5 or 6 failed attempts for Echo (sitting in my living room) to recognize my Hue Bridge (about 15 feet away in the next room), I moved the Bridge about 8 inches, moving it from sitting on top of my router at the back of the desk to the middle of the desk. As I tried Echo's \"discover devices\" process yet again, instead of pressing the big button on the Bridge just once I decided to press it several times, even decided to hold it down for about 10 seconds. One of these random, meaningless acts apparently made all the difference and this time Alexa proudly announced that she had discovered my Hue Lights! In fact, she discovered twelve, although I only have two!! I have no idea where the other 10 came from, except to say that they appear to be \"bright\" or \"dimmed\" versions of the two I had installed. Getting Alexa to actually turn them on and off was another whole learning process, however. To spare you the hour or two of frustration, suffice it to say that I successfully named the lights in My Hue account, which made little difference to Alexa. She repeatedly told me she couldn't find anything under those names. Eventually I also learned that I didn't need to say, \"Alexa, open Hue\"--to which she consistently replied that she was having trouble with skills and recommended that I try again later. Apparently, I only needed to say, \"Alexa, turn on ____ lights\" or \"Alexa, turn off ___ lights.\" This nugget of information was cleverly included as an example of Alexa's abilities, clearly hidden in plain sight in the helpful paperwork that came with Alexa. I only needed to take heed of it. However, the real key was the divine revelation that it was also necessary to create groups for my lights in the Alexa app on my phone. Apparently this applies even if I only wanted one light in the \"group.\" So I created a group for the Bedroom and a second group for the Living Room, voiced the request, \"Alexa, turn on living room lights,\" and presto, SUCCESS!! But when I tried this in the bedroom, no such success.I must admit it was a little puzzling why Alexa politely declined to turn on the bedroom light when using the Dot we had set up for my wife in the bedroom, but I knew now that there must be a way. If she could do it in the living room, I felt certain she could master the same task in the bedroom. Another divine inspiration led me to create the same groups in the Alexa app on my wife's phone, and then at long last, COMPLETE SUCCESS!! Issue the instruction to either Echo or Dot and the lights go on or off as requested. After I rest up a bit, I might even try to add several more bulbs in some other rooms of the house."}
{"Author": "Queendawn", "Date": "on December 27, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "We live in an old house that doesn't have dedicated ...", "Text": "We live in an old house that doesn't have dedicated light switches. We use it with Alexa and are loving the ability to turn on/off lights."}
