{"Author": "Barb Smith", "Date": "on December 27, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Easy to set up and use", "Text": "Easy to set up and use. Works with the included bridge connected to your home wifi and an app on your smartphone or tablet. Push a button on the bridge to connect to your wifi then enter the password on the app. Use the app on your smartphone or tablet to control the lights, or use voice commands with Alexa (Amazon Echo). Very reliable either way."}
{"Author": "Bill M.", "Date": "on December 27, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Why didn't I order this earlier", "Text": "Very easy to set up and woks perfectly with My new Echo. I am going out now to purchase additional bulbs."}
{"Author": "TJL", "Date": "on December 27, 2016", "Stars": "2.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Severe Flaws", "Text": "Promising, but has some huge flaws:\n\n1. Semi-incompatible with third party hardware. Hue uses ZigBee, which in theory makes it compatible with non-Hue stuff. However, this doesn't work so well. If you use anything other than Hue products (which are generally more expensive), you will find those products often go offline or become non-responsive. Other Zigbee-based hubs (Smarthings, for example) have no problem with third party stuff. Either Phillips is trying force you to buy their stuff (evil), or they aren't as good as other manufacturers (incompetent).\n\n2. App sucks. Every time the app updates it wants me to go upstairs an push the button on my hub. Why? Why can't the damn thing just update? And the app seems to be getting worse with each update. In the latest version it will no longer allow me to rename lights. I'm stuck with \"Dimmable Bulb #1\" - which makes it almost impossible to use with Alexa or Google Home.\n\n3. Expensive. As previously stated, Phillips stuff is the most expensive. I thought I'd be getting what I paid for - I was wrong.\n\nAvoid Phillips Hue."}
{"Author": "Gaurav Arora", "Date": "on December 27, 2016", "Stars": "3.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Connectivity issues.", "Text": "Bulbs disconnect from Network from time-to-time. I have to switch them off and back on, in order to connect them again."}
{"Author": "MusicLover", "Date": "on December 27, 2016", "Stars": "2.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Too much work to set up", "Text": "Received as a gift. Extremely minimal instructions included with the kit. It felt like a hassle to connect the hub, download an app and then try to link to Alexa. Setting up the groups for rooms is annoying. The biggest gripe so far - I am unable to turn off/on the lights while not on my wifi (such as vacation, not at home etc). So basically all this work to avoid a light switch?!? I can probably set up a timer or just use the light switch with much less frustration and time. Perhaps this will get easier..."}
{"Author": "Ranger Phil", "Date": "on December 26, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Convenient, good quality lights", "Text": "These are bitchin! We have a house built in the 1940s that as we make improvements for energy efficiency I'm also trying to introduce some automation. We've converted to almost all LED lighting, super insulated the attic, installed a modern HVAC system, a solar PV system and so on, so this is a minor but fun and useful improvement.\nThe problem for us though is that we don't have that many fixtures that just use a standard socket anymore. I sure hope that Philips makes some hue bulbs that will work in track light (GU 10) fittings and with the small screw in sockets used in some chandeliers, as well as bulbs used in today's ceiling fans. Then we could have some exquisite light control throughout the house.\nI'm not sure how I paired the included hub with my Alexa devices (tap and dot) but it worked after a few minutes. I've got my lights on a sunset-late evening and an early morning schedule, but it's pretty danged convenient to just ask Alexa to light the living room during storms when there's poor natural light. I can also control the lights from the Hue app on my iphone.\n\nGiven the cost, I'm not sure if these will ever pan out as a true money saver for us, but the increase efficiency is worth a small extra cost, and LEDs are a darn sight better than the CFLs that I've replaced."}
{"Author": "mia", "Date": "on December 26, 2016", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "One Star", "Text": "Out lamps are so antique they wouldn't work. Maybe something to do with three way switches."}
{"Author": "LEO. G", "Date": "on December 26, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "YES! works flawlessly. love it", "Text": "awesome awesome awesome"}
{"Author": "Amazon Customer", "Date": "on December 26, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "... for a couple of weeks but so far so good. They are bright and work excellent with Alexa ...", "Text": "Only been using for a couple of weeks but so far so good. They are bright and work excellent with Alexa and Smartthings... love being able to adjust the brightness just I want it as needed."}
{"Author": "William", "Date": "on December 26, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Simple, works and useful!!", "Text": "This is simply as easy as it gets. Order the kit, download the HUE Application, set up the bridge and bulbs and your in business. I have the Echo and two Dots so I walk around the house and speak to turn on the lights as I come and go. Love this technology.\nIt may seem like a toy, but you quickly get used to having the ability to turn on and off the lights without walking to them. Great when you are ready for bed and the lamp is a bit of a reach, or you have a couple of lights out of reach. (Also if your significant other is already asleep).\nWith the application you can check to see of the lights are out or on as you wish from anywhere you can use the application on your phone."}
{"Author": "Alundy", "Date": "on December 26, 2016", "Stars": "3.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Only one light works will update after replacement received.", "Text": "First let's be clear you must hard wire to your router to the hub so you must have a router close enough to your light location that it will eventually control.\n\nAlso it seems that the hub must be on the same network as your echo. Probably this is intuitive but was not for me. The easiest hub to use was a network that my echo was not using because it is a slower network. I had to change networks. The faster network is in the basement and could cause connection issues.\n\nOnce the echo dot found the lights it named them, hopefully I can change the name somehow later to something easier and shorter\nProblem is one of the lights will turn off but not on. I swapped it into different lamps and no matter where it goes it will turn off via voice but not on. Once I tell it to turn on, and it stays out I can turn the on off switch on the lamp to off and back on and it will light back up. But once I turn it off via voice it will not come back on. The other light works perfectly.\nSo based on other reviews which document pretty clearly the lack of hue support from Phillips when there is a problem I will be returning to Amazon for replacement.\n\nOn a second note perhaps if Phillips gets enough of these back they will see it is more beneficial to handle customer issues more efficuently. It is a great idea and I don't care so much one was bad. Anyone can have a bad product now and then. What matters to me is how they are handled. It's why I like Amazon so much.\n\nWill update when I get the replacement. Btw I did not download the app on my iPhone and use it. I got these just for use with my dot. I will try that before I return to see if the App works in case someone want them just to use with their phone. But if it won't work with Alexa it is no good for me."}
{"Author": "G Lewis", "Date": "on December 26, 2016", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Not Worth the headache", "Text": "I was able to establish a connection with Alexa to turn on two lights but only one time. Once the connection was lost, it was impossible to reestablish and I tried everything! I redid the entire setup process , rebooted my router, had Alexa \"forget\" the product and reinstall but nothing worked. The hue bridge was recognized but not the lamps as they were constantly shown to be offline. I had to return the product.\nI think it's a great concept but has some bugs to be worked out by Phillips."}
{"Author": "Amazon Customer", "Date": "on December 26, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Well worth it!!", "Text": "Great job Philips. I know there are other cheaper products but this was seamless and didn't require me to purchase anything else. Love it."}
{"Author": "Jmom", "Date": "on December 26, 2016", "Stars": "4.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Four Stars", "Text": "I use it with Alexa and I love it. Except I wish they sell brighter light bulbs."}
{"Author": "Amazon Customer", "Date": "on December 26, 2016", "Stars": "3.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "gateway requires wired connection to router", "Text": "I don't like that the gate way has to hard wire into the router. The Osram lightify lights do not require a wired gate way, their gate way can just plug into an unused outlet anywhere in the house. The bulbs work great but offer no differences over other less expenses smart bulbs. This kit will work directly with alexa (amazon echo) without the need of another smart hubs like smartthings or similar, but if your going to expand your smart devices throughout your house your going to need a smart hub anyway. The smart hubs require hard wire to routers also so with this setup that takes up two ports on a router alone. not to mention three power cords (router, hub, gateway) requiring power at in the same area. Bulky plugs as well so takes up a great deal of space on a power supply or surge protector."}
{"Author": "Bruce a. Brown", "Date": "on December 25, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Happy with Hue", "Text": "Necessary system to bridge Hue with Echo, very easy to use. Now have 12 lights and 1 strip, all but the two with the starter kit are color lights and are in four groups or can be controlled individually. Every time you add a new light and ask to detect the new light, a simple press on the bridge button helps Echo detect the lights."}
{"Author": "CHRIS SEXTON", "Date": "on December 25, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Easily set up", "Text": "Easily set up, once you have the lights named in a group, easy to identify, BEST PART, can be used w/ multiple Alexa Devices... ordering more light bulbs, going to simply have to remember names for them all! Super Easy, much better than other Alexa lighting choices, TRY IT!"}
