{"Author": "Snowbird", "Date": "on December 24, 2016", "Stars": "4.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Okay, but not consistent in operation like the TP Link outlets are", "Text": "When I purchased my Amazon Echo, I learned that Alexa has deals each day that have significant discounts. One of these deals was for the Phillips Hue starter kit and bridge, and how could I resist? It seems once you get an Alexa product, a whole new world of home automation opens up. The bridge is easy to install, it must be attached to your wifi router to work, and the bulbs are dimmable and recognizable immediately in the Alexa app. There have been a few times in the last month since I purchased them where Alexa told me that the light wasn't able to connect at the moment, and I have no idea why, but after a few minutes pass, eventually they do come on or off. That's why I'm taking off a star, that and the price as compared to other manufacturers of bulbs, and outlets, like TP Link.\nI have found that while I like these, I prefer to have the lamps automated by TP Link outlets, and I prefer using their app to set up recipes for when I want them on and off or the IFFT app is good for that, too. I've never had a problem of the TP Link outlets not connecting or turning my lamps on or off like the Phillips hue seems to have.\nI would have never paid the full price to get the Hue Starter kit, but it's okay when discounted. I highly recommend the TP link outlets over these. And download the IFFT app to create your own recipes. I like the TP link app Kasa, as well.\nI hope they figure out how to make these bulbs or the bridge act more consistently."}
