{"Author": "Hammer", "Date": "on December 17, 2016", "Stars": "3.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "This is a good, not great product", "Text": "I been using Philips Hue lights for several months now. I have a few of the \u201cstandard\u201d LEDs that replace 60W incandescent bulbs, and several BR32 programmable white LEDs that go into ceiling cans. My conclusion is that Hue falls short in some critical areas and that most people will be just as happy with good soft-white LEDs that work with old-school light switches. Here\u2019s why:\n\nThe LEDs themselves: The Hue LEDs make fine light \u2013brighter than the incandescent bulbs they replace, in warm tones and using far less energy. That\u2019s great, but that is no different than any number of LEDs you can buy for far less money. You are paying a big premium for the connected features, and that is where things fall off fast with Hue. They also don\u2019t seem to have the ability to maintain a setting. So if you like a certain \u201cscene\u201d (color and brightness in Hue-speak) for your lights, it would be nice if you could set to that scene and have that scene active when you turn on the lights using your old fashioned wall switches. That doesn\u2019t work with Hue and you can\u2019t change the default. They will always turn on to the factory default with your wall switch, and if you\u2019re like most people, you probably don\u2019t want to have to reach for your iPhone every time you want to turn on a light. Philips solution for this is that you replace your wall switches with their proprietary switches at $30 a copy.\n\nThe Hue Bridge: The Hue Bridge is the central controller for the lights. It uses Zigbee (radio) to connect to the lights. Philips made a few big mistakes with this. First, they did not make the Hub a WiFi client. Had they done that, you\u2019d be able to put the bridge anywhere there was power to get maximum coverage to reach all the lights in your home (which is critical). But instead you have to have a wired connection, which for many people means direct connection to your home router which may not be in an optimal location in your home for coverage, or using a wired jack which you may not have available. That matters because if the bridge can\u2019t reach an LED to turn it on at a scheduled time, that LED just doesn\u2019t turn on (or off) because the signaling mechanism they use does not confirm that the action actually had an effect. The Hue Bridge simply sends the signal once at the appointed time and if the LED is out of reach because of interference (ZigBee uses 2.4GHz band where there is tons of interference), weak signal etc. too bad \u2013that light won\u2019t change. If your lights are distributed between floors, or you have some in outside fixtures, you\u2019re bound to run into this. Philips suggests you buy another bridge to solve this (which is a running theme for them).\n\nThe App: The app delivers decent functionality for the basics like tuning lights on and off, dimming, changing colors, etc. But there are certain things that are really weak. Foremost among the Cons is scheduling your lights which Hue calls \u201cRoutines\u201d. The interface for this is crazy-making. First off, you can\u2019t just create a simple schedule like in one place to turn your outside lights on and off for example. You create one routine to turn the lights ON, and a second routine to turn the lights OFF. Why? How about I just select the days of the week and say turn on at 6:00PM and off at 6:00AM? Why make me do it twice? I have four sets of lights that I want on a schedule. That means eight routines. The routines interface also requires too many clicks and is not intuitive \u2013it\u2019s grey and white on black and if you select a day of the week you turn it grey (from black) and grey typically means not active these days so you\u2019ll wonder if you did it right (Philips should be ripping off the Nest app interface). Then there are the obvious missing features like scheduling based on sunrise/sunset. It would be easy to just enter your zip code into your bridge and have it determine when to turn lights on or off based on when the sun was rising or setting in your area. But Philips wants does not offer that. They do offer a light/motion sensor you can buy to tell when the sun goes up or down (just like they had in the 1970s).\n\nFinally, your Hue LEDs won\u2019t like conventional dimmers. Philips wants to sell you their proprietary dimmers.\n\nMy conclusion is the system is not worth it for normal lighting applications. I\u2019ll continue using it to schedule outdoor lights and a few lights when I\u2019m away, but that\u2019s it. I\u2019m buying inexpensive LEDs for everything else with no regret."}
{"Author": "Grayson Roberts", "Date": "on December 17, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "A breeze.", "Text": "I love this so much! The set up was so easy and connecting it to Alexa was a breeze. I have replaced all the bulbs in the house and have even set up groups to control different parts of the house. No if only training the family to not turn off the light switches was as easy."}
{"Author": "s.pauley", "Date": "on December 17, 2016", "Stars": "2.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "too much to install", "Text": "had to return never could get it set up"}
{"Author": "Matthew J. Vassallo", "Date": "on December 17, 2016", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Junk", "Text": "Terrible. I have 4 bulbs and the Hue bridge. Has't worked consistently after the first couple of weeks. At first I thought it was the bulbs, and returned those for replacements. Again, it worked for a week or two and then failed. I have missed the window of time to return this item, so I am out $70.00. I will not make the mistake again of buying Philips products."}
{"Author": "J Chen", "Date": "on December 17, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Love it", "Text": "Working well with Echo. Easy to set up. Love it."}
{"Author": "Mort23", "Date": "on December 16, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Works with Echo Dot", "Text": "Works great with Alexa. Took a little time to sync with Alexa but worth it."}
{"Author": "Doc Martin", "Date": "on December 16, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "I am 'all in' with Hue!", "Text": "I've used WeMo for a long time and I've grown tired of losing lights, having to reboot, firmware issues...blah blah blah. I did some research and decided to go with Philips Hue. I really wish I had gone with them from the start.\n\nSetup was insanely easy. The hue lamps work as 'mini-bridges' so running lights across the home was a snap. I like how you can organize lights by rooms and control the lighting scheme as rooms or individual lights. My bride loves our variable white lamp - I installed that one in our living room near her recliner....it will be perfect for relaxing or reading. The bridge will accommodate some 50 lights and accessories - this should be fine for most homes.\n\nI haven't worked much with routines yet - I tend to get up insanely early, but I will run up something that will work well for my Bride.\n\nThe price of bulbs aren't outrageous when you consider the cost of a 'dumb' LED light bulb. Other accessories - like the dimmer switch - convinced me that this was a good way to go; the ability to use a conventional style switch when your phone isn't handy is a great idea. I do wish Philips had smart outlets - I would love to be able to control my Christmas tree. I understand that this could work with a third party outlet - I will probably play around with this over Christmas break (I am a teacher).\n\nIntegration? I haven't decided if I am going with Alexa or Google Home (sorry Jeff)...but Philips works well with either voice activated platform so I am sure that it will be fine either way.\n\nAll in all, a simple and powerful kit to get your smart home lighting solution well in hand."}
{"Author": "E.Ceron", "Date": "on December 16, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Very good product.", "Text": "I gave it as a gift. Very good product."}
{"Author": "Anonymous", "Date": "on December 16, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Works really well!", "Text": "This is really awesome, easy to set up, and actually works! You can control it through Siri, Alexa, or the Hue app, and you can even set timers so that the lights turn on in the morning (which helps wake me up)."}
{"Author": "Amazon Customer", "Date": "on December 16, 2016", "Stars": "3.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "good if you like this color ~3000K ,for starters.", "Text": "only 1 color around 3000 K. Good set to start if you like this color. If you don't then invest in the hue started kit with LED color, $90 more but it would be worth it. good integration with alexa, kinda confusing when setting up but then works like a charm. You need to have the bridge close to your router or modem because it needs a cable connection, apparently it doesn't have a dual band connection with Wifi. that's a big set back if you have a big house and your brigde cannot cover all the rooms. Not sure if it works with location, for example: when i am arriving home turn on the lights, when i am leaving home turn off the light, but it doesn't say it work in the manual. easy to install in you smartphone and to set the widgets if you have android."}
{"Author": "JoAnn Peters", "Date": "on December 16, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Love it.", "Text": "Have lining room & bedroom lights connected & can access through my Dot or use phone app to turn off/on from anywhere. I get into bed & realize I left livingroom light on I just say Alexa, trun off living room light & she does.Love it."}
{"Author": "Lana", "Date": "on December 15, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "I love the idea of turning on my lights remotely", "Text": "I love the idea of turning on my lights remotely. I like it for security and cause it's just convenient and cool. I am very happy that I bought this bundled with the Echo Dot, and if there's a sale on the bulbs, I will buy more of them!"}
{"Author": "Nancy Jones", "Date": "on December 15, 2016", "Stars": "4.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Where does it say I need to know where my router is?", "Text": "This was just what I needed to get a light to turn on and off with Alexa...but it would have been better if more instructions were provided for a novice like myself. I didn't realize the Hue kit needed to be plugged into my router. That was a big deal for me, a tech klutz. Fortunately, online videos helped and I got the thing to do what I wanted. Now my hubby, with dementia can just say, \" Alexa, turn on the light\" and find his way from the living room to the bedroom."}
{"Author": "Jason Stokes", "Date": "on December 15, 2016", "Stars": "4.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Works great, love the automation with apple home kit", "Text": "Works great, love the automation with apple home kit. It doesn't run so well out of the box until you update it. After the update, it works great. Every once in awhile I have an issue with turning the lights on and off from my phone, but overall it works as expected."}
{"Author": "Yakkity", "Date": "on December 15, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Bought as a lark--but super useful!", "Text": "Didn't think I would like this system as much as I do, but it's really been amazing. Initially I bought it to go with my Alexa, but I have really gotten into using this and added a color changing bulb as well. I love being able to dim the bulbs without having to have a dimmer switch installed) and I have gotten so used to using Alexa or my phone to turn them on or off. If I accidentally turn the light off at the switch I am so annoyed at having to get up--so just know these will make you super lazy.\n\nI still need to play with the online features that allow you to set up vacation modes and automatic on off times based on your arrival home. I am interested in getting some to use for my covered outdoor lights so I can turn the lights on from the car if I get home and it is dark."}
{"Author": "Joseph D'Andrea", "Date": "on December 15, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Greast package", "Text": "I made a great choice when I ordered this package."}
{"Author": "Lance", "Date": "on December 15, 2016", "Stars": "3.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Was a Christmas Gift for my brother in law.", "Text": "My sister asked me to order these for her husband for Christmas, I think they are something they will like."}
