{"Author": "J7470ek", "Date": "on July 25, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Great with echo.", "Text": "Bought this and extra bulbs to voice control lights in my house. I rent so I can easily take with me should I move. bought on prime day so i saved a little money. regular price i think is expensive but if bulbs last it will be worth the investment. Hub was easy plug into outlet and ethernet cable gets plugged into router. download app and it finds your hub for set up.The app should be more dummy proof its rather confusing for first time users. My advice would be set up one area at a time (bathroom vanity light then hall then kitchen etc) Install bulbs turn on your switch to that area search for bulbs in app then name that room. when naming room you have to be specific echo only reads what you put in.now go back and repeat for hall kitchen etc. remember the numbers (bathroom is bulbs 1,2,3 etc) you will need for echo. then tell alexa to search devices she tells you to press hub but no need to you have already done this. go to alexa app and create group for each single or set of bulbs (this is where you name room) she will bring up ALL bulbs in numbers thats why you need to remember. take those numbers and create your group. (bulbs 1,2,3 was bathroom etc) check mark bulbs 1 2 3 create group and name bathroom. now you leave all switches in the on position. ask alexa to turn on or off and she will once you have created groups for all bulbs. the bulbs are for inside use ONLY not designed for outdoors also they are better suited for a lamp and not flush mount ceiling lights. the bulbs are not to be covered up (ie flushmount) the bulbs are heavy and get hot as well. I have owned operated for a couple weeks now and really enjoy of course if your wifi goes down you can still flip the switch to turn lights on and off."}
{"Author": "Pongo", "Date": "on July 24, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Phillips Delivers", "Text": "Im very pleased when a product lives up to the hype. Works as promised, about par for home automation setup, nice app and good inter connectivity with Echo / Dot as well. Once you've got the Hue bridge setup, expansion is very easy. Kind of compelling. Turning lights on is not as valuable as having them turned OFF. got kids, woke up in the mornings to find every light in every room left on. The home,automation routines and away commands took care of that. Meets expectations which good because they are pricey. Some cheaper option I tried did not function at all."}
{"Author": "Robbie", "Date": "on July 23, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Five Stars", "Text": "Great product love using them just need to get more bulbs now for more lights in my home"}
{"Author": "MJEP", "Date": "on July 23, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Love!", "Text": "Love! Alexa now controls my lights!"}
{"Author": "L. Noyes", "Date": "on July 22, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Great smart bulb system?...and bug killers?!", "Text": "When I bought my Amazon echo, I decided I wanted to buy this valve system for my porch and living room lights in case I'm not home and forget to have them on. The set up was really Tivoli easy although I needed to be right next to the queue bridge with my iPad controlled echo in order to pair the device. The bulbs are quite bright although I think they need to be brighter for indoors they are perfect for the porch.\nHere is the weird part\u2026 Since I've put the bald in my porch light, I and finding dozens of dead June bugs and mobs below the light every morning! I Soum there something special about these bulbs that not only attract the bugs but kill them as well. Luckily they don't seem to have the same affect indoors! I'm actually kind of glad to get rid of all those June bugs is just an odd surprise I didn't expect to find. The Alexa system works well with the system and I'm thinking about purchasing some more lightbulbs!"}
{"Author": "George R Wendt", "Date": "on July 21, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "It's incredibly convenient and kind of fun. The lights themselves are a nice", "Text": "I use these with my echo to control all of the lights in my apartment. It's incredibly convenient and kind of fun. The lights themselves are a nice, warm light. I'd say it's a bit cooler than a tungsten filament incandescent bulb, but still quite warm as far as fluorescent bulbs go. No issues with either the hub or the bulbs so far."}
{"Author": "W. Lee", "Date": "on July 21, 2016", "Stars": "3.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Great quality but didn't exactly work well with Siri", "Text": "Great quality but didn't exactly work well with Siri. At first I thought it be really cool to control lights from my phone or Amazon Echo but quickly wore out."}
{"Author": "nothingness", "Date": "on July 20, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Works great after set up", "Text": "Installation took a few more minutes than expected, needed to do a reset before app would recognize device. Also had to enter serial numbers for bulbs before they were recognized. After that was easy breezy and Siri and Echo both work great."}
{"Author": "S. Powell", "Date": "on July 20, 2016", "Stars": "3.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "OK, but not awesome out of the box.", "Text": "OK, but not awesome out of the box. The App is pretty weak - for example, you can create a scene but not edit it or delete it. WTF? I guess a 3rd party app is required to get the most out of these. Lack of power failure recovery is a likely dealbreaker.\n\nPros:\n- nice quality of light\n- controllable from phones, etc.\n- can be turned on (fully to default) with a normal switch if you don't have the app or a remote handy. almost a nice feature, but see cons...\n\nCons:\n- lame app - horribly lame really\n- no Power Failure recovery - if the power goes out and comes back on, the lights come on full rather than at their last state. For that reason, I can't see using these anywhere where a sudden fully lit room might be a problem - bedrooms especially. This will probably be a dealbreaker for married guys trying to set these up - my wife was not impressed!\n- pretty expensive given the other cons."}
{"Author": "GadgetGuy", "Date": "on July 19, 2016", "Stars": "4.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Overpriced but works great.", "Text": "I've been wanting a Phillips Hue system for a while and decided to purchase this starter kit on Prime Day. I like the convenience of the system and it works great with my Amazon Echo. I subtracted one star, however, because I think it's a bit overpriced for two bulbs and bridge. But setup was extremely easy and it works just like you would expect."}
{"Author": "Douglas Buffa", "Date": "on July 18, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Easy setup, even for a novice like me", "Text": "Easy setup, even for a novice like me. Would like to see more variety on types of lightbulbs to use with the hub."}
{"Author": "A. Garvin", "Date": "on July 18, 2016", "Stars": "4.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Works great with Amazon echo.", "Text": "Great lights but i dont know why they need to be so expensive."}
{"Author": "Jennifer Victorino", "Date": "on July 18, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Great product. Works well with Alexa aka echo and ...", "Text": "Great product. Works well with Alexa aka echo and our WiFi. We are currently buying more lightblubs for our entire house."}
{"Author": "Chris Granger", "Date": "on July 18, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Awesome (Wish they were cheaper)", "Text": "Paired with the Alexa. These things are awesome - I just wish they were cheaper so I could get more without breaking the bank."}
{"Author": "Ali A", "Date": "on July 17, 2016", "Stars": "2.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Love the Hue Color", "Text": "Love the Hue Color. But was disappointed with Hue White. No warmth control. Just too white. Not sure if the pictures here are from Hue White."}
{"Author": "Fernanda B.", "Date": "on July 17, 2016", "Stars": "4.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Hello everyone, I'm living in Uruguay and I bought ...", "Text": "Hello everyone,\n\nI'm living in Uruguay and I bought this kit few weeks ago. Now can I confirm the Bulbs are 110v and the Bridge are 110-220v.\nIn my opinion it's very interesting use this. I can integrate with HomeKit but I can't use outside my house with my appleTV.\n\nI will continue trying."}
{"Author": "Allen Bock", "Date": "on July 17, 2016", "Stars": "2.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "If you are looking for a yellow glow bulb then buy the Phillips bulb.", "Text": "I am looking to my our home in to a smart house, and I am starting to buy some toys for it . The Philips 455303 Hue White starter bulbs have a yellow glow to them not what I was looking for, so back they went thank you Amazon for the easy return. If you want a true white bulb look at the Lifx 800 it will meet everyone needs, yes it cost more but it will make your eyes happy."}
{"Author": "B. B.", "Date": "on July 17, 2016", "Stars": "4.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "great to start building your smart home", "Text": "I have it working with my echo and love it"}
{"Author": "William A. French", "Date": "on July 17, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Five Stars", "Text": "Nice product - easy setup and integrates seamlessly with SmartThings and Alexa."}
{"Author": "Amazon Customer", "Date": "on July 17, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Great vendor, great product. Stop futzing around and just order it. You will NOT be disappointed.", "Text": "Just order it. You know you want to. It is easy to plug in, simple to get started and the phone app works great. Alexa is still not playing well but I'm sure that is my fault not hers. :)"}
{"Author": "Ryan Lonergan", "Date": "on July 16, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "The best", "Text": "Amazing."}
{"Author": "Chris Figel", "Date": "on July 16, 2016", "Stars": "4.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "These are great.", "Text": "These are great. Getting Alexa app to recognize the bulbs isn't the best on initial setup and I have 7 bulbs so far; is the only reason for the four stars. However... it is a piece of cake if you do the initial setup through the Hue app first."}
{"Author": "GregE", "Date": "on July 15, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Really great product!", "Text": "I bought these on Prime Day & they were delivered today. Set up was a piece of cake. I used them on my front & back porch. I can turn them on & off in one of 3 ways (1) with the app (2) with Siri using my iPhone (3) with my new Echo by asking Mrs. Alexa. The lights are also able to be dimmed. I will be buying more bulbs now that I see how great it works. It also has such a \"wow, cool!\" factor!"}
{"Author": "Janet Mac", "Date": "on July 14, 2016", "Stars": "4.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Great Start to my Smart Home", "Text": "Expensive, but it works great and compatible with my Echo."}
{"Author": "Reading reading reading", "Date": "on July 14, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Woohoo, by golly it works!", "Text": "I bought the GE Wink system and it came in on Tuesday, I spent a couple hours at least, trying to get it to work and on the phone with various tech support trying to discover why it wasn't working when I decided to check if Amazon had any tips in the reviews and some one had posted 20 minutes earlier that they had the same problem and found out that GE didn't own rights to the hub at this moment and the bulbs were not linking to the hub. I got on the phone to Amazon, got a return label and ordered the Philips Hue Starter Kit (Prime Day Deal, woohoo again!) It came in today and I had it working with my 2 Echos and iPad in 45 minutes and thats counting the trips back and forth a few times with the step stool, love it!!"}
{"Author": "Carolyn Pierce", "Date": "on July 14, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Compatible with Echo...great purchase!!", "Text": "Works with Echo. Love having Alexa turning on and off lights."}
{"Author": "RRob", "Date": "on July 13, 2016", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Who designed this crap Cannot verify bridge will return", "Text": "Software awful. Who designed this crap\n\nCannot verify bridge will return"}
{"Author": "LA Holc", "Date": "on July 13, 2016", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "I am pretty tech savy and this product is not at all ...", "Text": "I am pretty tech savy and this product is not at all worth the price or effort. First the app couldn't find the hub by searching or by entering the IP address. I don't have time for tech products that aren't quite right out of the box. I have never had issues with all my wireless products, security cameras, echo, etc. I am going to wait until a better product launches or do more research before I buy another \"smart\" lighting product."}
{"Author": "M. C. Austin", "Date": "on July 13, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Great thing to have when your hands are full!", "Text": "I got these because it works with Amazon echo. I like how you can set it up to call it whatever you want. I made my wife laugh till tears rolled when I got her into a discussion about how smart Alexa is. During the conversation I said I could prove it and said, \"Alexa, turn on the light of the prettiest girl in the house.\" Alexa said OK and my wife's light came on. It was priceless! Setting up the Hue base is very easy! Just plug it in. Screw in the bulbs and they find each other. It couldn't be easier. To control it all by phone, download the app, press the button on the Hue base and you're done. We have 3 lights in the bathroom. At night we turn 2 of them off and dim 1 to 1%, like a night light. Works great! We can tell Alexa to dim Michael's bulb 50% and she will. So far we only have the white lights and love it! At Christmas, we might try a color light. One comment regarding what we read from others, I was concerned about reviews I read saying the light was yellow, not white. We don't have that problem. They are white and bright! It's fun and comes in handy when you hands are full bringing in the groceries!"}
{"Author": "DadNamedRob", "Date": "on July 12, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Great for Echo Integration", "Text": "Bought the Hue system to work with our Amazon Echo. Absolutely love it all."}
{"Author": "Nicholas De Pauw", "Date": "on July 11, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "I really enjoy this system and the automated routines i built with ...", "Text": "I went cheap and got the white only lights. I really enjoy this system and the automated routines i built with the app and home kit. I look forward to adding some color bulbs in the next few months."}
{"Author": "Mohan Muppidi", "Date": "on July 10, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Five Stars", "Text": "Pretty cool, connected home is here"}
{"Author": "Johnny Wu", "Date": "on July 8, 2016", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "slows my wifi and my home network, not worth it.", "Text": "I was so excited to use it until discovering that after a week or so, it started hogging wifi and my internet speed slowed down to a halt, apparently it's internal setting is interfering with my entire home network so much that my internet speed goes from 30mbps to 2mpbs or less. not good. I have since disconnected the system and voom, speed is back to normal. not happy."}
{"Author": "SwEng", "Date": "on July 6, 2016", "Stars": "2.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Two Stars", "Text": "One bulb came DOA. The app is slow and counter-intuitive."}
{"Author": "GoldenSolo", "Date": "on July 5, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "They work great", "Text": "So far pretty good. They work great. I'm only using two bulbs right now, and I'll slowly buy more as time passes."}
{"Author": "L. M. Marcos", "Date": "on July 5, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "I absolutely love this product", "Text": "I absolutely love this product. The setup was really easy and became the gateway into buying 10 more bulbs. I also love the Amazon Echo integration. Great stuff!!!!"}
{"Author": "Peter Saeger", "Date": "on June 30, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Great Addition to the home.", "Text": "These Light bulbs have to be the greatest thing I've added to my home in a while. Paired with Alexa the ability to dim and turn them on or off is just fantastic. Setup was a bit touchy when I had one too far away to be auto detected but after entering the serial number it was detected and I was good to go.\n\nI do also appreciate the fact that when you use the light switch and turn it off and then back on the light comes on so you can use them like a traditional bulb if you have visitors or just can't get it turned on via app or Alexa.\n\nI think the next thing for me will be getting the multi-colored bulbs to have even more fun."}
{"Author": "Jim", "Date": "on June 30, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Bulbs work great - but know you are not getting color options ...", "Text": "Bulbs work great - but know you are not getting color options these are plain white. I have them connected to Amazon's Echo. \"Alexa, turn bedroom light on 50% - bam you have 1/2 power on the bulb. Love it. Can even turn it on/off from the Philips Hue app on my iPhone on a cell network. Don't buy the cheap stuff - get the Philips Hue."}
{"Author": "Lili", "Date": "on June 30, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Five Stars", "Text": "Great product!"}
{"Author": "DARYL FAIRCHILD", "Date": "on June 28, 2016", "Stars": "2.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Might be good for some.", "Text": "I was excited to start with this kit Philips 455303 Hue White Starter A19 Kit, 2nd Generation, Works with Alexa and get experience with the Hue system. Sorry to say my experience has not been that good. It was fairly easy to get it set up and running. It performed as expected for a while. I soon discovered that any power interruption required that I go through the setup again. Living in the \"Lightning Capital\" of the US means I have frequent power surges and power drops. That effects the Wi-Fi the Hue is connected to and it must be reset. This results in the Hue system not working until I can reset it. That defeats my plan of having lights turn on and off while I am away from the house since it would only work until the first power failure.\nI guess I will go back to the plug-in-the-wall timer. Does anyone know of a good one?"}
{"Author": "Tim Davis", "Date": "on June 27, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Living in the future.", "Text": "This thing is amazing. I connected it to my Amazon Echo and control the lights fully with just my voice. I can't get it to work when I'm away from home as the description claims but that is not a big loss to me. Voice activation makes me feel like I'm living in the future. These bulbs are white only, not sure why you would want other colors. fully dimmable by telling Alexa what percent to turn the lights to."}
{"Author": "Chuck", "Date": "on June 27, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Works great. It's also a real cool add-on to the ...", "Text": "Works great. It's also a real cool add-on to the Amazon Echo!"}
{"Author": "John", "Date": "on June 27, 2016", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Great if it would just work", "Text": "Great if it would just work! Problem is it constantly loses its connection to wi-fi and I have to reconnect it every time I want to use it. It has been disappointing. It has been of no practical use to me!"}
{"Author": "Zach S.", "Date": "on June 25, 2016", "Stars": "4.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "The lights themselves are fine, but the system is slow to react sometimes", "Text": "The lights themselves are fine, but the system is slow to react sometimes. Lights are hindered by the app at the moment."}
{"Author": "Jeanne Burns", "Date": "on June 24, 2016", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Bad App Therefore Bad Tech", "Text": "I wish I'd read the app reviews before buying this item because I couldn't get the app to connect to my network and therefore the system never worked for me. I'm pretty tech competent and have never had a problem connecting devices to my network. I print wirelessly, for instance. But over and over again I got a text saying I wasn't putting in the right code. I'm sure this will be good tech in about a decade or so."}
{"Author": "Grade2Pencil", "Date": "on June 24, 2016", "Stars": "4.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Work well, but still way too expensive.", "Text": "Work well, but still way too expensive."}
{"Author": "Amazon Customer", "Date": "on June 22, 2016", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Horrible. I got one out of 3 bulbs to ...", "Text": "Horrible. I got one out of 3 bulbs to pair. 2 bulbs came with the starter kit along with the bridge, and I bought a third one for a different room. 1 bulb is actually working. It saw the 2 that came with the set up initially but now says 'Unreachable' for both - but one actually does what I ask of it, while the other sits there dark (although it does blink when I change channels - that's useful). I will try again tomorrow, but I think I will be getting my money back and going another route for remote lighting to increase security."}
{"Author": "Michael Janski", "Date": "on June 22, 2016", "Stars": "3.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Meh. Just ok.", "Text": "Well, I purchased the Philips Hue starter kit with 2 white bulbs, hub, and dimmer switch. It's not hard to set up. The app for Android is okay, as it does give you control over how warm and dimmer level. The issue I have is, why give us only a 60 watt equivalent bulb? Philips only offers a low lumen bulb for their connected hub. I replaced a 3 way standard bulb for a low power one that doesn't meet the lighting needs of our living room. I'm sorry Philips, but I'm going back to the standard, brighter, 3 way bulb until you up the lumins on your connected bulbs."}
{"Author": "Amazon Customer", "Date": "on June 22, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Five Stars", "Text": "This one is what I need!!"}
{"Author": "Jacob Riha", "Date": "on June 22, 2016", "Stars": "4.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Great product. I have a system myself and I ...", "Text": "Great product. I have a system myself and I bought one for my Mom to work with her Amazon Echo. It works great! Only complaint is that you have to be pretty tech savvy to set it up in the Philips App and then the Alexa App. It was difficult for my Mom to figure it out. But once installed it makes life a little easier and toe stubbing in the darkness less likely!"}
{"Author": "abraham c pendon", "Date": "on June 20, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Five Stars", "Text": "Awesome.... That is all."}
{"Author": "Es", "Date": "on June 20, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Five Stars", "Text": "Awesome now I got colors and stock bulb"}
{"Author": "William Kirby", "Date": "on June 19, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Five Stars", "Text": "Absolutely love it, my whole house has smart lights."}
{"Author": "Christopher J. Bartnik", "Date": "on June 19, 2016", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "NOT WORKING WITH ECHO", "Text": "I cannot get these to work with my Echo. Customer support from both Amazon and Phillips is all but nonexistent. I have no issues with WeMo and other devices, just Hue. I will be returning for a refund."}
{"Author": "Koasmom", "Date": "on June 18, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Great idea.", "Text": "Ok, so my husband thought this was pretty silly but I love them. They are the size of a regular bulb. While Phillips has a free app, I did go ahead and pay for a different one. I like the way it works better. The lights come on at dusk and stay on until the time I set to go off. I liked these so much, I bought a couple for the spare room."}
{"Author": "Andrew J. Good", "Date": "on June 16, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Hue Light Bulbs are very nice. Being able to control them through a phone ...", "Text": "Hue Light Bulbs are very nice. Being able to control them through a phone app is wonderful and they are very easy to setup. What's also nice about them is they are LED bulbs so they'll save energy and last for a very long time. Also compatible with Amazon Echo so anyone can control them through voice.\n\nThe app could use a lot of work however. One of the biggest features I would love to see added the the apps is security. Right now security is pretty simple, I activate my app, and one time only I click on the button on the hub and have access to every single bulb that's connected to it. I would love to be able to designate certain family members phones to be able to control only certain light bulbs. Their newer app also allows you to group bulbs together for simultaneous control but it doesn't allow a single bulb to be apart of multiple groups."}
{"Author": "BMaryott", "Date": "on June 16, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "My future's so bright.... if I want it to be.", "Text": "Going Phillips for my lighting in the future!"}
{"Author": "Butch", "Date": "on June 15, 2016", "Stars": "4.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Four Stars", "Text": "works well"}
{"Author": "John Thomas Morgan", "Date": "on June 15, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Awesome product!", "Text": "Super easy to setup and works great with the Amazon Echo!"}
{"Author": "Randall Morris", "Date": "on June 14, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Great addition to my Smart Home", "Text": "I bought this starter kit to work with the other Homekit devices in my house (which I control via Siri with my iPhone). The router attachment was easy to configure as was their app. Now I have the lights integrated into the \"I'm Home\" scene with Homekit. When I tell Siri I'm home, the door unlocks, the thermostat changes from away to home, and these lights turn on. The Philips app to control individual lights has worked flawlessly (given I'm just using white lights, I haven't done anything with color) and I've never had any issues with Siri commands to turn the lights on or off. This is a great buy and only takes a minimal amount of setup time to work flawlessly."}
{"Author": "Robert S.", "Date": "on June 13, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Let There Be Light", "Text": "Super easy installation. Controls all of my lights effortlessly. Love how lights can be controlled from my iPhone when I'm not home."}
{"Author": "Mark Stout", "Date": "on June 13, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "I love these lights and the starter kit", "Text": "I love these lights and the starter kit. I am transitioning my home to a more automated environment and these played right into what I am trying to do with my house. I am now able to control the lights through my phone or my computer. This is great."}
{"Author": "erase-o-rama", "Date": "on June 13, 2016", "Stars": "4.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Has potential, but missing security.", "Text": "It's got some issues, no remote access or SSL connection. And I would never pay full price for it (got mine through warehouse deals).\n\nBut it does allow for remote control of my light through a 3rd party app, as long as you know how to setup port forwarding on your router. Lack of SSL connection here is concerning."}
{"Author": "Magic", "Date": "on June 11, 2016", "Stars": "3.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Three Stars", "Text": "won't connect to wifi for me"}
{"Author": "Joseph T Harper", "Date": "on June 11, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Can't believe I waited so long to begin the move to a smart house.", "Text": "Ordered the starter kit on Amazon and three days later, after setting up Philips with Echo, had to go buy more lights. Can't believe I waited so long to begin the move to a smart house."}
{"Author": "Karin A.", "Date": "on June 11, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Perfect!", "Text": "Got this \"used\" (I'm guessing it was a customer return) but works perfectly. Love it! Ordering a few more bulbs."}
{"Author": "MastersOfNone", "Date": "on June 11, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Smart home lighting.", "Text": "This is what I used to start my new wifi-enabled home lighting project. The bulbs are great, the interface is great and the best part is, they work with Amazon Echo."}
{"Author": "David W Mills", "Date": "on June 7, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Technology is just the best! I love being able to control my lights ...", "Text": "Technology is just the best! I love being able to control my lights in my home with my voice. Can set mood lighting or full on brightness. Perfect for social time and TV time. Plug and go!"}
{"Author": "Jeffrey S.", "Date": "on June 7, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Five Stars", "Text": "works great, easy setup."}
{"Author": "JRB", "Date": "on June 6, 2016", "Stars": "2.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "You get less than what you pay for.", "Text": "These worked decently, but I hate that I can't connect the device to the internet wirelessly. You need to plug it into a modem/router directly. Also, one of the bulbs went out in about 6 weeks. This was pretty expensive of a light to have it break down so easily. I wasn't even using them as anything but ordinary lights in that time, so I can't even say it was from overuse."}
{"Author": "Kindle Customer", "Date": "on June 6, 2016", "Stars": "4.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "it works fine. I'm considering buying some of the colored lights ...", "Text": "It was a little confusing (for me, at least) to get it to work the way I wanted, but once going, it works fine. I'm considering buying some of the colored lights also."}
{"Author": "Steve", "Date": "on June 6, 2016", "Stars": "4.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "More Light for the Dollar !", "Text": "The Phillips A19 Kit is a nice start to automate things in your home. Another great Smart Home addition. Easy to set up and amazingly Fast shipping."}
{"Author": "Jessica Brown", "Date": "on June 6, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "No more coming home in the dark!", "Text": "I love my lights and am so glad I installed them. The color is great and I love that I can set them to different dimness levels throughout the day according to my needs. I wish the app for the iPhone were just a bit better. You can only use the app if you are near the hub. Otherwise there's a website to connect to that allows you to adjust the lights over the internet."}
{"Author": "K", "Date": "on June 5, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Love them! I use them everyday and they work ...", "Text": "Love them! I use them everyday and they work exactly like they should! I love being able to dim the lightbulbs themselves, it's a feature I use constantly!"}
{"Author": "cmf", "Date": "on June 4, 2016", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "the TRUTH!", "Text": "It works and It doesn't work because they released a product making you abandon all your scenes if you press the reset button. it should of been on beta longer. it also doesn't work with sleepcycle or sleep cycle doesn't work with it.\n\nbasically released a product not ready for prime time. it is half assed need to say."}
{"Author": "Kathie A Tardie", "Date": "on June 3, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Fun and Convenient", "Text": "Works well with Amazon's Alexa."}
{"Author": "Christopher A. Hedlund", "Date": "on June 2, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Five Stars", "Text": "This product came and it delivered, it works with my phone"}
{"Author": "Amazon Customer", "Date": "on June 2, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Five Stars", "Text": "Love them. Let me know when they are on sale. Will purchase more."}
{"Author": "D-doc", "Date": "on May 31, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Thinking about it.... Buy it.", "Text": "Hue bulbs work very well. They are brighter than I imagined them to be. There was some trouble getting the hub to be controlled when out the home (flashing third light for Web connection) but my solution was as simple as unplugging my router for a few minutes then powering it back up. Currently I use them with my echo and it has worked flawlessly so far. Definitely recommend theses if you are looking into home automation products."}
{"Author": "Paul", "Date": "on May 30, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Much better with native Alexa integration", "Text": "I became much happier with this when hue upgraded to allow native compatibility with my Echo. IFTTT was a clunky solution. The bulbs are slightly brighter than the old LUX. Overall, I'm happy with the purchase."}
{"Author": "Bruce Drake", "Date": "on May 26, 2016", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Hue WiFi kit to control lights fails the Apple test", "Text": "I have a rule. If setting up on app with devices is not as easy as setting up a new iPhone, it fails and I cut my losses. After wasted hours, that's the case here"}
{"Author": "Jose R. Huerta Sanchez", "Date": "on May 24, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Connected it to Echo and works very good. But i have not been able to change ...", "Text": "Connected it to Echo and works very good. But i have not been able to change the name of the lights."}
{"Author": "DW", "Date": "on May 23, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "So cool--can't wait to order fancy ones got my recessed lighting", "Text": "I bought this as a trial starter kit. I use them for mostly night lights. They are programmed to be dim at night.\nReally cool feature: with IFTTT integration, when the baby moves/cries/whines, the Nest/Drop cam in the nursery will cause the living room lamp to flash.\nI also can turn on/off using Amazon echo (Alexa).\n\nOf purchasing for just one or two lights it's ok, but if you can integrate with Alexa, Nest, IFTTT, and other home lights they are worth the money. It's like living in the future!"}
{"Author": "Poshjap", "Date": "on May 23, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Great kit to work with Amazon Echo!", "Text": "I love these light bulbs. The kit works really well with my Amazon echo. I love that it dims nicely and it doesn't get too bright."}
{"Author": "William K", "Date": "on May 23, 2016", "Stars": "4.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Recommend this Starter kit for home automation", "Text": "Yes, I like this starter kit. I enjoy the compatibility with my echo. Easy set-up, within minutes. I like that I am able to control intensity (echo: bedroom light 25%). I immediately ordered two more bulbs."}
{"Author": "Nate", "Date": "on May 23, 2016", "Stars": "4.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "I almost bought this 4-5 times before finally pulling the ...", "Text": "I almost bought this 4-5 times before finally pulling the trigger. The product has a lot of potential--the only reason for a missing star is some preferred options on the software side."}
{"Author": "Daniel Taylor", "Date": "on May 20, 2016", "Stars": "4.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Good", "Text": "I like them. They work with Alexa. I like that I can dim the lights. Pretty cool tech."}
{"Author": "Christopher M.", "Date": "on May 20, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Five Stars", "Text": "Works perfectly with my Amazon Echo. I haven't had any issues with it."}
{"Author": "R. Kosh", "Date": "on May 18, 2016", "Stars": "4.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "\"Hey Siri, dim the living room light\"", "Text": "I'm giving it a 4-star only because the instructions to make it work with Apple Home Kit and Siri really suck. I needed to go onto the Internet and search for ideas.\n\nAs you may have guessed, I bought this to work with Siri. I'm replacing my old fashioned remote lights and timers with modern smart home equivalents, and this was to be my replacement for a living room light and my bedroom light. Setup was a snap. I plugged the Hue hub into my ethernet switch, and the iPhone app quickly set thing up within about a minute. The Hue app worked great, but I could not for the life of me get it to pair with Siri--which was the whole point of buying this. I finally found something one the Internet where someone else had had the same issue and got it to work by plugging the Hue hub into the router directly, not a switch. I tried and was instantly rewarded with the hub pairing to Apple's Home Kit and Siri. Anyone else with this problem would be advised to give this a try.\n\nI am now able to set up schedules for the lights to go on and off, and can control them lights by telling Siri to turn the on/off or dim them. With this added convenience, I see no reason to move off my sofa . . . ever. I will likely have a heart attack and die in place, with Siri wondering why I quit talking to her."}
{"Author": "Jonathan H.", "Date": "on May 16, 2016", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Philips locked support for other zigbee bulbs. Go with WeMo.", "Text": "Completely updated. 3rd party ZigBee bulbs not working. Thanks for nothing Philips. Good luck with your narrow ecosystem of proprietary devices. Ibhope that everyone who reads this review saves their money for something more open lime WeMo."}
{"Author": "GeekMom", "Date": "on May 14, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Best tool to make waking up easy!", "Text": "Seriously LOVE these guys! I wake up so much easier now, I have the HUE app alarm that sets them to turn on to a low light mode 15 minutes before my alarm goes off. I never sleep over my alarm anymore. it makes waking up so much more peaceful and enjoyable! I love being able to turn them on before I come in to be able to see where I am going and they work flawlessly with amazon echo. Yes they are costly, but even after having a cat knock over a lap they keep working. and The ability to change lighting settings so easily with the added on remote from hue to dim and brighten is AMAZING benefit for entertaining during the evening hours."}
{"Author": "K. Valen", "Date": "on May 13, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Works great with Alexa.", "Text": "Works great with Alexa. Simple set up. Great control over lighting moods through the Philips app"}
{"Author": "J. Pilcher", "Date": "on May 13, 2016", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Weak range", "Text": "This technology will not work if your bridge must be plugged into a router that is located on a separate floor than the bulbs. The technical requirement is bulbs must be within 50 feet of unobstructed distance from the Philips bridge. So mine had to be returned. Unfortunately, the bridge does not use wifi technology where separate floors would not be an issue."}
{"Author": "Amazon Customer", "Date": "on May 8, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "better than WIX", "Text": "loved it you have to have near a modem to use the thing but that is not a problem to me I liked how you can hang it up on a hook if you have no space. It took quite a bit to setup though it didn't work the first couple times but I was patient enough and it worked. I really like how you can dim lights that can't regularly be dimmed."}
{"Author": "Luis Fernandez", "Date": "on May 6, 2016", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "White led bulbs really? They are Yellow ligths!!!", "Text": "Everything works as expected what bothers me is that its says WHITE led bulbs when in fact they are YELLOW. Truly disapointed!!!"}
{"Author": "Mash", "Date": "on May 6, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Works great with Echo", "Text": "Works great. I got the Chrome extension for Hue to setup the system. Name the bulb groups ('Living Room', 'Bedroom',...) to make it easy to control using Echo. It was easy to setup with Echo as well, basically say 'Alexa, scan for devices' and press the round button. These bulbs are dimmable so Echo can control brightness."}
{"Author": "Abhirav Kushwaha", "Date": "on May 5, 2016", "Stars": "4.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Four Stars", "Text": "Wish they had included color lights in the starter kit"}
{"Author": "mamil", "Date": "on May 5, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Simple to use and not unreasonably priced", "Text": "10-minute set-up and I have Alexa controlling my lights. I love it. Much better than Wemo. The replacement bulbs are $15/per (for white only), not far out of whack with LED bulbs' ordinary cost. I only worry: if GPS has killed my map-reading ability, will these kill my ability to use a light-switch?"}
{"Author": "Kellie Lynn Art", "Date": "on May 5, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Pleasantly Surprised", "Text": "I was worried that it was just my inner geek wanting cool stuff. These work incredibly well and we love them in the house. When paired with the Echo, these are really great. Of course, it means you may need to get some extra walking in, because now we just ask to turn on our lights instead of getting up.\n\nThe dimming feature is my favorite thing about these as well as grouping the lights. When we go to bed, we just say lights off and all the lights in the house shut down. The dim goes pretty low if you just want a little bit of light and they are pretty bright bulbs too."}
{"Author": "MrPersonGuy", "Date": "on May 4, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Easy to set up", "Text": "Easy to set up, works as advertised.\n\nPrior to this I had purchased GE Link bulbs, with the Link hub (which works through wink). I had several issues with unresponsive or lost connections between the GE bulbs and the link hub. I ditched the link hub and now connect the GE Link bulbs to the hue bridge without any trouble. Latency and unresponsiveness is gone.\n\nThe hue white bulbs themselves are bright, and a good color. I don't find them much different than the GE link bulbs, aside from physical appearance of the bulb itself."}
{"Author": "Adrienne A Hicks", "Date": "on May 3, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Love electronics!", "Text": "I'm addicted!! Bought and Amazon Echo... bought these so I don't have to get up all the time to turn on lights, or enter my brothers room to turn off his light. Oh, Philips, your addicting..."}
{"Author": "Jeremy D. Pavleck", "Date": "on April 30, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Just works. Period.", "Text": "WARNING! The Amazon Echo is an Automation gateway drug - that's how I ended up ordering this Hue starter kit a month ago, and have since spent many dollars on adding more lights to the system.\nIt's amazing how well it works. And the bridge appears to receive constant developer attention as I've had 3 updates since I bought it.\nI really can't add anything more then what other reviewers have listed, but I can say that since I've started using the Hue I can't believe it took me so long to get it!"}
{"Author": "Evan Jensen", "Date": "on April 28, 2016", "Stars": "2.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Not white, but yellow light.", "Text": "These are cool in that you can control them with your smart phone and voice, but they are not white. I wanted white lights and these are called white, but sadly they are yellow. Due to this I cannot give a good rating and will be returning the kit."}
{"Author": "Aimee Rose", "Date": "on April 27, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "...", "Text": "Completely unnecessary and it enables you to be lazy. I absolutely love it \ud83d\udc4d Already ordered color bulbs and string lights.\n*Only complaint is the Phillips Hue app itself but I found one I really like:\nall 4 hue (for Phillips Hue)"}
{"Author": "ScottF", "Date": "on April 26, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Works pretty flawlessly with my Echo", "Text": "Works pretty flawlessly with my Echo.The dimming is the best part. The app isn't the best but I seldom use it anyway, I mostly control via the Echo."}
{"Author": "Bradley H Jones", "Date": "on April 25, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Five Stars", "Text": "I have these hooked up and and using Smartthings and Alexa!"}
{"Author": "teknoge3k", "Date": "on April 25, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Five Stars", "Text": "Works great with my Echo!"}
{"Author": "Amazon Customer", "Date": "on April 25, 2016", "Stars": "4.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "usage is easy and responsive granted Elexa hears you", "Text": "Physical Set up was simple, app/echo (groups) setup was a bit combersom. Once setup is complete, usage is easy and responsive granted Elexa hears you."}
{"Author": "Algee", "Date": "on April 24, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "All over the house and control with Echo", "Text": "I have it , I love it , and control with Amazon Echo"}
{"Author": "Sacgirl2", "Date": "on April 22, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "The Lights were very easy to set up", "Text": "This was my first adventure with hue lights. I chose the white starter kit because of the cheaper price. I plan to add color bulbs later if the price goes down. The Lights were very easy to set up. I bought 2 extra white bulbs, place them in my living room and bedroom lamps. It was very easy to add to echo. I love saying \"Alexa turn on bedroom lights\" no more walking in they dark. I will purchase more bulbs eventually. Happy to see that the 2nd generation now works with Apple products as well as echo."}
{"Author": "PhoEniX", "Date": "on April 22, 2016", "Stars": "4.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Awesome product, but it should not need to be wired to your router", "Text": "while i love the fact that i can control thelights and their brightness through my echo dot now, setting this up was not easy. not impressed by the fact that the link needs to be connected to a router(wth!), instead of just connecting to your wifi."}
{"Author": "Chupa Cabra", "Date": "on April 22, 2016", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Wireless interface and therefore the product does not work.", "Text": "Doesn't work. Philips Customer Support was no help. They told me I needed to set up a second wireless network just for the hub. Does not work as advertised."}
{"Author": "Cordain A. Lucas", "Date": "on April 21, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "1 free A19 light with purchase of this kit.", "Text": "I have been eyeing the Philips Hue system for a while now. As someone who has paid his share of early adopter tax I figured I would wait this one out a little bit until the 2nd generation came out. I am glad I waited. I have read some of the reviews of folks who purchased earlier units and to say that it wasn't smooth sailing is an understatement. But enough of the past let's talk about the current state of technology.\n\nINCLUDED IN THE BOX:\n2 Philips Hue 60 Watt equivalent WARM Bulbs\n1 Power Transformer (120VAC to 5 volt DC)\n1 Philips Hue Ver 2.0 controller (Version 2 is square, Version 1 is round)\n1 24 inch Cat 5 ethernet cable\n1 Quick Start Guide\n1 FCC Compliance Card / Warranty Card\n\nSetup was a breeze in fact it took me longer to purchase my Hue kit than it did to set it up. I did not purchase my kit from Amazon because a local big box home improvement store had the kit on sale cheaper and I was able to pick it up tonight. Luckily for me this was a local purchase because the first Hue kit was DOA. I plugged the Bridge into the wall and no lights turned on. I placed my amp clamp around it the wire and power supply and no juice was flowing. Hopped back in the car and did a quick exchange and the second kit has been flawless.\n\nSetup is roughly 3 steps.\n1.) Twist light bulbs in, turn on light bulbs. (Leave on)\n2.) Plug Phillips controller into home router, you need 1 ethernet port on your internet (WiFi) connected router. Plug hub into power from included transformer. Plug transformer into live electrical outlet.\n3.) Download Hue app to phone or tablet.\n\nAssuming you followed those instructions in order, you should have no problems. Once you start the app the Hue will guide you through setting up your bulbs and adding them to your system as well as Siri voice control if you are into IOS. Otherwise it works with Amazons Echo device as well. I'm sure Android works.\n\nThe hue comes with a few scenes setup for you already amongst these are:\nAll Off\nTwilight (Maybe 20% on)\nSnooze (For alarm clock mode)\nRise and Shine (Slowly brings lights from dim to full power)\nRead (Maybe 60% on)\nFull Bright (100% on)\n\nYou can change any of those presets or create your own scenes with different lights at different levels. Since this is the white kit, dim or bright is about as exciting as it gets.\n\nAs far value is concerned. If you are looking to get into smart home technology and specifically the Philips Hue system on the whole this is a great kit to dip your toes in without going full monty right away. I looked at the Hue starter kit Philips 456210 Hue White and Color Ambiance A19 Bulb Starter Kit 2nd Generation, Works with Alexa with the 3 full color + white led bulbs and while it is a decent value @ $200 if those are the types of bulbs you are interested in it was not exactly what I wanted.\n\nInitially I was going to buy just the Philips 458489 Hue Bridge - Frustration Free Packaging, 2nd Generation which is currently retailing on Amazon for about $60 Prime. When I found this starter kit at the big box store for the price of the Philips Hub and a Philips White A19 I was essentially getting a second Philips White A19 bulb for free. Pretty sweet deal and I recommend it if you want to get into this technology but aren't looking to drop a whole wad of cash on your initial purchase or if the starter kit doesn't have the types of bulbs you want.\n\nPersonally I am going to be building my system out with the Philips Par Philips 456673  Hue White and Color Ambiance Extension Par16 Bulbs, 2nd Generation and Friends of Hue Philips 259960 Friends of Hue Personal Wireless Lighting Iris Single, Frustration Free around my home. I like the light to be seen and not the bulbs so I will be bouncing the lights off of diffusion fabric and ceilings and walls so the room is bathed in a glow of non directional light. I will post photos later after I have built my system out.\n\nApple Watch integration is neat. You can use either your phone or you watch to issue commands to Siri. Of course there is a minor delay built in between Siri understanding the command and then relaying it back through your phone to the hub. It's faster to pick your pre-canned scenes from your watch, they execute almost instantly.\n\nAll together it took me longer to get a working starter kit than it did to setup this system. I have started to order the bulbs and fixtures for my new system and I cannot wait to have it all installed."}
{"Author": "The Critical Consumer", "Date": "on April 20, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Awesome!", "Text": "Fantastic bulbs and great controls through the app! I tried Wemo before because they're cheaper, but these are so worth the extra money. They just work."}
{"Author": "Diedra Holley", "Date": "on April 19, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Good alone; great with Echo.", "Text": "I got this, pulled out the quick start directions and it couldn't have been simpler. Put the light bulbs in your lights, plug in the bridge, download the app. Off and running. These are really wonderful. It was just as easy to connect these so I could control them with my Echo. Now I walk into the house with a double armload of groceries or gear and say, \"Alexa, TV room lights, 80 percent.\" I hear Alexa says \"Ok\" just as my TV room lights turn on to 80% brightness. I go through my evening, crawl into bed and then it's, \"Alexa, all lights off.\" They all turn off and I head off into dreamland. I have my Nest thermostat hooked up to my Echo as well. Slowly but surely I am turning my home into a smart house that I can take with me when I move. I think that's the best part. I can create a complete and total smart house, but if I move, I don't have to start over or yank a bunch of wiring. I just unscrew the bulbs, unplug the bridge, unplug my echo and Nest and take it all with me. No need to invest more money on the next house to get it how I want it again! Single investment is a wonderful thing!"}
{"Author": "FLORENTINO F. PEGUES", "Date": "on April 19, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Great product.", "Text": "I'm slowly converting my home into a smart house. They are kind of expensive, but worth it. Great product. Can't wait until they go on sell to get more."}
{"Author": "J. Reyes", "Date": "on April 19, 2016", "Stars": "2.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "They really should not call these lights \"White\" because they ...", "Text": "They really should not call these lights \"White\" because they are not. they are yellow and very dim even at full brightness."}
{"Author": "Cheryl Drake", "Date": "on April 18, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Five Stars", "Text": "Easy to install and I control my lights using my Echo !"}
{"Author": "ocalaheart", "Date": "on April 17, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "A lot cheaper than having an electrician move your light switches", "Text": "My wife wanted some large pictures to be hung, but 2 wall switches were in the way. Thought about calling the electrician to move the switches, but this turned out to be a whole lot cheaper. With this gadget, you no longer need to use the switches, so I can cover them with the pictures. First replace the bulbs with the Hue bulbs. Switch them on and leave the switches on. Connect the Hue bridge power cord to an outlet near your router or access point, and then connect the included ethernet cable from the bridge to the router or access point. Download the Hue app to your smartphone (mine is a Samsung Galaxy 4), install it and open it. It finds the bridge and the bulbs quickly. The app allows you to rename the lights to something more practical than the default \"lamp 1\" and \"lamp 2.\" Worked instantly the first time. Then the cool part. It took her 3 tries, but Alexa (Amazon Echo) found the lights with the names I gave them. Now I just say, \"Alexa. Turn the south porch light on,\" and she says, \"OK,\" and she does! Same thing with turning it off, and same thing with the north porch light as well. Don't need the light switches anymore, and my wife can cover them with her pictures."}
{"Author": "danny", "Date": "on April 15, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "whats not to like? led lights are better than conventional bulbs save ...", "Text": "whats not to like? led lights are better than conventional bulbs save power and have flexibility using them!\nonly downside is price, i live in a small condo so it was a good investment for me, a bigger house will cost a lot just for bulbs.\n\nusing the app i can turn my lights on and off as long as there is internet"}
{"Author": "RDC", "Date": "on April 14, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Seriously cool", "Text": "receivedAmazon Echo about 3 days ago, and ordered this kit 2 days ago. Just received it and it took about 10 minutes to set up. Very easy, even for complete newbie. Works beautifully with Alexa. Couldn't figure out how to change the light bulb names in the Hue app I downloaded, but just created groups of 1 in the Alexa app to personalize each lamp. Can turn lights on, off and dim them with easy voice commands. How cool is this?!? Science Fiction rushing right at us!!"}
{"Author": "Benjamin T. Vonderschmitt", "Date": "on April 14, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Finally shinning some light on home automation.", "Text": "I have had Hue now for just over a month with just the two bulbs. I also have Alexia from Amazon. Some of the reviews left me worried that it would take a bit of effort to pair the two. There was next to nothing to be done, the hardest part was setting up the scene in the right app (the Alexia app instead of the Hue app.) It also works well with my Apple Home Kit devices. Occasionally one of the lights will not come on in a scene, but overall a very easy and reliable product."}
{"Author": "James", "Date": "on April 13, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Easy setup, fun to use", "Text": "I have 3 Echo devices (original, dot and tap) that now control most of my indoor lighting. Setting up the bridge took seconds, searching for lights was a breeze. Follow the directions in the easy-to-use app and make sure to power them on before searching. Then create any groups after Alexa finds them (find additional bulbs: tap the bridge button again, easy). App allows you to turn any bulb on/off from practically anywhere."}
{"Author": "Shannan Thompson", "Date": "on April 13, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Works great with Alexa", "Text": "This product works great with Alexa. I love how easy it is to control my lights."}
{"Author": "Victor", "Date": "on April 11, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Great LED bulbs and connectivity, a bit spendy, but very much worth it!", "Text": "So, when I initially purchased this Philips Hue starter kit, I had it in my head that this was nothing more than an expensive novelty to add to my Amazon Echo (pretty sure my wife thought the same thing!) I'm a techie and love this kind of stuff! So, I was super excited when the package arrived. I immediately opened it all up, installed the bulbs into the 2 lamps in the living room and hooked up the Hue bridge. After downloading the app from the Play store, I fired her up. It was a very simple process. Check it out, I can control the lights from my phone! Sweet! Next, I opened the Alexa app and connected the bulbs. I named the simply \"Living Room 1\" and \"Living Room 2\" with a group containing both called... wait for it... \"Living Room\". So, now, I can control them individually or as a group with my voice! RAD! Expensive? Yes. Novelty? Probably. Totally awesome? Um, yes!\n\nThe app...\nThe official Hue app is, a little lacking. I feel the interface could use some polish and some functionality tweaks, but, it serves it purpose. Most of the time, Alexa handles the lights... she's so nice. However, there is something that I do use on a daily basis, and that is the alarm.in my household, we all get up at about the same time. So, I have an alarm set every morning where the lights will fade on over a few minutes time until they get to full brightness. My own simulated sunrise... on my time. Also, with Alexa and the use of IFTTT (IF This Then That) I added a feature so when an Alexa timer goes off, the lights will pulse. This is handy if step out the back door, or am down the hall and don't hear the timer, I will certainly see the flashing lights.\n\nThe bulbs...\nThey look nearly identical to regular incandescent bulbs. I was a bit worried at first thinking that they may not be bright enough and that the warm tone might be too warm. Once I got them installed, I knew I made the right choice! I'm very glad I didn't go with a daylight white... the warm, more natural looking light is perfect! And, they seem a touch brighter than the previous CFL bulbs they replaced.\n\nBottom line...\nYeah, they're expensive. No, you don't really NEED them. But, they are pretty neat and handy to have. I will be expanding my Hue ecosystem soon!"}
{"Author": "Drinkster", "Date": "on April 9, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Perfect.", "Text": "Excellent. Just minutes to reliably config with static IP and all bulbs under control."}
{"Author": "Landslide", "Date": "on April 8, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "I love these lights", "Text": "I love these lights. They are very easy to setup and they truly shine when to mix them with samsung smartthings and Alexia. They truly are amazing when you pair the three together. I now have motion lights and timed lights!"}
{"Author": "SPH", "Date": "on April 7, 2016", "Stars": "3.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Not related to Hue type", "Text": "NOT RELATED TO PHILIPS HUE- they never advertised that they were but don't want others to make mistake we made. Perfectly fine bulbs but I can get for better price elsewhere. Not worth it to go through return process."}
{"Author": "George", "Date": "on April 6, 2016", "Stars": "3.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Buy the Samsung hub if you want to use any bulb you like.", "Text": "I bought this device in December despite the fact that a recent update caused 3rd party\" bulbs to stop working. Philips said they were going to push out an update to reverse this \"mistake\", but it is now April and I still cannot use my GE Link bulbs with this hub. Buy the Samsung hub if you want to use any bulb you like."}
{"Author": "John Boatman", "Date": "on March 30, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "great brightness, great responsiveness", "Text": "It's just Philips Hue. Works as advertised, great brightness, great responsiveness. I got the starter pack AND the wall switch pack. Three bulbs, one hub, one wall dimmer. Perfect setup."}
{"Author": "Greg", "Date": "on March 29, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Happy", "Text": "Works well."}
{"Author": "Amazon Customer", "Date": "on March 28, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Incredible product - very straightforward and efficient.", "Text": "I bought the Hue White Starter kit (2 white bulbs only) to try it out in my room. I thought it would be another one of those \"good to have, cool\" but not really necessary items at home but honestly I think I was WAY off.\n\nLet's start off with the convenience factor. Installation took 10 seconds. Plug in the bridge and the internet cable, put the light bulbs in as any other light bulb would be installed and you're pretty much set (some minor wi-fi connectivity steps need to be taken when you download the Hue app, etc.). Now you're set and ready to control the lights with your phone or Siri/Alexa (depending on which lady keeps you company at home). I LOVE the fact that I can get into bed, read a book and then I don't have to get up to shut lights off when I want to sleep. The lights can also be dimmed which is an added bonus: \"Hey Siri, set the mood.\" (wink wink).\n\nThe app has many different settings that you can use to your advantage - you can set automatic timers to on/off (with alarms), you can set a proximity sensor that will automatically turn lights on when you arrive and off when you leave your home, and you can set an automatic \"off\" setting after certain amount of time to shut lights off for you and save electricity. My point is, you have many different ways to control the lights that allow flexibility.\n\nI can't leave out what I think provides the best value added for me. I usually have trouble waking up in the mornings. My room is dark, cold, and my bed is comfortable. I have the Sleep Cycle app (which is also great btw!), and the app can be connected to the Hue App so that they work together. The result? The Sleep Cycle app is supposed to monitor your sleep cycle so that it wakes you up within a 30 min (you can set the timeframe) timeframe when you're coming off the deep sleep and you wake up feeling rested. Once you connect the app to the Hue lights the app will automatically start to dim the lights on within that time frame to gradually get you to come off that deep sleep prior to having the alarm go off. It's been day and night for me, literally as I'm able to get out of bed faster. That by itself is worth the cost of the product.\n\nFinally there's so many different options and additional products you can buy to combine. I plan on buying more light bulbs so I can place around my apartment (you can pretty much control all the light bulbs in your apartment with one bridge, and you can name each bulb to separately control them if you want to). You can also buy light switches if you prefer to have a button to press and control the lights. There's really no negative I can find from this, and I'm being 100% honest!! If I do come up with a negative I'll point it out.\n\nGood luck!!"}
{"Author": "Douglas Waters", "Date": "on March 27, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Five Stars", "Text": "now i dont have to tell my wife to turn off the light."}
{"Author": "XxShelbsterxX", "Date": "on March 25, 2016", "Stars": "3.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Quite easy to setup and I have enjoyed them so far", "Text": "They should make it clearer that these are not the color bulbs I ended up keeping them anyways though and just put them in my living room and bought colored one for bedroom. Quite easy to setup and I have enjoyed them so far. really makes keeping the last turned off easier and when friends and family visit its a cool trick lol."}
{"Author": "Malocclu", "Date": "on March 23, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Works like a charm.", "Text": "Very pleased with this item. Easy and flawless set up. Wife loves it."}
{"Author": "Kris Kidwell", "Date": "on March 23, 2016", "Stars": "4.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Great, but have a long ways to go.", "Text": "I like them, but they are not consistent. I bought these for use with my Amazon Echo and to turn on when I pulled up to my house. Turning on for when I pull up works maybe 60% of the time, and Echo can't communicate with them a couple times a week at least. The technology is still pretty new, but I have high hopes for it! I also have some color bulbs for my bedroom. I enjoy the color bulbs far more than I thought I would have, the red light at night makes it easier to go to sleep when my girlfriend wants to stay up."}
{"Author": "Hal", "Date": "on March 23, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Five Stars", "Text": "Worked perfect with Echo and android app"}
{"Author": "Tami C.", "Date": "on March 21, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Easy to set up.", "Text": "I purchased the Philips Hue after much research between the Hue, the Wink and the Wemo. After making my decision, I found an open box model through Amazon Prime so I was able to purchase it for almost $10 cheaper than the full price of 79.99. Until purchasing this product, I didn't realize that open box models could be made through Amazon. To my delight, upon receiving the product, I couldn't even tell that it had been opened, everything was there, directions and cords. It was fairly intuitive and easy to follow the directions given to set up. Presently I am using mine with my Echo system and love it.\n\nI have found that Hue can become confused if you turn the lights on by Siri and then attempt to turn them off using Alexa. It has had a slight learning curve to it, but nothing major and I plan on adding other bulbs soon. One disadvantage, Philips does not make a small bulb and I have one lamp that this bulb will not fit into. Also, if you are looking for plugs, Philips does not make these either."}
{"Author": "like's books", "Date": "on March 19, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Love it.", "Text": "Works well with Amazon Echo."}
{"Author": "Daniel", "Date": "on March 19, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Awesome connected lights", "Text": "Started creating my SmartHome and loved the fact this product is compatible with Apple HomeKit so I can control my devices through my iPhone and Siri. Set up was a breeze and love the features. You can create scenes within the Philips Hue app to turn on a certain set of lights (say Living Room) to a certain brightness at the touch of a button. You can also set your geo-fence so your lights turn off when you leave so you will never have to worry about \"did I leave the lights on?\" and then you can set it to turn lights on when you enter the geo-fence again (it also gives you the option to only apply this after sunset) so no more walking into a dark house."}
{"Author": "Mike in Texas", "Date": "on March 18, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Easy to Set-Up and Use; Very Pleased.", "Text": "I'm so happy I bought this ecosystem versus some of the other HomeKit light kits out there. Easy to set-up and use. I do recommend that you download and use the iConnectHue app as well as the original Philips Hue app; it has more features that you can use. If you're an Advanced HomeKit person like me, ultimately you'll want to download the \"Home\" app which allows triggers and other cool functions. FYI."}
{"Author": "Joseph Curtin", "Date": "on March 18, 2016", "Stars": "4.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "I would recommend this to any busy family", "Text": "I have been using my starter kit now for a month and the system is working really well. The lights are very responsive to the hub. I have it connected to my Amazon Echo and it is working well also. My wife loves when she has her hands full and is able to turn on a light without having to put everything down to turn on the lights. I would recommend this to any busy family. I only have 4 bulbs hooked up now, but plan on buying more for the house. I am also going to purchase the Echo Dot for other areas of the house."}
{"Author": "Carl", "Date": "on March 18, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Five Stars", "Text": "Love it! Makes me love the echo even more!"}
{"Author": "Leigh", "Date": "on March 17, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Five Stars", "Text": "they work perfectly. I use them with an amazon echo."}
{"Author": "Jacob E. Walker", "Date": "on March 16, 2016", "Stars": "3.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Three Stars", "Text": "Works well, but the app is absolutely a UI mess."}
{"Author": "Savvy Skeptic", "Date": "on March 15, 2016", "Stars": "4.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "UPDATE: Echo Connection Problems", "Text": "I initially could not get this bridge to connect with Echo. The Hue bridge and lights worked great on their own, and Alexa worked great on her own, but the two couldn't find each other. I tried every online troubleshooting tip I could find, and went so far as to completely reset my Echo and the Hue, meaning I had to reinstall and run full setup again. No fun, and still no joy.\n\nAlexa knows that Hue bridges sometimes talk to her and sometimes don't. She apparently doesn't take it personally, but she mentions this hub by name and offers unsolicited troubleshooting tips during every random device discovery attempt, even if you have no Philips devices. According to many online forums, the 2nd gen Hue hub has been randomly having connection problems with Echo since mid-2015. Software updates and device reboots have not resolved the issue as of my purchase date.\n\nI initiated a return of this item because I bought it to specifically use with Echo; two days later while I was getting ready to pack it up and ship it back I decided to try it one last time just for the heck of it. \"Alexa, discover devices....\" And wonder of wonders, whattayaknow, \"I have located 2 connected home devices.\" Go figure! What's funny, is that Echo still finishes up with the standard message that if you were trying to discover Philips Hue bulbs, you might want to press the button on the Hub and try discovery again. The fact that she says this every time, by default, even if she already found your device, tells you that this has been a frequent and widespread problem.\n\nAll I can say is that if you buy this item and it doesn't work at first, I can't explain it--and apparently neither can Amazon or Philips--but let it sit all connected and powered on for a day or two and try again. They might suddenly start to click. From what I've read, and now experienced, it seems like these two tend to randomly hook up when the mood strikes just right. Once my Echo found my bulbs, they work perfectly together....so far, anyway. I did see some reviews/online comments that mentioned these two randomly losing their connection, too. I guess time will tell if they stay faithful to each other or drift apart.\n\nThere is also some question of whether this hub will continue to be compatible with any 3rd party devices/bulbs; apparently Philips plans to change the software so that their hub only works with their products. I hope that is not the case, but we'll see. In the meantime, Hue and Alexa are happily paired and making beautiful light and music together. So far the relationship has been worth a little work. Hope this helps if anyone else bought this to use with their Echo."}
{"Author": "Brett East", "Date": "on March 13, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Yes voice and tablet/phone light control is pretty great but beyond that is dimming lights while laying ...", "Text": "Got an Amazon Echo? Then it's a no brainer to get some automated lights. Yes voice and tablet/phone light control is pretty great but beyond that is dimming lights while laying on the couch or setting a timer to turn lights on when your alarm clock rings. If you're on a budget the \"White bulbs\" are OK but you will be REALLY happy with every color bulb add. (or buy the color bulb starter pack to start with).\n\nYou CAN use GE Link bulbs with the Hue bridge, so that makes \"white\" bulbs as cheap as $15 (as of today). but I think the Philips bulbs ($23) are better if you want to be able to turn them really low. In time all my primary lights will be color bulbs and the whites will find there way to the garage, laundry and spare room as even if you don't light your house like a techno bar the ability to make the color bulb turn true white (unlike the yellow/orange \"white\" bulbs), and the subtle blues, reds, and greens can really compliment different parts of your home."}
{"Author": "Joel Adler", "Date": "on March 11, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Five Stars", "Text": "Very happy with the performance and recommend it to others"}
{"Author": "Amazon Customer", "Date": "on March 10, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Five Stars", "Text": "These work great, tho the bulbs are a little greener in color temp then a traditional incandescent bulb"}
{"Author": "Thomas G. Hanlin", "Date": "on March 9, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "I love them. A+++ would buy again. Will buy more!", "Text": "These are most wonderful. There's nothing like having automated dimmable lights, and efficient LED lights at that. I look forward to getting more in the future.\n\nThey just screw into any ordinary lamp socket and work as you'd expect. The light quality is excellent. The bulbs are a bit large and may not be suited for all lamps.\n\nI'll admit the price is a little disturbing. However, these should hopefully last for many years to come."}
{"Author": "Coghan", "Date": "on March 8, 2016", "Stars": "3.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "It's ok considering a starter kit", "Text": "The hub has to stay plugged into the router to work. Also the bulbs are quite dim. They say 60W equivalent but it's more like 40W light output. That said, it wasn't hard to get working. Took a minute to figure out I had to name the group of lights in the Alexa app in order to turn them on or off at the same time. This is my first foray into wireless home management and it wasn't a total waste of money by any means. It does work. But it is less than perfect for sure. Update 3/16/17 Interestingly the first one just burned out, almost exactly one year to the day after purchase. Until a couple days ago both bulbs continued to work correctly. I reiterate that the bulbs are very dim though. I put a regular 40w bulb directly beside and the light output is almost identical. Defo not 60w equivalent. I have decided a better route is to get the Alexa controlled switches and use whatever bulb I want to use. Let there be light."}
{"Author": "Daddio814", "Date": "on March 8, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "I love them.", "Text": "I'm a nerd, I love them."}
{"Author": "Chris Youngblood", "Date": "on March 8, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Easy", "Text": "Very easy to set up and synched it straight to my Echo. I have also added lights and am really enjoying this product!"}
{"Author": "Killala", "Date": "on March 7, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Like it, like it.", "Text": "Works well, use the light through the Amazon Echo &IF, very easy setup."}
{"Author": "Amazon Customer", "Date": "on March 7, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Easy to set up", "Text": "Exactly what I needed. Easy to set up. Works with Amazon echo perfectly."}
{"Author": "Clinton D. Hart", "Date": "on March 5, 2016", "Stars": "4.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Serious cool factor.", "Text": "4 stars because of the price. These can be much more affordable.\n\nFirst the safty factor. These bulbs do not get very hot. After an hour being on I could hold them in my hand. This is important for long life and safety from catching fire.\n\nThese support 3rd party apps and there are some really cool ones.\n\nBottom line there is some really serious cool factor here. But they are expensive."}
{"Author": "Beard", "Date": "on March 1, 2016", "Stars": "4.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "So far so good! Easy to set up", "Text": "So far so good! Easy to set up. I did misread the description when purchasing. I thought this was the RGBW bulbs:(. But I had plenty of options with these bulbs. I have one In my Office Lamp, Foyer, Porch(covered) and Daughters Room! All work great. I do have some control/settings issues via the App, but being new to the game, Im not sure if its User Error or the Development. Overall, a good product if your after giving your home an intelligence upgrade!"}
{"Author": "Jenn Murray", "Date": "on March 1, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "awesome!!", "Text": "Great lighting system...works great with Echo!!"}
{"Author": "Amazon Customer", "Date": "on February 28, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Super easy to use", "Text": "Super easy to use. I connected this in a matter of minutes. The app was hung up on updating it but I closed it and reopened it and saw no issues. Amazon Echo with Alexa integrates very easily with this product."}
{"Author": "Lenny", "Date": "on February 25, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Surprisingly easy to set up, and a wealth of features to explore (with updates after 3 weeks of use)", "Text": "Update : after 3 weeks, I'm even more impressed with this than I was initially. What impressed me : availability of physical switches / dimmers, reliability, a REST interface to the bridge, and a fairly active developer community.\n\nI had a Belkin WeMo light kit that also works over ZigBee. It was convenient, it was wonderful. Then one day it decided to stop working and nothing I did managed to coax it back. Hopefully this one works better.\n\nThere are some major differences between this and the Belkin. First, the Philips requires a wired Ethernet connection. I was quite surprised by this, but I actually prefer wired Ethernet. They can be a lot more reliable. Philips also does not require you to create an account - although there are advantages to creating one. More on this later.\n\nI downloaded the Android app, launched it, and plugged in the bridge. It took almost a minute to start up. The app immediately asked me to update the firmware. That took another 5 minutes.\n\nOnce update was completed, the app showed me the two light bulbs, already registered with the bridge - nice and convenient. It showed them as unreachable, however. No surprise - I haven't plugged them in yet. I screwed them into lamp sockets, turned on the switch to those sockets, and the hub detected them as online quickly.\n\nWith the app, you can control the bulbs individually, or as part of a scene. There were some pre-defined scenes, and you can create new ones. For example, a scene could set both bulbs to 50% brightness. Or it could turn one on and the other off. You can also set timers to have the lights turn on / off at specified times.\n\nSo what are the other features? Create a Philips Hue account, and additional features become available. Without an ID, you need to be on the same network as the bridge in order to control the lights. With an ID, you can do it from anywhere. You can also control the lights through IFTTT. For example, you can have the lights blink if you receive an email.\n\nAs with any other ZigBee Light Link systems, there are some limitations, and there are work-arounds. In order for the light to be controllable from your phone (or through Apple HomeKit, Amazon Echo, IFTTT or timer), the socket it is screwed into needs to be left on. You can turn it off from the wall - no power, no light - but you will then need to turn it on from the wall. Fortunately, turning on power to a bulb that has been powered off always puts it to max brightness, so if the bridge fails (like it did with my Belkin WeMo) you can still use it like a normal light bulb.\n\nZ-Wave wall switches works the way regular wall switches do, and you can control it both from the wall switch as well as from remote controls or a gateway. Installation, however, is a much more tedious process, unlike these lights. To install a smart light, you screw it into the socket, and you're done. Philips appear to have wall mountable switches that I need to look into.\n\nThere are many things I'd like to explore that I haven't had a chance to yet, such as their API. I will update this review when I do. In the meantime, I already like this better than the WeMo kit I had.\n\nUpdate 1 : Added two GE Link BR30. Reset them according to instructions found online (off for 3 seconds, on for 3 seconds, repeat cycle 5 times until bulb dims and blink once). Adding was very straightforward. Bulbs do seem unresponsive sometimes, especially if commands are issued rapidly. For example, if sliding it down to turn off, it might get stuck at partially dimmed. Need to explore this in greater detail. With Philips bulbs there are no issues.\n\nUpdate 2 : Attempted to add the WeMo bulbs. Managed to reset them according to Belkin's instructions, but was unable to connect it to the bridge.\n\nUpdate 3 : The bridge has a REST interface, meaning it is very easy to develop for it. You don't need a Philips Hue account for this. Documentation is quite good and libraries in different programming languages are available.\n\nUpdate 4 : Philips Hue Dimmer Switch - this is what will make the system complete. Works great - read my review on the switch if you're interested. I find that it works better if I have it controlling a scene rather than a bulb, even if the scene only contains one bulb, if I want \"On\" to always turn a bulb to 100% brightness instead of previous level before it was turned off."}
{"Author": "Tom E G", "Date": "on February 25, 2016", "Stars": "2.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Awesome when they work, but extremely frustrating", "Text": "These lights are convenient. Great for times when I\u2019m on another floor of the house and realize I forgot to turn a light off or creating schedules. However since I bought these in the beginning of February I have had issues where the Bridge won\u2019t connect to the internet and I can\u2019t connect to my lights. To fix I have to unplug the Bridge and plug back in. Especially annoying if you want to control lights away from your home. The unplugging and plugging back in fix usually helps for four or five days, but then the connection drops again. I bought these a few weeks ago from Home Depot and will be utilizing their 90 day return policy. It\u2019s not worth when it only works certain times."}
{"Author": "G. Tyacke", "Date": "on February 23, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Five Stars", "Text": "Easy to setup, and was easy to integrate with our Amazon Echo."}
{"Author": "Mmm", "Date": "on February 23, 2016", "Stars": "4.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Nice basic starter kit", "Text": "This is a very nice basic kit to get you going. It would be a great entry point for someone coming in the Apple Homekit for the first time.\n\nAdditional bulbs are cheaper at the box hardware stores.\n\nYou can also add the Hue light switches and other accessories to the bridge, but my house is older and doesn't have the third wire so I have to do all home automation through bulbs/peanut devices.\n\nThe ability to remotely manage your lights is great. When you're on vacation, you can set random schedules, or manually come in and adjust the lights. Remember this is a white light kit only, and there is no color to the bulbs. Some of the other Philips products do have color changing LED bulbs.\n\nInitially I set this up with the included hub. I will try removing the hub and tying directly into my SmartThings V2 hub when I get a chance. I doubt that it would be an issue, and that's probably how I'll leave the system, having one less hub is one less breaking point."}
{"Author": "Psdenno", "Date": "on February 22, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Nice to be able to control lights and set timers ...", "Text": "Arrived on time and works well. Nice to be able to control lights and set timers with my phone."}
{"Author": "Super Mum", "Date": "on February 22, 2016", "Stars": "4.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "One star lost for Siri/Apple HomeKit issues, other than that, I LOVE the Hue system...", "Text": "This is my second Philips 455303 Hue White Starter A19 Kit, 2nd Generation. I purchased the first in October 2015 and, the second, I obtained via the Vine Program last month. The main reason I invested in the Hue system was due to its Apple HomeKit integration. Unfortunately, this has been the biggest let down of the Hue system. Fortunately, there is so much I love about Hue I am willing to forgive (and hope that Apple and/or Philips figures this out eventually).\n\nPros:\n\n- Lights go on and off via app and switch instantaneously. Absolutely no lag and that is a beautiful thing.\n\n- In several rooms of my house, I have pull-string lights. Yes, I live in a charming little village in a \"darling\" old house but the reality is, there is nothing charming about pull-string lights after 15 years. Walking blindly into a pitch black room at night grasping around for a string while stubbing toes is infuriating after a couple months and crazy-making after 15 years. Adding Philips Hue lights and Philips 458158 Hue Dimmer Switch - Frustration Free Packaging to the kitchen and bedrooms has made my life so much better! (No exaggeration.) I just stuck (via included magnet and purchased 3M tape, depending on the room) the switches by the entrances to each room and now I have an easy (and painless way) to turn on/off or dim the lights. This in-and-of-itself is the reason I truly love the Hue system. My toes and shins are happy campers and there is no need to go hunt down my iPhone to use the app to turn off/on or dim a light.\n\n- As for the included white Hue bulbs, I love that I can tailor the warmth and coolness depending on mood, headache, or the need to have a bright blinding bulb to stay super alert and focused.\n\n- I love the \"fun\" Hue add-ons in addition to the more functional pieces of the Hue ecosystem. Particularly, we enjoy the Philips 800284 Hue Lightstrip Plus, 2nd Generation which lights up the back of my entertainment center and makes us feel like we are at a movie theater and, my personal favorite, The Bowl of Light AKA Philips 798835 Hue Go Personal Wireless Lighting which is a great, and safe, alternative to lighting a candle. Of course we also adore our Philips 456186 Hue White and Color Ambiance Extension A19 Bulbs, 2nd Generation but find we don't use them in color as much as we do in plain white (which is just so darn functional in everyday life).\n\nCons:\n\n- While the app and wall switch are flawless, there are many hiccups with HomeKit integration. Siri has plenty of problems turning off and on lights/scenes and I am so tired of hearing him (yes, my Siri is a he) telling me he can't \"do that right now\" or \"can't reach all my devices at this time\" or \"hmmm, I'm having trouble enabling your XXXXX scene, try checking your devices\" or the other phrases that haunt me on a regular basis. While I have no idea if this is on Philips or Apple's end, this is the main reason I purchased the bridge back in October and has been the biggest disappointment thus far. While I purchased Hue for Siri integration, it was so that I could solve the pull-string light problem mentioned above. However, once Philips introduced the Philips 458158 Hue Dimmer Switch - Frustration Free Packaging the Siri issues weren't nearly as bothersome and, frankly, I like the wall dimmer switch better as my phone is often in an inconvenient location and the switch is always on the wall, right where I, and company who come to visit, can always find it.\n\n- The final nit-picky con is that, prior to purchasing the Hue system, I had a dozen or more Zigbee bulbs that were compatible with the Hue system. However, every so often Hue chooses not to support them... then to support them... then not to support them. While I understand that Hue wants people to purchase their bulbs (both to make money and to be able to make a reliable system that their customer service is able to support as a whole) I am slowly purchasing Hue bulbs to replace the other Zigbee bulbs so I don't have days where the non-Phillips bulbs work/don't work."}
{"Author": "Stephanie Sullivan", "Date": "on February 22, 2016", "Stars": "4.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "(UPDATED Jul 20, 2017) Great Alexa Integration For Philips Devices, New Install Super Easy, Upgrade From Gen1 MAY Be a Pain", "Text": "The 2nd generation of my old 1st generation Philips 453761 Hue Lux 60W A19 LED Starter Kit. I like my old kit and it integrated with my Amazon Echo (Alexa) and recently my 1st generation FireTV (now with Alexa). The new generation adds Apple HomeKit compatibility and has different bulbs that are a bit more than 10% brighter.\n\nLike the first gen hub you can control your lights from anywhere through the Philips Hue app. This generation has all the features of the older one and just adds to them.\n\nIntegration with Alexa/Echo is great for Philips bulbs and switches. I have never been able to get 3td party bulbs or switches to work with Alexa using the Philips Hue hub even though most work fine with the Hue app! If you want a all-Philips environment for Alexa voice control it's great but another hub might be a better choice for Alexa control of bulbs and switches from other manufacturers.\n\nI'll use this review to compare the first and second generations. I liked my first gen kit and I like the new one but it's not all rose petals.\n\nIN THE BOX:\nThe contents of the new kit are much like the older one:\n+ Hue square bridge (the older model had a round bridge)\n+ 2 Philips 455311 Hue White Extension A19 Bulbs (Old kit had Philips 433714)\n+ Power adapter (2A output compared to 800ma on previous)\n+ About 3ft LAN cable (same as the older one)\n+ Various getting started and marketing paperwork (similar to the older)\n\nThe biggest changes are the new bulbs are slightly brighter, run hotter and are shaped more like incandescent bulbs. The hub is square, requires a little more power, and now supports Apple HomeKit. The power adapter is bigger and I had to move around plugs on my power strip so it would fit.\n\nINSTALLATION:\nWarning: I wanted to see what a new install would be like, but if you are upgrading I suggest pairing your bulbs to your old hub first, then migrating your configuration to the new hub. I wanted to experience a first-time installation for this review and didn't do that, and oh what a PAIN!\n\nNew Install:\nIf Installing the new gen kit as a new first time installation, it is wicked easy! Install the hue app (I had it installed on my iPhone already), create or login to your account, discover the bridge, search for new devices. If the included bulbs are on they will auto pair. Easy Peasy! I did this first.\n\nUpon installation I was asked if I wanted to add the device to my home (Apple HomeKit)., This is new with this generation and nice to see and be able to use Siri as an additional voice control channel to Alexa.\n\nUpgrade Install:\nInstalling as an upgrade was not so nice.for me as I had already setup this hub as a new install. During setup the app *really* wanted to migrate my old hub's configuration to the new hub - the dialog in the app leads me to believe that they can not coexist so nicely. In the process of the upgrade the new bridge's configuration was cleared, the old hub's devices migrated to the new one. Then the old hub's configuration was then cleared.\n\nDuring the upgrade I was warned I would have to re-pair any previously pair devices or bulbs like those included in the kit. When I went to pair those nice new bulbs. What was previously seamless and easy before became a frustrating task. I finally had to resort to manually pairing the kit bulbs manually by using their serial numbers then doing them one at a time. It was an annoying pain that took several tries.\n\nI was also able to pair a new Cree Connected 60W A19 LED Light Bulb manually. The trick with the Cree is to make sure you start the manual paring immediately after turning on the bulb. The timing is very close with the Cree and it took me two tried to get it paired. This was the same experience as with the old Hue hub.\n\nOnce things were paired I was able to mate the new Hue hub with my Echo and Alexa happily turned my hue bulbs on and off, but would NOT recognize or control any of my Cree light bulbs connected to the Hue hub. The Hue app worked them perfectly. This is the same as the older bridge and still a rather annoyingly closed system.\n\nIN OPERATION:\nHomeKit compatibility is a plus for Apple users and gives a voice option other than the Echo (my preference). I've only just tried it a little so far. Alexa (Echo) is my home voice control preference.\n\nThe new bulbs are about 10% brighter and that's just noticeably brighter to my eye. The new bulbs are shaped more like incandescent A19 bulbs than the older style Hue Lux bulbs. Like the older Lux bulbs these are fairly heavy bulbs and may not be appropriate for some track lighting or swing-arm lighting fixtures. The Cree Connected bulbs are only a little heavier than incandescent bulbs and probably a better choice for more delicate fixtures.\n\nThe bulbs also seem to run hotter than the old ones. In an open socket the base got uncomfortably hot to the touch. In a similar situation the older bulbs got warm but never what I would call hot. I am concerned running hotter means a shorter life.\n\nSpeaking of shorter life, one of the two bulbs failed with between 1 and 2 hours of operating time. I turned it off and then it would never turn on again. A bummer for sure and I hope an anomaly.\n\nQuality of light from the new bulbs is not much different from the old ones. The lighting pattern does not seem much different even with the more round shape.\n\nIN CONCLUSION:\nFor my environment where I am using the Hue app and Alexa/Echo the new generation offers little new. For HomeKit users this will offer new possibilities. If I had to pay for this upgrade I would have passed. If I were buying for the first time I'd get this new kit.\n\nFor new users setup could not be much easier, migrating from an old hub may be frustrating as it was for me. Maybe if you never pair the new bulbs or pair them with your old hub before migrating you will have a better experience than I did.\n\nPhilips Hue system seems to only begrudgingly support non-Philips devices. Echo can't control my Cree bulbs I connected through the Hue bridge. They work fine through the Wink hub with Alexa. Late in 2015 Philips released a firmware update that prevented pairing of non-Philips products, but quickly reversed that decision. Bottom line is this: If you want to stick with Philips I think the Hue is a great choice, but if you want a more open system select another option.\n\nAll things considered I think the Hue White Starter is a 3.5 star experience. 4 stars for a new user, 3 stars for a upgrade. No half stars so I'll give it the benefit of the doubt and 4 stars it is.\n\nUPDATE: Jul 20, 2017:\nIn the year and a half since Feb 2016 the control hub has operated flawlessly, but one of the two bulbs stopped working. I didn't bother Philips about this as I had a spare bulb from another purchase. These newer bulbs do run hotter than the older ones so maybe it was heat related?\n\nI use the Hue system for controlling white lights. I don't use their color lighting and all my lights are plain old white dimming ones. The hub still does not support non-phillips devices with Alexa and that's a serious shortcoming for me. If I were an all Phillips household it would be great. Given I'm not, if I were to start over I would probably use a another zigbee hub that supports other branded devices with Alexa like my Cree brand smart bulbs, for example.\n\nIf you want great color lighting control with scenes I think this is a 5 star starter where you can add color lighting later. If you want to use non-philips branded devices it's probably 3 stars because Alexa control isn't supported."}
{"Author": "David S.", "Date": "on February 21, 2016", "Stars": "4.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "I do however think that someday I will change my mind so I am happy with the product", "Text": "Works well, in hind sight I do not need to turn light bulbs on and off with anything this sophisticated. A light timer would do the same more or less. I do however think that someday I will change my mind so I am happy with the product."}
{"Author": "Bass Cadet", "Date": "on February 20, 2016", "Stars": "4.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "+ \u00bd *: Great for light automation", "Text": "As far as automating lights, this set is very easy to set up and use. I use the Android app and had no problems setting up an on/off program. The app also has a randomize function that turns lights on or off within a 30 minute period. It has timers in addition to alarms. Integration with an Amazon Echo is also simple and effective. I also like that Hue lights can be used like regular switched light bulbs.\n\nOne big advantage this system has over the WeMo is the ability to dim lights. The dimmer functions work well and the preset scenes are handy for quickly setting light levels. I am considering buying some Hue lights with color ambiance. The only thing holding me back and seemingly the only negative about Philips Hue lighting is cost."}
{"Author": "D. T.", "Date": "on February 20, 2016", "Stars": "3.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Great hardware. Bad app..", "Text": "The bulbs work fine and connect to the hub easily. You sort of need a physical dimmer switch as well because you aren't going to use your phone every time you want to turn the lights on and off when you walk in the room. (You have to leave the light switch on all the time for the app to be able to control them)\n\nI got this so the lights would turn on in the morning gradually to wake me up. The alarm feature in the Philips app wouldn't work for a while, possibly due to some time zone bug, but I got it working eventually by playing with it.\n\nThe app for creating the timers and programming the lights is really bad. Horrible usability and design. For instance, you can't group the lights into rooms, so you have to control them individually or manually create scenes for each possible scenario. According to news Philips is redesigning the app from the ground up and it is currently in beta. When that happens hopefully these will become more useful."}
{"Author": "Brian_In_Fargo", "Date": "on February 20, 2016", "Stars": "4.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "... have this connected to my Amazon Echo and it's fun coming into a room barking orders without it getting ...", "Text": "I have this connected to my Amazon Echo and it's fun coming into a room barking orders without it getting all sensitive about my tone."}
{"Author": "fatmav", "Date": "on February 18, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Two 2700K 800 lumen dimmable LED bulbs that can be controlled by a smartphone", "Text": "Courtesy of the Amazon Vine program, I have received a \u201cPhilips 455303 Hue White Starter A19 Kit, 2nd Generation\u201d. This item comes in a so-called frustration-free packaging, which is essentially a bare brown box (not retail). The item includes a network bridge, its power supply unit, an ethernet cable, and two \u201cwhite\u201d lightbulbs.\n\nSetting up is easy but it is important that you have an available ethernet port on your wireless router. I power up the bridge, connect it to the router using the included the ethernet cable, and then install and launch the Philips Hub app on my Android phone. Assuming your phone and the bridge are on the same network, the app will find the bridge automatically and ask you to press the (only) button the bridge to confirm. In my case, I managed to connect to my bridge in well under five minutes from opening the box.\n\nThe lightbulbs emits 800 lumen, which is about a 60W bulb. The color temperature is 2700K, which means it is like an incandescent light. Now this is really a yellowish light, so please be alert when you buy this. I don't know why they call this \u201cwhite\u201d. (I would consider 5000K white.)\n\nThe lightbulbs are dimmable, and you can use the app to set a timer (turn off) or an alarm (turn on). The alarm timing information is stored in the bridge, and therefore it does not need an internet connection. (I tested this by disconnecting the ethernet.)\n\nFeature-wise, Philips delivers all the promises and I have to give this a 5/5. However, honestly I am a bit underwhelmed with this kit for its price and performance ratio: it really does not do much other than dimming, and Philips is asking quite a bit more if you want color bulbs. The only redeeming feature is that the bulbs are LED and this kit includes two LED bulbs. However, considering that the traditional (non-smart) LED bulbs are so much cheaper, I find it a little hard for an apartment-living person like me to justify the current cost of this kit unless you like walking to your smartphone to change the light setting than to walk to a light switch."}
{"Author": "Picky", "Date": "on February 18, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Amazing Voice Command with Alexa", "Text": "Works great with Alexa - Getting Spoiled, never knew what I was missing."}
{"Author": "George McAdams", "Date": "on February 17, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "A Very Good Lighting System that Will Add Value to Your Life", "Text": "UPDATED (2016/04) See End of Review: For 35 years, I have had lightning that works by remote control, and have enjoyed being able to control the lighting and some appliances in my apartment or house with a remote. With the advent of the smart phone, our world has changed.\n\nFirst of all, these bulbs are great! The Hue system is very good, although trying to find a decent set of instructions for installation was difficult. Finally, the price of the bulbs that you can use is getting more reasonable each year.\n\nThe Phillips Hue White Starter A19 Kit contains 2 LED bulbs that emit 800 lumens of cool light (which is slightly above what we used to get from a 60 watt bulb), a WiFi Bridge, an adapter for the bridge, a short CAT5 cable for hooking the bridge to your wireless modem, and two HUE small pamphlets which have almost no instructions. The first pamphlet tells you to go to (...) to learn how to use the Hue lights. The second pamphlet tells you three steps to follow, in 20 languages. While the instructions one finds on the Phillips site are not specifically designed for these bulbs, there are some instructions that are very similar.\n\nIf you go to the Phillips site, and select the link \"Friends of Hue\" at the top, this will take you to their partnering page on Apple Homekit. If you scroll down to the bottom of that page, you will find instructions for using Siri, which are the same for these lights, instructions on setting-up Apple Homekit, which are very similar. Look over those to familiarize yourself to how these lights work. One thing I have noticed with the lights, if I enter the room where I have them plugged into lamp that turn-on and turn-off by the light switch, and I find them off. If I move flick the light switch back and forth, the lights come on.\n\nThe three steps they tell you about are: 1) Power Your Light Source(s), 2) Plug in the Hue bridge and connect to your WiFi router, and 3) Download the Hue app and follow the instructions.\n\nOnce you do these, your lights will work.\n\nUPDATE (2016/04) have my Hue lights installed in lamps placed on bedside tables in the bedroom. These lamps are placed in the electrical circuit that operates from a light switch on the wall at the entrance to the bedroom. On top of this, the light switch at the entrance to the bedroom is one that has a light in the switch that glows when the switch is turned off, and it is part of a two-way switch that has its paired switch on the wall next to the bed (which we do not use). By doing this, these lights now have these extra features if the lights in the lamps are turned \"on\" and left \"on:\"\n\n1) If I, or my wife, enters the bedroom and find the light switch switched down and glowing, we know the lights are off, and switching that switch at the entrance to the bedroom \"on\" with turn the two Hue lights \"on\" IF the Hue lights were switched on at each lamp when either the light switch at the bedroom entrance was switched \"off\" (by this I mean turning the lamps \"on\" and leaving them \"on\" as I said at the end of the previous paragraph) or we used the Hue app to turn the lights \"off.\"\n\n2) If we enter the bedroom and find the switch at the entrance to the bedroom switched \"on\" and the Hue lights in the lamps \"off\" (which means the Hue lights were turned 'off\" with the Hue app, not the light switch), switching the switch at the entrance to the bedroom \"off\" and then \"on\" will make the Hue lights turn themselves \"on.\" Thus, if my wife, or I, don't have our phones with us, we don't need our phones or the app to turn \"on\" the lights. When we leave the bedroom, we can turn \"off\" the light switch at the door, but doing so means we cannot turn \"on\" the lights using the app until the bedroom entrance light switch is turned \"on.\"\n\nI hope this doesn't sound more confusing than it needs to be. At this point, I could go into a lot of variables here that could happen, but it will just complicate things further. The good that comes out of the two points I have listed above is that if either my wife or I go to the bedroom and we find the two lamps \"off,\" we can turn them \"on\" without having to activate the lamps using the telephone app. For my wife this was a selling point that allowed me to install them, even though it meant there was one more electronic gadget in her life. She seems to think, sometime, I have electronic things in my life to keep her from using them, and we all know that is not true."}
{"Author": "Ryan S.", "Date": "on February 17, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "download app and you're good to go", "Text": "Literally the definition of plug and play! Plug in power and Ethernet for bridge, download app and you're good to go. Have already added multiple switches and bulbs and it's a breeze."}
{"Author": "D.W", "Date": "on February 17, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Perfect companion for Alexa", "Text": "I love this so much. I was worried about the temperature of the light compared to other fluorescent and LED bulbs that put off terrible blue tinted light. The light from these is PERFECT ! I can hardly distinguish between them and the light from a real incandescent bulb.\n\nFast too. Dragging the dimming slider in the hue app, and I could see the changes in real time. No visible lag. Wow !\n\nIf you have an Echo or FireTV, the voice controls are very responsive too. Lights respond faster than Alexa can say \"ok\". I saved the two bulbs into a group called lights. \"Alexa lights on\" and \"Alexa dim the lights\" and more! This is the future!\n\nI also purchased with a Hue Dimmer Switch because I wanted physical controls in addition to the app, the geofencing, and the voice commands. The switch was easy to pair in the hue app and link the switch to both bulbs.\n\nBeyond simple on / off commands, here is my ranking of the multiple methods of controlling these lights:\n- The best is the hue app. Has the most control and the scenes are straight-forward.\n- Second is the physical Dimmer Switch, a couple of presses on bright/dim buttons and you can get the mood you want to quick.\n- Last are the voice controls, dimming presets are not available so you find yourself saying over and over \"Alexa dim the lights\" to get down to the level you want."}
{"Author": "Bradley Nelson", "Date": "on February 15, 2016", "Stars": "4.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Great product, but way too expensive", "Text": "I guess I'm coming at a product like this from the perspective of cost. The whole Hue system is so expensive for what it is. The idea is cool and convenient, but I can't get over paying $20 for a light bulb. For that price, I'll just get up and walk across the room. And it seems you can't use other bulbs with their products. So, it's really cool technology and works really well with HomeKit. It's very well designed. The bulbs are LED bulbs but obviously controllable via Hue. This starter kit is a good way to get into using this system because you get two standard bulbs and can add more as you go.\n\nUntil this system is more open to non-proprietary bulbs, though, I'm not sure I'll be using it."}
{"Author": "Jerry Palmerino", "Date": "on February 15, 2016", "Stars": "4.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Works Great, but Replacment Bulbs Could Be Expensive", "Text": "I have been a Belkin Wemo user for a couple of years, so I approached Hue as an alternative to Belkin Wemo. In essence, these two setups are different ways to solve the same problem: wireless control of lights\n\nWith Wemo, you plug a device into your outlet that handles the wireless connection, and you use standard light bulbs. With Hue, you plug a device into your router and it communicates with the light bulbs.\n\nThe Hue setup was quick and easy. It took just three steps:\n\n1) Plug device into router\n2) Put the heavy (relative to normal bulbs) Hue light bulbs into lights.\n3) Install the app and follow its guidance to configure Apple\u2019s Home-kit. I used my iPad to do the setup. You have to press the big button on the Hue device and then everything starts talking. (Note: There is an Android App in the Google Play Store, but I have not tested it).\n\nSetup was quick and easy. My son really enjoyed telling Siri to turn the lights on and off.\n\nI have had trouble in the past with Wemos losing their capability to talk to the Wemo app. Only time will tell if Hue has a similar issue or not.\n\nYou do have to have your light switches in the On position for Hue to work. Because I am no electrician, I do not know if this causes electrical use or not when the HUE bulbs are off, but the light switches are on.\n\nSo that\u2019s basically it. It is quick and easy and so far works reliably. The bulbs are a lot more expensive than normal bulbs, so this may be a consideration for you. You may find solutions like Wemo to be less expensive because ultimately you can use normal light bulbs."}
{"Author": "jkenn", "Date": "on February 15, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Alexa? Lights on!----\"OK\"", "Text": "Was easy to set up with Echo and works great!"}
{"Author": "Angel O. Andrews", "Date": "on February 14, 2016", "Stars": "4.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Four Stars", "Text": "Works great."}
{"Author": "WLJ", "Date": "on February 12, 2016", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Not worth it", "Text": "These bulbs work as regular light bulbs which is good since the app is unreliable. It took a really long time for the app to find the bridge, and it constantly loses its connection. It's nice to be able to adjust the brightness of my lights, but having to pull my phone out and pull up the app to do so is laborious.\n\nThe app is also limited. All you can do is turn the lights on and off and set the brightness. You have to pay extra to be able to get lighting presets, scheduling the lights to turn on automatically at a certain time, and things like that. If it costs $80, you should get these features already!\n\nThis product is overpriced, doesn't work well, and charges extra for the features that would actually be nice to have. It's not worth it."}
{"Author": "Neilbert", "Date": "on February 11, 2016", "Stars": "2.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "If it's defective out of the box, don't bother contacting Philips, just return it.", "Text": "Ordered this starter kit as a way of slowly moving into a more connected home. Unfortunately, when the package arrived, one of the two bulbs was defective - it intermittently disconnected from the network, and would not turn completely off. I contacted Philips and was told no problem, they would send out a new bulb and I could use the packaging to return the old one. Two weeks go by, no package. I call Philips again to find out what's going on. This time, I was told that the support rep had completely mischaracterized the issues in their system, and they don't do replace bulbs as they had said on the previous call, that they only send out replacements after receiving the defective bulb back... and that even if they did, they don't have any replacement bulbs available right now. Given that I've had only half of what I ordered working, I have decided to return the product.\n\nThe other bulb and the bridge work fine, and I love the concept, but will do more research before purchasing a different brand. My experience with Philips support left me with the feeling that they don't really understand how to support customers directly."}
{"Author": "Kay", "Date": "on February 10, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Get product as well as tech support", "Text": "The Hue lights system works, I can control our lights from anyplace. When the box arrived, I read the directions and quickly set it up. Initially, I was able to turn the lights on and off from anywhere in the house. I was also able to control the brightness of each light.\n\nNext, I went up the street to see if I control the light from another location. I tried both cellular to Wi-Fi and and Wi-Fi to Wi-Fi. Neither worked. At this point, I reread the directions and was at a loss. I decided to test tech-support. I sent a request via Facebook messaging outlining my challenge. The next day I called tech support and the solution was explained to me. I had misinterpreted a picture. Once I heard the solution I realized that it was my error. I should have read the directions more carefully.\n\nShortly after I talked with tech-support, I received a response to my Facebook message. Both the phone call and the Facebook response gave me the same recommendation. I followed the instructions and then went across town, tested it and it worked. The light system works well and the tech support is great. I highly recommend the hue light system."}
{"Author": "Orrin C. Judd", "Date": "on February 10, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "This package was surprisingly easy to set up and use", "Text": "This package was surprisingly easy to set up and use. Simply replace two non-dimmable bulbs in the house; turn on the lights; plug in the bridge and attach it to your router; then put the app on your Apple product.\n\nWe put one bulb in the Daughter's room--for some reason she has her lamp across the room from her bed--and one in the Oldest's room-he's away at college, but has a room at the front of the house. Now she can shut off the light from bed and we can light his room when we're away.\n\nVery cool."}
{"Author": "Amazon Customer", "Date": "on February 10, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "but so much better than the individual timers we used in the past", "Text": "This is an expensive product, but so much better than the individual timers we used in the past. We will be purchasing more!"}
{"Author": "Cori", "Date": "on February 8, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Great light bulbs", "Text": "These bulbs work great. I love being able to dim and control them remotely. They have paired up well with the wink app and I have not had any issues. As a bonus the add only bulbs are only $15 now I can replace all my bulbs cheap."}
{"Author": "Soka", "Date": "on February 8, 2016", "Stars": "4.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Good product, I almost worthy to be a 5 stars...", "Text": "I installed this Started Kit in my apartment. The installation was easy and the lights starting working with Alexa Echo right way. You can also use your phone to control the lamps. I think it is timing consuming to use the phone to turn off & on the lights since you need to go to several steps to get to the lighting. However, if you have Echo, it makes easy to control the lights and other accessories using your voice without pushing botons or switches. - I already added 2 more Phillips Hue lamps. One, is the color Ambiance A 19, and the other is the Hue 'Go\" lamp. Unfortunately, the only way to turn off / on your lamps is through your own WiFi ID that must to be connected to the bridge. I tried the 'Home Kit\" app which claims to control the Phillis Hue Lights with The Hub from the distance and it wouldn't work. I am using IFTTT to get the lights on at 6 PM even if I am not home. It is frustrating that the lights cannot turn off/on from any other WiFi system, only yours. The videos in the website makes you believe that you can do it - but you can't. This is the reason I am giving 4 starts instead of 5 at this time."}
{"Author": "Blane", "Date": "on February 8, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Philips Hue nails the Apple Homekit integration...at least in my opinion (and I'm picky)", "Text": "Let me start by saying I love Philips Hue. I currently have an Iris and (now) 4 Hue soft white light bulbs. The big change with this starter kit is the new Hue bridge which is faster and now offers Apple HomeKit support to control your lights using Siri with simple commands like \"turn on the bedroom lamp\" or \"turn off all the lights\".\n\nWhat makes this even better is the availability of 3rd party apps that Philips has embraced and even promotes to really take advantage of your Hue ecosystem. Sure there are some that might be crappy but others really have fun with everything Hue can do. I would highly recommend this to anyone starting out, and DEFINITELY recommend the bridge here: Philips 458489 Hue Bridge - Frustration Free Packaging, 2nd Generation for anyone who is using the first gen...especially if you are an iPhone user."}
{"Author": "Oliver Davis", "Date": "on February 7, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Five Stars", "Text": "Perfect home automation addition!"}
{"Author": "Thomas L. Shimko", "Date": "on February 6, 2016", "Stars": "2.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Have two in the front of the house, router ...", "Text": "Have two in the front of the house, router in the back. Side by side almost, app tells me one is on the other one is out of range, don't understand. On top of that, the lights are a pain in the butt to program"}
{"Author": "Jeanne Bourgeois\ud83d\udc2c", "Date": "on January 31, 2016", "Stars": "3.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Nice product, but weak app support...", "Text": "The ability to turn my house lights on and off while I'm away from home is really cool... too bad the app that comes with this kit is so bad. The package came with absolutely no manual at all, not even a quick start guide, but even without instructions it was very easy to set up. I downloaded the app, paired it with the wireless hub and was able to turn the lights on and off. Unfortunately, that is about all I was able to do with the kludgy app. The timer function doesn't seem to work at all, so if I'm out of the house I have to remember to turn the lights on at sunset through the app manually. There are third party apps that probably work better, but I'm not really interested in paying up to $10 to buy an app for an $80 product that can't seem to get it's app right. For the basics - turning lights on and off manually - it works fine, but that's it. I put one of the lightbulbs on my porch and the other in the bedroom - the only thing you have to remember is to leave the wall switch is flipped up so there's power running to the light.\n\nPS - Writing reviews has become an accidental hobby for me, and it always makes my day to know that people find my reviews helpful (and if not, why.) Also, if you have any questions, clarifications, or comments please feel free to leave a comment below. I usually respond pretty quickly and almost always within 24 hours."}
{"Author": "RedOneStandingBy", "Date": "on January 31, 2016", "Stars": "3.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "When at home the Philips Hue works perfectly, bulbs ...", "Text": "When at home the Philips Hue works perfectly, bulbs respond instantly, alarms turn on/off without issue, and so on. Unfortunately, I bought this for the geofencing feature which has been completely unreliable. After 2 weeks the geofencing managed to turn both light bulbs on/off twice. That's 2 times out of over 14. I now have to make sure to turn the bulbs off manually before leaving and re-enable the scene I wanted when I get home in order to have both bulbs do what they were supposed to do. There has been zero response from Philips about correcting the problems with geofencing and none of the troubleshooting available has resolved the issue. Do not buy this if you are hoping to use the geofencing feature."}
{"Author": "J. C. Carneiro", "Date": "on January 31, 2016", "Stars": "3.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Works well, I paired with echo and it really ...", "Text": "Works well, I paired with echo and it really makes life easier (turn off/on by voice, dimm etc). I just took two stars because I feel its still too overpriced for a one color light and I wish it was warmer."}
{"Author": "Ryan", "Date": "on January 29, 2016", "Stars": "4.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Cool! Use with Alexa.", "Text": "Very cool- I need to dig in a bit and learn a bit more. I use it with Amazon Echo. Alexa can't use the scenes but it can dim the lights."}
{"Author": "Domenico Bettinelli", "Date": "on January 28, 2016", "Stars": "4.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Work great when you need a lighting situation to be automated", "Text": "As an inexpensive entry into the world of remote-controlled lighting, this is a nice kit. There are still some things I wish the Hue lights would do. I wish the software allowed me to group lights into rooms or sub-sections of rooms into which I can put scenes. Also the IFTTT.com integration is very nice. I put two Hue bulbs in lights outside my front door and now my lights come on automatically at sunset and off before we go to bed. But again, because I can't group the lights, I had to make separate recipes for the left light and the right light.\n\nAnother drawback is that only those of us with smartphones configured to access the lights can control them, which means that the kids are constantly turning my lights off and leaving them inaccessible to the remote control. Plus my wife isn't convinced that she should pull out her phone, unlock it, launch the app and hit the scene button rather than just flip the light switch. I don't know if there's any easy solution to that.\n\nBut again, I think these are a great beginning of home lighting automation in the right sorts of places (the kind of lighting locations that work better with automation) and are a great way to set the mood, or save electricity by turning down the brightness when full-bright is not needed or wanted."}
{"Author": "Karen M", "Date": "on January 27, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Five Stars", "Text": "Very easy to install and the the bulbs work like a charm."}
{"Author": "J", "Date": "on January 23, 2016", "Stars": "4.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Love the system but not the iOS app", "Text": "The Hue lighting automation system is one of those things you never know you need until you try it. If you forget to turn a light off or on, just pull out your phone and do so. If your arms are full while entering a dark house, just tell your Echo to turn on the lights. If you're away from home and don't have a light timer, just turn the lights on and off from anywhere in the world. The Hue lights work via a first party app as well as through the Amazon Echo. The Echo integration is awesome. It gives true hands-free voice-controlled lighting without the need to pull out a smartphone and activate voice control beforehand. I definitely prefer it over the first-party iOS app. The app is buggy and requires the use of the iOS keychain which is also buggy. I stopped using the keychain in iOS and OSX last year after experiencing numerous sync problems caused by its bugginess, so I wasn\u2019t thrilled to be forced to use it again. It was also difficult to configure multiple handsets with the app. That\u2019s because it requires activating sharing in iOS keychain. Setting up two iPhones (my wife and I) to work with Siri voice control was a real pain. After doing so, I started encountering more issues, such as loss of contact between the iOS app and bridge. Overall, the iOS app is just clumsy and painful to set up and use if you have all but the most basic of needs.\n\nThankfully, the system works wonderfully easy with the Amazon Echo. Setup was a night and day difference from the iOS app. I simply asked Alexa to discover my devices, paired the bridge and created a new light group within the Echo App. Just like that, we had voice activated lighting. It is literally that simple and far easier than the Hue iOS app. We now almost exclusively use Alexa to turn off, turn on and dim the lights. The Echo responds instantly and I\u2019ve had no loss of connection yet between the Echo and the bridge. Best of all, the entire family can now use the Echo instantly and I\u2019m no longer forced to deal with the headaches caused by the Hue iOS app and iOS keychain. That doesn't render the app useless. Despite awesome localized performance, the Echo is only good over wifi and for basic commands (on, off, dim). If you want off network remote control, the ability to access several different lighting profiles, or the ability to control lighting from your smartphone (for instance if you're upstairs or downstairs and outside of the range of the Echo's hearing) you'll need the Hue app.\n\nThe bridge requires a direct ethernet cabled connection to the router. It is not a stand-alone wireless device. If, like me, you have an inaccessible or awkwardly placed router it may pose an issue. I had to get creative to connect the bridge to my router which is inside my foyer coat closet courtesy of a ridiculous Verizon rule requiring all new routers be connected directly to the ONT via ethernet.\n\nThe lights included with the starter kit have a warm color temperature similar to old-fashioned incandescent bulbs. They are not a cooler white temperature as the name may have you believe. Phillips offers a wide variety of bulbs and lights for the kit. If I didn't already own a Philips wake up light, I'd definitely consider buying the Phoenix lamp. App aside, this system is awesome so far and I can\u2019t wait to add new lights within the upcoming weeks to make the entire house and outside lights all smart controlled. Hopefully, the app gets its act together to make the entire bundle perfect."}
{"Author": "Juniorverse", "Date": "on January 23, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Works great with my Echo, IFTTT, SmartThings hub, Harmony remote, and a ton of third party apps", "Text": "I have been using Hue bulbs (color and white) for about a year now and I love them so much. I use them with my Echo for voice-controlled lighting, and IFTTT and my SmartThings hub for automating lights based on time of the day and a bunch of other events.\n\nThese bulbs are easy to set up. You plug in the hub, use the app to search for new lights and if they are close enough, the bulbs will be found. If not, you can enter a serial number printed on the bulbs and the app will find them if your hub is too far away from your bulb. You can then control them using the Hue app or any number of third-party Hue apps available on Android or iOS. You can create groups or rooms so it is easier to control multiple lights at once.\n\nIf you want to get really fancy with your lights, try IFTTT, Samsung SmartThings Hub, 2nd Generation, Harmony remotes, or the Amazon Echo.\n\nUsing IFTTT, you can automate your lights based on a ton of conditions and events. Want to turn your lights on when rain is detected in your area? Yup, you can do that. Want to flash your lights when you get a new e-mail? You can do that, too. And it's free.\n\nSmartThings allows you to integrate these bulbs into your home automation network for controlling the bulbs with inexpensive Z-wave remotes, or turning them on when smoke is detected by your Z-wave smoke detector. SmartThings picks up the names that you give the bulbs (Living Room Couch) so they are easy to integrate into your events.\n\nSome Harmony remotes, like the Logitech Harmony Elite Remote Control (915-000256), will allow you to control these bulbs, too. It works great with my Elite and picks up the names that I give the bulbs in the Hue app. I can turn off these bulbs when I hit \"watch a movie\" on my remote.\n\nHue bulbs are expensive, but it is because of how many other things you can integrate them with. If you are a programmer, you can even easily control them in .Net, Python, and other languages.\n\nThese bulbs rock. And if you don't mind spending a bit more, consider the colored Hue bulbs or other Hue products like the lightstrips and spotlights."}
{"Author": "J. York", "Date": "on January 23, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "powerful and easy to setup", "Text": "I\u2019ve been using the second generation Hue bulbs for about 3 months now and have found them to work exactly as advertised. In the past I used the Hue color (\u201cambiance\u201d) bulbs but these new Hue white bulbs work just as well, albeit with fewer features.\n\nThe A19 designation means these are meant to perform as any ordinary household bulb would perform. They fit into any ordinary household light fixture. Philips claims that these are equivalent to a 60w bulb and I found the brightness and uniformity of the light are exactly what I\u2019d expect of a 60w incandescent bulb. These Hue white bulbs turn on instantly and have a pleasant color \u201cwhite\u201d color. Light comes out of all directions and once in a light fixture, there\u2019s really no way to tell that these aren\u2019t traditional incandescent bulbs. Philips does not specify a color temperature but to my eye these are 3000K when at full brightness. Not too blue, not too yellow: these are just right.\n\nInstallation requires you to screw these into your light socket but it also requires you to setup the included Hue bridge. The Hue bridge is the central brains of the Hue ecosystem and is what enables you to setup schedules on your bulbs and to remotely control them through your phone or through internet services such as IfThisThenThat.com (IFTTT).\n\nThis kit includes the late 2015 \u201csecond generation\u201d bridge (the newest one available as of January 2016). You attach the bridge to your wired home network and then install the \u201cPhilips Hue\u201d app on your phone. Using an iPhone, I ran this application and it automatically discovered my bridge and then added it to my home\u2019s wifi network. The entire process is well organized and as simple as possible. All-told, I had it up and running in only a few minutes. Once your bridge is working, you can pretty much forget about it and instead use the Philips Hue app.\n\nThe app will quickly discover any newly added bulbs and you can give them custom names so you\u2019ll know what is what. Conveniently, whenever you\u2019re editing a single bulb in the Hue app, that bulb will flash on and off.\n\nThese bulbs only support turning on and off and dimming. The dimming functionality is not that great because unlike a traditional incandescent bulb, these bulbs stay exactly the same color of \u201cwhite\u201d as they dim. This leads to an unattractive, dim white-ish color at the lowest levels. A traditional bulb would have skewed towards a pleasant orange-ish color. Still, if you want to have these behave like a 40w or a 20w bulb, the dimming functionality works perfectly.\n\nUsing the Hue app I defined a \u201cscene\u201d for my two bulbs to be fully on and fully off. I then created multiple \u201calarms\u201d for my bulbs that uses these scenes to turn them on around 5pm and off when I go to bed. I can also configure the brightness settings of the bulbs using the app. While Philips calls the feature \u201calarms\u201d, it is more of a schedule. One cool thing is that you can have the bulbs come on gradually or turn off gradually. So if you wanted to use this to wake yourself up in the morning, it wouldn\u2019t have to be a jarring brightness to start. Most importantly, the alarm functionality does not require your phone. You can power your phone off and everything will still turn on & off as you scheduled (thanks Hue bridge!).\n\nSo far I\u2019m enjoying the functionality of Hue. At the current prices, none of this is a good value. But it is easy to setup and reliability has been as rock solid as one would demand for a lightbulbs. Unlike a timer where you have to deal with circuit breakers or hiring an electrician, you can just plug these in and go. I\u2019m sold on Philips Hue and will continue to add to my system over time."}
{"Author": "Erol Esen", "Date": "on January 22, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Works seamlessly with Amazon Echo!", "Text": "It works beautifully with Amazon Echo right out of the box. For that, I can't give anything short of five-stars. Yet, Philips Hue seems to be far more interested that it works with Apple devices. There is not a single mention of Echo or Alexa in their written instruction or box cover. This makes me think it's Amazon who worked very hard to make sure Echo works seamlessly with Philips Hue lamps. Amazon has done a great job."}
{"Author": "jack", "Date": "on January 22, 2016", "Stars": "2.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Returned for LIFX bulbs", "Text": "Returned and purchase LIFX bulbs instead...no bridge needed and they are in color with white option."}
{"Author": "William A. Nolan", "Date": "on January 21, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "A good way to automate lights with either Echo or apps.", "Text": "I love automating my house, and I have been using WeMo devices and my Echos to voice control things. I liked the idea to be able to do that with individual light bulbs, and the Hue system is perfect for that. This system is very easy to install, as long as you have an open Ethernet port on your router, which I didn't, so I had to add a switch, but that is a minor problem. You just connect it to your router, plug it in, and you are set. Press the button on top when you are connecting it to your apps or to Echo, and the hub will be found. It's a good thing that it's easy, because there really aren't any instructions. Once you have it installed, you can connect 50 bulbs, both white and color. That should suffice for most reasonable homes. You can control your Hue lights with either Android or iOS apps, or, as mentioned, with Echo by voice. All in all a nice system."}
{"Author": "JoeTAZ", "Date": "on January 20, 2016", "Stars": "4.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Good start to automate your home", "Text": "I'm a sucker for this sort of product. I've always dreamed of having a fully automated home that would respond to me entering a room or barking out commands sort of like Dave talking to HAL in '2001: A Space Odyssey'. As more and more home automation products are released that dream may come true some day.\n\nSetup of this kit was simple. Plug in the hub to your router and an AC outlet, screw in the two bulbs and you're done. I downloaded the Hue app onto both my Android tablet and my Android phone. I renamed the bulbs and then set up alarms for them. For example, I set up one alarm to turn the Family Room light on at 6:00pm and another to turn it off at 11:00. You can control each bulb (and anything you add in the future) individually or all together including a number of scenes and you can dim them. For example, you can turn all of your lights on or off at the same time.\n\nAfter the setup and generally playing around I went to my Amazon Echo and simply said, \"Alexa discover devices\". I had to press the big round button on the Hue hub and the Echo found it with no problem. Note - the Echo and the Philips hub are 35 to 40 feet from each other and there wasn't a problem with the signal. After the Echo added the devices I was able to control the bulbs with voice commands, \"Alexa turn Family Room on\" for example.\n\nA feature I had to research a bit was how to control the lights if I was away from my home, i.e., not on my home WiFi. The documentation that came with the kit wasn't much help but, after a few Google searches and reading the reviews here, I figured out that I needed to go to the my.meethue.com website, register and then the app would link to the website and allow me to control the lights. This is probably my favorite feature because I can now light up the house when I'm not home. I have two dogs so if I'm running late and it's getting dark out I can turn the lights on so they aren't home in the dark. It's also nice not coming home to a dark house. Oh, and it may keep criminals away.\n\nIn addition to the fairly basic functionality found in the Hue app you can install third party apps that provide a wide range of capabilities. The only one I've played with so far is a If This Then That app which is working fine.\n\nI plan on expanding this system over time. Someday I plan to ask it to do something and I'll be greeted with, \"I'm sorry Joe, I'm afraid I can't do that\". Dream fulfilled."}
{"Author": "\u262e S.Trasny", "Date": "on January 19, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Brilliant, Convenient Lightning System Installs Easily", "Text": "The review below got a bit out of hand. I couldn't stop running off at the mouth (keyboard?) about \u201cPhillips hue Personal Wireless Lighting.\u201d My Reader's Digest version is: I LOVE this brilliant, easy to install and program, connected home device / lighting system and intend to expand it to the fullest degree possible because doing so will save money over time and give our home ambiance, comfort and convenience options that were never before possible.\n\nTwo wireless light bulbs and a \u201cbridge\u201d were included in our Phillips hue White Starter Kit. Set up was amazingly easy. First step was choosing two living room lamps and installing and powering on the bulbs. Then the included power supply cord and cat5 cable were plugged into to the bridge; then the other ends to the wireless router and the electrical socket. Next, on the Alexa app, under Settings, the Connected Home option was accessed and the Discover Devices option was selected. Within a minute, Alexa at first said that no devices were found, but gave instructions to push the button on the hue bridge and try again. The second time, Alexa announced that two devices were found and they displayed on the Alexa Connected Home screen. It was then possible to give Alexa voice commands to turn each on and off. Using the Groups option, the two lamps were identified as Living Room Lights. That made it possible to turn either lamp on and off individually, or both at the same time. From there, it at first looked like it would be more complicated to set up a schedule to turn either or both lamps on and off. If read correctly, it looked like we would need to connect another app called IFTTT in order to communicate schedule specifics to Alexa. The hue app that the hue pamphlet referenced wasn't installed because I mistakenly believed it was for IOS only. At my husband\u2019s suggestion, I checked and found it available through Google Play for Android. Once installed and updated, we created an online account. At home, the app\u2019s proved to work perfectly to control and schedule the lamps to power on and off. Away from home, the app is supposed to recognize that we aren't on our home network, and signs us into our online account to control connected devices via the internet. We'll primarily use Alexa to control the lights, but the app is handier (for now) for setting up a schedule, until I decide to learn IFTTT functionality. We have a couple of other brands of connected home devices, including a wall switch and two smart plugs. I wish that their installation had been as easy as Phillips hue devices. Going forward, for connected home solutions, I'll look to Phillips first before considering other brands. The bridge works with up to 50 connected devices; I'm excited to expand the hue system, especially to include color changing ambiance lighting. The dollar total necessary to change out all bulbs is big, so I'll do it a bulb / fixture at a time. In the long run, it's a move that will save money because (according to PC Magazine) the bulbs rate 15,000 hours life span and use 80% less power; eventually they'll pay for themselves. Phillips hue lighting is moving to the top of every birthday, anniversary, etc wish list I'll make in the next couple of years. Highly recommended!"}
{"Author": "Doug Hibbard", "Date": "on January 18, 2016", "Stars": "4.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Alexa, Trigger Lights!", "Text": "I have another LED/controllable light from a different manufacturer, which I like for the full color spectrum. The drawbacks have been evident in the controls, and so I was happy to get a shot at the Philips Hue system.\n\nI love the difference having full connectivity makes--yes, it needs the Internet bridge, which is included in this starter kit, to work. And that may become problematic. And I do miss the full-color experience, but you can't fault a \"White\" bulb for not being purple.\n\nHere is the primary drawback: the cost of getting into this ecosystem and truly converting a whole room over to it is prohibitive. Yes, in time, it pays for itself in energy savings and bulb-use savings. But to just replace very bulb straight off? Ouch.\n\nStill, if you've can swing it, here's why it's worth it:\n\n1. Easy programming and setup. Seriously easy--push button, ready to go.\n\n2. Programmable with timer for wake up, programmable and effective with \"geofencing\" for location light turn on--lights come on when I get home.\n\n3. Connects to my Amazon Echo for voice control. Now, we don't have to find a phone or anything else to turn off the lights. And full hands when carrying items around still allow light control.\n\nI'm impressed. I'm not sure I'm \"Pay fifty bucks for more bulbs\" impressed, but it delivers on what it promises."}
{"Author": "Parker Knight", "Date": "on January 16, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Light control compatible Nest and Siri", "Text": "Plug the bulbs into lights like lamp and ceiling lights. Connect Bridge to a router data connection, then, download the app for smart phone. It works with Siri so you can use Siri's voice command \"Siri, turn light green.\" \"Siri, turn lamp off.\" You can add more light and also system works with Nest to control the dimming and lights on to mimic home being used by humans. All in all, gives you some bragging rights and use it to set the mood at home. It uses one data port on the router to function correctly and work with iPhone and iPhone has to connect to the same router or network."}
{"Author": "Traci \ud83d\udd75\ud83c\udffb\u200d\u2640\ufe0f\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc67\ud83d\udc5c", "Date": "on January 16, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "A Great Solution to a Common Pgje", "Text": "What a lifesaver! I can't ell you how many times I've stayed out late (unplanned) and come home to a very dark home. Dangerous and not safe at all.\n\nThis product allows you to remedy that. If you come home late, you merely turn your light(s) on in order to see who (hopefully) isn't there. It's also a great deterrent if you feel concerned that someone is \"borrowing\" you stuff without your permission. Burglars don't like light and this item is the last thing they want do come across.\n\nSetting safety aside, it's merely practical. And it also creates ease of use for people who have a hard time getting up and down to dim the lights.\nSo far this work splendidl and I highly suggest it."}
{"Author": "Susan", "Date": "on January 15, 2016", "Stars": "2.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Cumbersome and complicated to use with Echo", "Text": "(I bought the Phillips system at Best Buy,not over Amazon.) It does not work well with Alexa Echo. Cumbersome and complicated. If I can't plug something in, push a few buttons and have it work, I don't want it. After 1.5 hours of work, I could only get it to 'discover' one of 3 light bulbs. And nowhere on the internet could I find this 'app' you are supposed to download. For set-up, your android (or PC) and Alexa must be located right at your router (which is down 2 flights of stairs in my house). Then if you're testing it, you have to run up and see if it's working. Which I would have put up with, but still couldn't get Echo to recognize more than one bulb. Also, the spotlight bulb is so small that if put into a recessed socket, you can see all the insides of the socket. The system will only control bulbs. If you want to control an appliance that has more than one bulb, you need many bulbs, Get a Wemo, is what I say."}
{"Author": "Bob Feeser", "Date": "on January 15, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "This works great. It couldn't be easier.", "Text": "This works great. It couldn't be easier. All you do is take the hub out of the box and plug in the A/C adapter and then the included Ethernet cable into your router. Then you download the app into your device; in this case that means my Amazon Fire HDX tablet. It also works great with iOS iPad's iPhone's etc. There is an app in the Google Play Store as well for Android.\n\nThen you open the app and it tells you to press the button on the hub, and then it automatically connects. Then on the next screen you have the lights that come with the kit. Turning them on via the switch on the light, and leaving it on makes it active in your Phillips Hue App. So it shows up in the device window. Then you can slide the bar across to fade or brighten the lamp as well as turn on/off.\n\nNow it gets interesting because you can use it with the Amazon Alexa to be able to control devices, lights in this example with just a voice command. So you actually go through the same pairing procedure with Alexa by telling her to discover devices. She then says, \"Push the button on the Hue hub\" and you do, and then let it go, and within 5 or 10 seconds she acknowledges that you are now connected.\n\nYou can then say to her, \"Alexa turn on Phillips Hue Bulb 1\" and she will. You can also tall her to make it softer, or brighter and she incrementally does so in small steps. Of course you can tell her to turn it on or off. However I renamed the bulbs in the Phillips Hue app in the Fire HDX and when I told Alexa to do the following with the renamed light of, \"Alexa turn off my bedroom light\" she said no such device found. So I had to re-pair with Alexa. That is super easy, just tell her to find devices, and she say press the button the Hue hub, and you only need to do so for a second, and then she now re-pairs, and uploads the new device names. So then I said, \"Alexa turn on my bedroom light\" and presto she did. I know this is going to make me sound like a dork but my favorite thing has become to get ready for bed, tuck myself under the covers, and say, \"Alexa turn off the bedroom light\", and her sweet caring affectionate voice says, \"Okay\". It's the last thing I hear before going to sleep at night. Sorry but I love it when a female voice says that. :-) I'm hooked.\n\nThis is just the beginning for me with automating my home. I'm looking forward to advancing to a comprehensive smart home. I like that I can download the Phillips Hue app to work in everything including my Android based phone, to my Amazon tablet, to my Apple iPad air. I kind of went crazy buying tablets mostly because I grew tired of being locked out of Android for example when I had my Windows based phone. The Amazon tablets are incredible for clarity, and entertainment purposes, as well as a myriad of different uses.\nSo I don't know about how this has worked for others, but all I know is it worked perfect for me right out of the box, no hassles, hiccups, or burps.\n\nOne last thought is that I have a projector screen that is used ideally in a totally black room. So unfortunately when I am done watching Amazon Prime movies for example, and I am remodeling my house, I have to get up while the projector is still on, climb over stacked rugs and more, turn a light on, and then climb back to the viewing chair, and then turn the projector off, finally leaving the room turning the light back off. So now with the tablet I just turn the light on in the chair, shut the projector down, and then leave the room.\n\nYou can also say, \"Alexa turn on my bedroom light in one minute\" and Alexa responds, \"Turning on bedroom light in one minute starting now.\" She started lighting up with the colors swirling and a pleasant tone so I said, \"Alexa what are you doing?\" and she replied, \"I am answering questions and learning more.\" So I guess she was updating. Okay maybe this review is starting to drift a little more into the Alexa realm, but the exciting thing is she becomes the main helper in complete home automation, and works beautifully with this Phillips Hue Lighting kit. No problems at all so far so I highly recommend it.\n\nUpdate: Read my comment/reply below that shares with you how cool it is to use Alexa with Ooma to be your secretary, handling your phone chores."}
{"Author": "R. Morgan", "Date": "on January 14, 2016", "Stars": "4.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Feels like living in the future", "Text": "The hub is expensive, but it's nice to have the lights turn on to wake me up and dim before bed and turn off when it's time to go to sleep. It's also really nice to be able to control them from my tablet without walking over to the light switch."}
{"Author": "Hong Xiao", "Date": "on January 12, 2016", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Bad news started right away", "Text": "Very excited with the idea to control lights with smartphone and voice command via Amazon Echo. Got this start kit. Bad news started right away, Hue app crashes on my Samsung phone, not all the time, but quite often, and never know when it will crash next time. Went back to Best Buy, WITHIN 14 days of purchase, told that this is not returnable after it is opened. Called Philips customer service, the support person is even worse, claiming the crash of app is not Philips issue and they can not do anything other than suggesting to use my 9.7 inches iPad. The main reason for me to get this sucker is to be able to control the lights while I am away and I don't always bring the large iPad with me. Explained this to Philips support person, and he even accused me for willing to return because I simply don't like it. REALLY Philips? this is how you treat your customer? Now I have a product sitting there that I cannot really use the way it is designed for. So, be very careful before you get this product."}
{"Author": "Sleep of Reason", "Date": "on January 11, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Very easy to set up and immediately begin using.", "Text": "Very easy to set up and immediately begin using."}
{"Author": "Juice Box", "Date": "on January 9, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "A lot of misinformation in the reviews, read this", "Text": "This WILL WORK WITH MOST SMARTBULBS! Phillips cut off functionality with 3 party bulbs momentarily but pulled a quick 180 when the masses showed up at their doorstep with torches and pitchforks. The white hue bulbs are only $15.00 now so there is really no cost savings anymore anyways, also the hue bulbs are superior in my opinion.\nThe second generation bulbs CAN BE CONTROLLED FROM ANYWHERE IN THE WORLD! You do not need to be connected to your home network, any internet connection will do you just need to log into/create a my hue account through your app when you're setting things up. Additionally, if you are an Apple user and have an Appletv 3rd generation or higher on your home network then you can also use Siri to control the lights from anywhere without using the hue app. Without the Appletv you need to be home to use Siri to control the lights, but it works great, just use words she understands easily to name your scenes.\nNINJA BONUS: Leave an old iphone/ipad/ipod constantly plugged in somewhere convienient, enable \"hey siri\" in the settings and now all your lights are voice controlled.\nThe Hue is the best smart bulb system out there right now. Stay away from the colored bulbs, which you don't really need, and it's very affordable too. Just 5 years ago we spent $10k on a huge hard wired lighting control system for a large restaurant which was a bear to program. It's crazy to think we can do that same restaurant today with these bulbs 100 times better, 100 times easier for like $750 bucks!"}
{"Author": "PNWT", "Date": "on January 9, 2016", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Would be cool if it worked", "Text": "In conjunction with an Amazon Echo, I was constantly having to re-scan for devices. When using it with my phone, the app would randomly cease to function (and Siri never achieved better than about 60% success). Switched to the Wink hub, which works marginally better."}
{"Author": "Amazon Customer", "Date": "on January 5, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Five Stars", "Text": "Great Easy set up :D Works perfectly."}
{"Author": "Andrew Byerly", "Date": "on January 5, 2016", "Stars": "3.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Good but... Could be better", "Text": "Just purchased this system as a birthday gift (to myself). I'm really happy with the bridge and software but not the bulbs. The soft white is a horrible color. If you are somewhat picky about light color, avoid this bulb. I'd recommend the colored A19 Phillips Hue bulbs. Expensive but worth the additional expense."}
{"Author": "mr.rayburn", "Date": "on December 31, 2015", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "An easy on ramp to connected devices", "Text": "I've had the Hue Starter kit for a month now and I'm very happy with the Hue Stater Kit. After using it for 2 weeks I added an additional 6 bulbs to my set up. These lights provided a very simple solution to something in my house - for security I wanted timed lighting but didn't have many lamps which could be connected to inexpensive outlet timers. To pay an electrician to swap out a light switch for a timed light switch was fairly expensive when you include the hardware and the labor.\n\nWith this kit, I was able to set it up in 10 mins. I connected the hub to an Ethernet cable on my modem, downloaded the Hue app from the App Store, and swapped out my lightbulbs. Within ten minutes I was able to turn lights on or off from anywhere around the world. Pretty cool and easy. With the app you can set timers to turn lights on and off on any schedule. You can program a single lightbulb if you wanted to. You can even control the brightness of the lighting and dim your lights if you wanted. For my set up, being able to program the lights to turn on and off and control the brightness should save us some money in the long run on electrical bills. Overall I'm very happy with the Hue system and look forward to adding more bulbs to the set up over time."}
{"Author": "Swish!", "Date": "on December 30, 2015", "Stars": "3.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Pricey, for What it Does", "Text": "A lack of information on how to set up certain features of the system is very frustrating. Why don't they support their product? Needed to rely on customer blogs and other (non-Philips) sources for sometimes outdated information. That trick of \"It's so simple there are no directions!\" only works when it really is simple!\n\nAs with all things internet related, reliability is spotty. Occasionally, one light would disconnect. Sometimes all lights would only partially turn on.\n\nConvenient to have for setting up an \"Away from Home\" scenario, but can't see much convenience in having to get out one's cell phone to turn lights on/off."}
{"Author": "BuBu", "Date": "on December 28, 2015", "Stars": "4.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Learning curve", "Text": "Came as ordered-only 3 starts since it only works if you are within range of the base unit.\nNot like my thermostat that works anywhere there is internet!\n\nDoes work well with apps it has and then there are other apps besides this one.\nThe color bulbs are pretty expensive at $25.00 Plus\n\nNot for the person that wants to hook up a whole house unless they spend lots of $ on Colored bulbs!\nWhite bulbs are only $14-$16 which is affordable but not as good as the color bulbs.\n\nDifficult to turn off/on if you are not using the app. Let's say, one can turn a lamp on/off the old way. The problem is left turned off will disrupt turning it on/off through the app. Therefore, I'm using an app to schedule lights.\n\nUpdate: I recently broke my hip. Since then I am most grateful to Phillips, I'm adding a star. Nevertheless, I still believe the concept needs work and lamps are too expensive."}
{"Author": "pompon8686", "Date": "on December 28, 2015", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "I like Philips Hue because it allows me to remotely turn ...", "Text": "I like Philips Hue because it allows me to remotely turn off the lights. It made life easier for my son to control his lights when he had reduced mobility after a surgery."}
{"Author": "Paul Basquez", "Date": "on December 27, 2015", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Works Flawlessly With Echo", "Text": "Works with Echo. Was very easy to set up and use. This starter kit included two bulbs, but we quickly realized we wanted more. Searching Amazon for additional WHITE bulbs that were compatible with the HUE Bridge was confusing and ultimately pointless (and I've never felt like that - they usually have everything).\n\nBut I found the correct bulbs at Bestbuy for $15 each. I went and picked up 7 more the day after Christmas. In case you are struggling to find the white wireless bulbs for the HUE Bride, search for Model: 455295 / SKU: 4374300\n\nIf you are using with Echo, make sure to create \"Groups\" and name the groups something simple, like \"Living Room\". Echo had a very hard time understanding \"Alexa, turn Hue Lights On\", but she understands \"Alexa, turn the Living Room on\" every time. You can even create sub groups. For example - I have \"Living Room\", Dinning Room\", \"The Lights\" (Which is both living and dinning room) and even small groups like \"Lamps\" (which are just 2 of my living room lights).\n\nEasy and it works."}
{"Author": "Dan Carrera", "Date": "on December 27, 2015", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Great products works well with Echo / Siri", "Text": "Works fine with Echo and Alexa iterated lights color lights, etc for home automation. I even have it connected to SIRI on my iPhone to turn on/off lights or to dim them The Install was a breeze."}
{"Author": "Kliverance", "Date": "on December 26, 2015", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Smarthome? Order one", "Text": "Love the hue system, paired with alexa its a techies dream"}
{"Author": "Ryan P. Phinney", "Date": "on December 21, 2015", "Stars": "2.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "BUYERS BEWARE!!! NEW SOFTWARE UPDATE REMOVES THIRD PARTY FUNCTIONALITY!!!", "Text": "I purchased this after reading reviews of the capacity to use GE Link bulbs, since the Philips Hue bulbs are so expensive. Unfortunately, it seems Philips Hue has put out a software update which results in the Hue Hub refusing to recognize any bulb BUT a Philips Hue bulb. It is obvious that the original software would work (when searching, other bulbs blink as they are accessed) but that a specific exclusion was built into the software. I realize that they feel a proprietary system will be more profitable, as the greater the investment, the less likely one will change systems, thus the greater one's investment becomes as one expands their automated system.\n\nBuyers should be aware of the potentially expensive trap they may be entering, and the reviews originally posted for the Philips Hue Hub are misleading with the current update on software.The system does function as advertised, provided one recognizes that older reviews are no longer valid with the new changes.\n\nSo long as you always buy Philips Hue devices, it should function well, albeit quite expensively..."}
{"Author": "Old geek", "Date": "on December 20, 2015", "Stars": "3.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Works well, but extra bulbs may be VERY pricey.", "Text": "The \"reasonably priced\" bulbs are now not available, so you must pay a ridiculous price for light bulbs. Also, the latest update prevents you from using third party builds. Lighting device companies are now capitalizing on Echos popularity and gouging people. However, the system is easy to set up (you need an app or pc). I use just lights and they work well with the Amazon Echo. I did find a source of cheap Philips bulbs and got a few more. You get two bulbs with this package, if you plan to use more....look for cheaper ones on the internet and get them before they boost the price. They are dimmable LED lamps and are nice. I took two starts off for price of extra bulbs. Otherwise, I would give it five stars."}
{"Author": "Natasha", "Date": "on December 19, 2015", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "I love this product", "Text": "I love this product! It works perfectly, was fairly easy to set up and my echo works with it. I purchased a few Wemo's but it turns out I cant use them because my house is over 100 years old and the hot wire is in the light fixture rather than in the switch. The Philips Hue is the perfect solution for my issue. I'm using three bulbs right now and cant wait to add more around the house."}
{"Author": "CJ", "Date": "on December 19, 2015", "Stars": "3.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Works well for me. Only problem is Philips' threat ...", "Text": "Works well for me. Only problem is Philips' threat to make the hub proprietary and inoperable with other devices or lights."}
{"Author": "Mark D.", "Date": "on December 16, 2015", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Great product ruined by intentional breaking of customer trust/loyalty.", "Text": "Well... that was short-lived! I've been an avid supporter of Hue with my Echo, but as others have rightly pointed out, Philips really screwed up here when they rolled out an update around Dec 10, 2015 which intentionally blocked third-party bulbs. I myself didn't realize that was the issue and decided it was now time to upgrade to the new hub. However, same thing. No support for all the non-Hue bulbs I had been happily using. (I used Hue for color bulbs and GE Link for white bulbs since they were only $15 each.) So yeah, my system was basically dead thanks to their firmware upgrade.\n\nFortunately I convinced a rep at the local Home Depot which had the old hub on display to swap it with mine since it obviously didn't have the new firmware, and thanks to them, I got my lighting working again. Had to start from scratch, but at least I wasn't in the dark.\n\nBut it also meant now I could not use their own Dimmer kit which required the firmware upgrade!\n\nThankfully Philips has since reversed their decision (google philips-hue-reverses-decision-to-block-third-party-light-bulbs) but I'm still giving this a one-star review because this change was intentional and they did not warn existing customers with existing, perfectly working installs that this would break their systems. They need to know they can't do this kind of thing. It's a shame because as for the product itself, it's pretty great. (Ok, so the colors in the Hue aren't that great and the LIFX 1000 bulb kicks it's butt on colors, brightness and convenience with WiFi) but the Hue was damn simple to set up and worked with Amazon's Echo like a boss. Now they have a black eye, have tarnished their reputation and are forced to retreat. But posting that notice or not, they still haven't released the upgraded firmware so even with that mea culpa, it's still one star for now."}
{"Author": "Amazon Customer", "Date": "on December 16, 2015", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Great.", "Text": "Phillips released an update that broke it. Great."}
{"Author": "Richard Brennan", "Date": "on December 16, 2015", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Philips Hue reverses course, will continue to work with third-party bulbs", "Text": "Philips Hue announced today that it will roll back the system software update that blocked customers from pairing third-party smart bulbs with their Hue Bridges. From their press release:\n\n\"We recently upgraded the software for Philips Hue to ensure the best seamless connected lighting experience for our customers. This change was made in good faith. However, we under estimated the impact this would have on a small number of customers who use lights from other brands which could not be controlled by the Philips Hue software. In view of the sentiment expressed by our customers, we have decided to reverse the software upgrade so that lights from other brands continue to work as they did before with the Philips Hue system.\n\nWe are working on the reversal of the upgrade and will shortly confirm when this will be available.\""}
{"Author": "Amazon Customer", "Date": "on December 16, 2015", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "One Star", "Text": "Very disapointed after just purchasing and now discovering that third part support is blocked with the latest firmware."}
{"Author": "Schark03", "Date": "on December 15, 2015", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Phillips bulbs are great! Can I control my PlayStation with my xbox ...", "Text": "Phillips bulbs are great! Can I control my PlayStation with my xbox app? No. The update makes functionality with Siri possible and makes hue bulbs more fluid. If I wanted to buy the cheapest smart jobs and have them work with a hue app, it would sacrifice the quality of Phillips. These are easy to install and look like normal bulbs."}
{"Author": "KA", "Date": "on December 15, 2015", "Stars": "4.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Philips' membership in the Zigbee Alliance is sort of like Iran's on the Human Rights Council.", "Text": "Actively and willfully blocked other Zigbee Light Link protocol products after an \"update\" to the firmware. Blocked them not because they did not work with the Hue bridge, but precisely because they did. All done without informing Hue users that the update would do this.\n\nPhilips' membership in the Zigbee Alliance is sort of like Iran's on the Human Rights Council.\n\n***Update***\nAfter all the uproar from its user community, Philips offered a sort of non-apology apology and unblocked other ZLL lights. I haven't had any problems with it since."}
{"Author": "Amazon Customer", "Date": "on December 15, 2015", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Incompatible with non-Hue bulbs", "Text": "I was ready to buy this when Philips decided to make it incompatible with bulbs from other manufacturers. I don't want to be locked into buying bulbs from Philips (since they don't even make some of the bayonet-format bulbs I need), so I'm passing on the Hue set."}
{"Author": "RF", "Date": "on December 15, 2015", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Philips just ruined this product with new firmware", "Text": "Philips just ruined this product with new firmware. Greed does not make a good product."}
{"Author": "Miles", "Date": "on December 15, 2015", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Seek a different solution unless you're prepared to commit to only using the very expensive Philips bulbs for all solutions inst", "Text": "Philips sent out a firmware update that removes functionality from Hue, blocking legitimate, ZigBee-certified bulbs that are not part of their \"Friends of Hue\" program. Seek a different solution unless you're prepared to commit to only using the very expensive Philips bulbs for all solutions instead of cheaper 3rd-party ones that work as well or better."}
{"Author": "Robert B. Hamilton", "Date": "on December 15, 2015", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Policy reversed! Philips is #1 again. Thanks!!", "Text": "Update Dec 18 2015: (Original review below)\n\nI had reviewed this product with 1 star because, in typical corporate greed mode, Philips had decided to lock out competing light bulbs from the Philips Hue hub. I was super annoyed with this decision. I called Philips and wrote a 1 star review. I suppose a lot of people must have felt the same way. Today I see that Philips has decided to reverse it's policy. They are once again playing nice with other light bulbs! I assume they asked the corporate executive in charge of the previous lock-out policy to commit ritual suicide - and rightly so. But now all is well in the world and I love my Hue again! Thanks Philips. I should mention that the Philips Hue Hub works very well with the Amazon Echo (well for on and off - not for colors - but good enough). Very cool to come into your house and say \"Alexa - Turn on the Kitchen Lights\". You need this thing!\n\n======================================\n\nOriginal review:\n\nCareful! The new update locks out superior GE Link and Cree bulbs. If you have the older firmware do NOT update. If you have purchased more recently and have the update installed - if you can still return this product make sure to do it right away. How many Philips Executives does it take to screw in a light bulb? None - at Philips the light bulbs screw YOU!"}
{"Author": "John D", "Date": "on December 15, 2015", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Shame on you Phillips!", "Text": "Recently pushed firmware update to take away compatibility with other bulbs. Shame on you Phillips. Lifx here I come!"}
{"Author": "Me", "Date": "on December 14, 2015", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Latest firmware update locks out other bulbs even though Philips ...", "Text": "Latest firmware update locks out other bulbs even though Philips is in the Connected Lighting Alliance member they no longer follow the\nZigbee Light Link products protocol So no more interoperability with other brands"}
{"Author": "Amazon Customer", "Date": "on December 14, 2015", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Philips? Do not buy!!", "Text": "BAD! Philips changed policy for customers! So now i have a expensive useless product!!"}
{"Author": "William L. Crow", "Date": "on December 13, 2015", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Screwed by Philips!", "Text": "I too have been screwed by Philips. I had my philips hue 2 less than a month an now Philips has rendered it useless with a software \"Upgrade\" and my 3rd party bulbs are no longer supported.\nI will never again buy another Philips product, Just ordered a Smart Things hub and throwing the Philips away. This is what I should have done to start with. Live and Learn, don't make the same mistake."}
{"Author": "Matt W.", "Date": "on December 12, 2015", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Don't lock yourself in", "Text": "Do not purchase. Philips has retroactively \"upgraded\" existing customer's hubs so they will no longer work with third-party bulbs. They have actively removed functionality from the devices that people own."}
{"Author": "Sam M.", "Date": "on December 11, 2015", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Be prepared for philips to change policies and hardware to no longer work", "Text": "Update: Philips announced that they will be reversing their decision. It shows that they do listen to their users and value or opinions. I've changed my review back to how I originally felt, which is this is a great setup. I love that the bulbs dim on command and setup is pretty straight forward. I look forward to continuing my relationship with Hue.\n\nOriginal:\nPhilips recently changed their Hue API making it incompatible with bulbs made from other manufacturers. What grinds my gears is that it makes all existing users now have incompatible equipment with no notice or anything. It's one thing to have a closed ecosystem from the start, its another to pull the rug out from underneath your current and once loyal users. I'm dumping hue."}
{"Author": "John D.", "Date": "on December 11, 2015", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Shame on Philips", "Text": "Avoid... Philips blocking added of 3rd party bulbs without notice! Now you can only use Philips branded bulbs."}
{"Author": "Paul", "Date": "on December 9, 2015", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Elegant and simple controls", "Text": "Works very well and intuitive to use."}
{"Author": "JB", "Date": "on December 9, 2015", "Stars": "4.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "I thought it was asking for the serial number to add new devices like the Hue bulbs", "Text": "I had the previous generation bridge which stopped working thus the new purchase. It was a bit confusing with the setup especially when it asks for a code to scan. The code is on the box. I thought it was asking for the serial number to add new devices like the Hue bulbs. After I figured it out, it was nice that the app allowed you to transfer your bulbs from the old bridge to the new bridge. You need to follow the directions pretty closely and carefully but it worked really nice. The hue lux bulbs are great and bright. All in all pretty decent. A bit pricey for what you're getting which is why the 4 stars rather than 5."}
{"Author": "Mobius", "Date": "on December 8, 2015", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "A very well-designed system - Highly Recommend!", "Text": "I've had this a month (picked up at Best Buy) and thought this warrants a POSITIVE review after having a terrible experience with Belkin's WeMo light switches. First off, a comparison. I used Belkin's WeMo light switches for 2 years before getting the Philips Hue. The WeMo products are an abomination and I would avoid at all cost. When I first got the WeMo, their Android app was garbage - it was able to communicate with the light switches maybe 50% of the time. TWO years later, I still can't get the remote-access feature to work on the WeMo. With the Philips HUE, I was astonished because the remote feature just WORKS (even my little sister who is terrible with tech would've figured it out) - recall I had the WeMo for 2 years and have never been able to get that to work. With the HUE, if it gets dark earlier than usual because there's a bad storm, I'm able to remotely turn on the lights for my dog while I'm still at work so he doesn't sit in the dark. Another advantage of the HUE system is that it doesn't kill your Wi-Fi router when you add additional lights because with the HUE, only the HUE-Bridge talks to the router. So if you grow your system to 30 Hue bulbs for instance, you still only have the 1 Hue-Bridge talking to the router as the Bridge does all of the leg work with the bulbs. With the WeMo \"system\", every single switch is talking to the router - imagine 30 WeMo switches linked to your router; on top of your PC, smartphone, Chromecast, etc. If you have to change your router's Wi-Fi password, set aside 8 hours to change all of the passwords in each of the 30 WeMo switches. When I think of it, maybe that's why my router kept on crashing when I had the WeMo switches - I'd be watching Netflix and my expensive $160 Linksys router would just crash....maybe because it couldn't handle all of the devices communicating with it. Another PLUS with the HUE is you can adjust the brightness of the bulbs to control the tone/mood of your environment. With the WeMo, your light is simply on or off. Currently, I only have white bulbs hooked to the Hue system. I seriously can't wait to try out the colored bulbs to further adjust the tones/mood of my rooms. The $80 price may seem steep for the initial start-kit, but the additional white bulbs (that lasts ~25000 hours each) is inexpensive at $15 a piece. If you factor in that this system could deter would-be break-in thieves (because there's a random on/off function in the app), then that $80 price tag will pay off for itself 100x over. I'm thinking of getting this for my mom as a Christmas present - I can see her really enjoying this system because she is older and hates having to get up to turn on/off the lights throughout the house."}
{"Author": "My Public Name", "Date": "on December 8, 2015", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Works well with Echo after initial issues", "Text": "Works well with Echo, although had to redo my wifi settings (without actually changing them) to get it to recognize the Hue bulbs. At least that's what seemed to make it see the bulbs. Prior to finding that tip on Google (!), Alexa kept apologizing that she couldn't find any connected home devices.\n\nWorks with IFTTT if you create a My Hue account. Can also control the lights through a Web browser from work or the app on the road. No idea how secure it is, but it is just lights.\n\nWas easy to set up. The bulbs come pre-paired to the bridge. Responsive. Hasn't come unglued yet. Figure at some point something will get unpaired, refuse to work without disconnecting and re-pairing, etc. That's the nature of these things. Have heard the light strips aren't recognized by Alexa at this time.\n\nNo buzzing from the bulb with the non-dimming lamps used.\n\nAdded color bulbs easily as well. Added the dimmer switch a little less easily.\n\nNot recommended for whole house automation or primary lighting. Useful for lamps, accent lighting, etc. Limited usefulness without the Echo and/or dimmer remotes.\n\nCould do most of this (minus the colors) since the 70's using X10, which gives you the option of thousands of different remotes, many under $10, where this works with one very limited $25 remote at this time. An IR -> X10 bridge runs about $30.\n\nBonus for developers: there's an open HTTP API."}
{"Author": "Yvette", "Date": "on December 8, 2015", "Stars": "4.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Phillips Hue White", "Text": "Works great once you figure out how to get it connected. I wish the instructions were a little more accessible. Basically a pamphlet telling you to go the website. But other than that I'm really enjoying the control. I paired it with my Amazon Echo and it works flawlessly."}
{"Author": "G O'Connor", "Date": "on December 1, 2015", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "No more kids leaving the lights on and leaving the house for school...", "Text": "Works well as advertised. Really just wanted the Hue Bridge and felt this would be a way to try out some of the bulbs too. I needed this for the Phillips Hue LED color strip. Using it with my Wink Hub. So far so good. I like I can turn lights off from work after the family is gone to school etc (without turning off the lights)... Next I'm trying to program the lights just to go on and off when we need them the most!!!"}
{"Author": "Sam", "Date": "on November 30, 2015", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Absolutely love this kit", "Text": "Outstanding. Absolutely love this kit. Works very well with the Echo too."}
{"Author": "jillybean", "Date": "on November 30, 2015", "Stars": "4.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "... to set up than the previous model but I love my Philips Hue", "Text": "I found these bulbs a bit harder to set up than the previous model but I love my Philips Hue. I've talked a lot of friends into getting it because they love when they come into my house and I control everything by voice or by the app on my phone. definite wow factor."}
{"Author": "tim haywood", "Date": "on November 27, 2015", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Love how intelligent this thing is", "Text": "Love how intelligent this thing is. It turns the lights on when I arrive home and off when I leave. It also allows us to set timers for the kids to read at bedtime but not stay up so late. The lights start to fade down, then turn off. Great for our bookworm who will read past midnight then be grouchy the whole next day...lol"}
{"Author": "Francisco D.", "Date": "on November 22, 2015", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Great with Siri and Apple Watch! White Bulbs are Great Price for Entry Into Hue Ecosystem.", "Text": "So far so good. I am not sure why the white starter kit is not as popular as the multi-color one, but this serves my purposes perfectly for a great price."}
